{[%evp 0,92,32,31,66,58,85,58,59,69,69,75,63,63,64,59,56,54,59,44,41,22,31,35, 35,12,-2,-2,44,-5,2,-1,-9,-22,-22,-13,-30,-72,24,-12,-5,-19,-11,2,-4,-27,-12, -22,-29,-34,-12,-37,-33,-17,-17,-36,-59,-107,-99,-168,-100,-98,-91,-124,-107, -183,-136,-176,-161,-138,-159,-169,-174,-294,-291,-291,-291,-270,-215,-349, -267,-336,-350,-349,-351,-346,-305,-304,-238,-238,-238,-264,-240,-1532,-1573] I could not resist the temptation to start with the game giving birth to the whole system.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {"R. Spielmann now started to think; a few minutes later, I deflected my eyes from the chess board and saw that my good old comrade in arms Spielmann was completely at a loss: he stared at the knight at length, sometimes confidently and sometimes suspiciously and eventually chose the cautious Nc3 (refraining from the possible attack against the knight with e4-e5 and so on) . The next year, I used the move 2...Nf6 against Schlechter. In the tournament book, we can find the following comment by Tarrasch regarding this move: <This is bad because it is possible to chase away the knight, but Nimzowitsch chooses in the opening such personal paths, which cannot be recommended to the public, though.> The mockery can achieve a lot: it can orientate for instance the evolution of the young talents. One thing is not given to it, though: detaining the triumphant advance of the new mighty ideas for a prolonged time." (Nimzowitsch) Aron's general discourse and even the concrete reference to Tarrasch are quite correct, especially if we relate it with the Nimzo-Indian and Queen's Indian. However, his system in the Sicilian never obtained unanimous acceptance.} 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bc4 e6 (5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 e6 {is a more restrictive move order, with a possible transposition to the game.}) 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 {In our repertoire, we have a similar position, with the only difference being that the bishop is developed to d6.} O-O 9. Ne5 {Slightly premature.} (9. Bd3 Nc6 (9... Nd7 10. Re1 Qc7 11. Ne5 $5) 10. Re1 {offers White some chances for retaining long term pressure.}) 9... Qc7 10. Bd3 Nc6 $1 {The most active way of offering the knights' exchange, since it also attacks d4 and allows thinking of ...cxd4 followed by ...Nb4..} (10... Nd7 11. Re1) 11. Bf4 Bd6 {The bishop reached this square anyway.} 12. Re1 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nb4 14. Bg3 (14. Be4 {would have required certain inventiveness from Black, to maintain the approximate equality.} f5 15. Bd3 Nd5 16. Bd2 Nb4 17. Bf4 Nd5 18. Bg5 b5 $5 19. Bxb5 Nc3 20. Qd3 Nxb5 21. Qxb5 f4 $44) 14... Nxd3 15. Qxd3 b6 $11 16. c4 Ba6 17. Rac1 Rac8 18. Qb3 f6 (18... Rfd8 $15) 19. Qa4 $2 (19. c5 $1 fxe5 (19... Bxe5 20. dxe5 {= Nimzowitsch} Qc6 $1 $11) 20. Qxe6+ Rf7 $1 (20... Kh8 21. Qxd6 Qxd6 22. cxd6 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 exd4 24. d7 Rd8 25. Re1 $18) 21. Qxd6 (21. cxd6 Qxc1) 21... Qxd6 22. cxd6 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 exd4 $11) 19... fxe5 20. dxe5 Ba3 $5 (20... Bc5 21. Qxa6 h5 22. h3 g5 23. Kh1 (23. Re2 h4 24. Bh2 g4 $1 (24... Rxf2 25. Rxf2 Rf8 26. Kh1 Rxf2 27. Bg1 $11) 25. hxg4 Rxf2 26. Rxf2 Rf8 27. Rcf1 (27. Kh1 Rxf2 28. Bg1 Rd2 29. Bxc5 Qc6 $1 30. Rg1 Rxg2 $1 {[%cal Gh4h3]} 31. Qb5 Rxg1+ 32. Kxg1 Qxb5 33. cxb5 bxc5 34. a4 c4 35. a5 c3 36. b6 c2 $19) 27... Bxf2+ 28. Rxf2 Qc5) 23... h4 24. Bh2 Rcd8 $5 $15) 21. Qxa3 Bxc4 {Black's position is more pleasant, but White should be able to defend.} 22. Re4 Qd7 23. h3 Bd5 24. Re2 Qb7 25. f4 $6 (25. f3) 25... Qf7 26. Rec2 (26. Kh2 $15) 26... Rxc2 27. Rxc2 Qg6 28. Qc3 $2 Bxa2 $1 29. Bh4 Bd5 30. Be7 Re8 31. Bd6 Qe4 32. Qc7 h6 33. Rf2 Qe1+ 34. Rf1 Qe3+ 35. Rf2 a5 36. Be7 Qe1+ 37. Rf1 Qe3+ 38. Rf2 Kh8 39. Bd8 Qe1+ 40. Rf1 Qe3+ 41. Rf2 Qe1+ 42. Rf1 Qg3 43. Rf2 Rf8 44. Qxb6 Rxf4 45. Be7 a4 46. Kf1 Qxg2+ 0-1 

