{[%evp 0,24,19,38,72,47,78,48,74,65,37,35,45,28,46,-16,6,7,-16,10,1,1,-4,-24, -19,-46,-43]} 1. e4 c5 ({Here is how the French line mentioned below goes:}  1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. Nf3 $6 {This is rather modest.} ({ The main line goes} 5. f4 c5 6. Nf3) (5. Nce2 c5 6. c3 Nc6 7. f4 {is more ambitious than the line below, too.}) 5... c5 {transposing to a comment below.} ) 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 (3. e5 {is examined in Lines 16 to 35.}) 3... d5 (3... d6 4. d4 {transposes to normal Sicilian systems.}) ({The same goes for} 3... Nc6 4. d4 ({With this move order,} 4. Bb5 {is also hard to meet.}) 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4) 4. e5 (4. d3 {is relatively modest.} Nc6 5. g3 (5. Be2 d4 $1 {leads to some sort of reversed Old Indian, in which White will have wasted two tempi with his queen's knight.} 6. Nb1 e5 7. O-O Bd6 $15 {Christensen,T (2179) -Cmilyte,V (2512) DEN-chT 0809 2008 (1.3) 0-1}) 5... dxe4 ({The daring ones may also try} 5... d4 6. Ne2 e5 7. Bg2 {True, this looks like a reversed Mar del Plata attack, where White's extra tempo could count, but the essential aspect is that Black has not castled yet.} h6 8. O-O Be6 9. Ne1 g5 10. f4 gxf4 11. gxf4 Bd6 12. Nf3 {Mestrovic,Z (2420) -Herrmann Baden-Baden op 1987 (1) 1-0} Rg8 13. Kh1 Qe7 $15) 6. Nxe4 (6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bg4 8. Be2 O-O-O+ {Do Nascimento,D (1715) -De Lima Jr,F (1688) Potiguar-ch Interiorano 2018 (4.7) 0-1 } 9. Bd2 Nd4 $17) 6... Nxe4 7. dxe4 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Bg4 9. Be2 O-O-O+ 10. Nd2 Bxe2+ (10... h5 $5) (10... Bh3 $5) 11. Kxe2 Nd4+ 12. Kd1 e6 13. c3 Nf3 14. Ke2 {Zapnik,G (1656) -Zimmermann,J (1735) Mecklenburg VP LL2 Ost 1011 2010 (3.5) 0-1} Nxd2 15. Bxd2 Be7 $11) (4. Bb5+ {is the subject of Lines 3 and 4.}) (4. exd5 {is examined in Lines 5 to 7.}) 4... Nfd7 5. d4 (5. Nxd5 {allows Black to clear things up in the centre with} Nxe5 6. Bb5+ (6. Nxe5 Qxd5 7. Bb5+ { offers Black a choice. He can transpose to the main line by developing the knight to c6, or play the simpler} Nd7 8. Nxd7 Bxd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. O-O g6 $11) (6. Ne3 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 Nc6 8. Bc4 e6 $11 {does not face Black with problems, either.}) 6... Nbc6 7. Nxe5 Qxd5 8. Nxc6 (8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. Nf3 g5 $5 $15) 8... bxc6 9. Bf1 (9. Be2 Qxg2 10. Bf3 Qg6 $15) 9... Bf5 10. d3 h5 11. Be3 e5 12. h4 Be7 $15) (5. e6 {is a typical pawn sacrifice, aiming at slowing down Black's development, without confronting him with serious problems, though.} fxe6 6. d4 ({White should care about the centre.} 6. Ng5 {is a premature attack.} Nf6 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Qe2 Qd6 $15) 6... g6 7. dxc5 (7. h4 Bg7 8. h5 Nc6 9. dxc5 Nxc5 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 12. Bd3 Kd7 $5 {[%cal Gd3g6,Gd8g8] Intending to meet the capture on g6 with ...Qg8.} 13. Bb5 a6 $11 14. Nxd5 $5 { An interesting sacrifice.} exd5 15. Qxd5+ Kc7 16. Bxc6 Qd6 $1 {Black can parry the attack by simple means.} 17. Be3 Qxc6 18. Qxc5 Qxc5 19. Bxc5 Bxb2 20. Rd1 Be6 21. a3 Bc4 22. Nd2 Bc3 $11 23. Bb4 $2 Rh8 $1 24. Bxc3 Rh1+ 25. Nf1 Rxf1+ 26. Kd2 Rxf2+ $19 {Guilbert,H (2140) -Komarov,D (2540) Clichy2 2001 (6) 0-1}) 7... Bg7 8. Be3 Nc6 9. h4 Qa5 {Not the only good move.} (9... Nf6 $5 10. Bb5 Ng4 $13) (9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. Qd2 e5 $13) 10. Qd2 Nxc5 11. h5 (11. Bb5 Nd7 $5 12. h5 a6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. hxg6 hxg6 15. Rxh8+ Bxh8 16. Bd4 e5 17. Qh6 Bf6 18. Qxg6+ Kd8 19. Qg8+ Kc7 20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Bxe5+ Nxe5 22. Qg3 d4 23. b4 Qxb4 24. Qxe5+ Kd8 25. O-O-O Qa3+ 26. Kb1 Qb4+ 27. Kc1 Qa3+ $11) 11... Bd7 $15 {Black has a strong centre and an extra pawn, is well developed, and his king is ready to escape on the queenside.} 12. Bb5 $6 Ne4 $1 13. Nxe4 Qxb5 14. Nc5 Qxb2 15. O-O Qc3 16. Qe2 Qc4 17. Qxc4 dxc4 18. Rad1 Bc8 19. Ng5 Bf6 20. hxg6 hxg6 $17 21. Rfe1 e5 22. f4 exf4 23. Bxf4 Bg4 24. Rd6 O-O {Rudd,J (2296) -Palliser,R (2402) BCF-chT 0405 (4NCL) 2004 (10.3) 0-1}) 5... cxd4 (5... e6 { transposes to a relatively modest white setup against the French mentioned above. While Black does not have any problems here, we can even avoid a perfect transposition.}) 6. Qxd4 {The most popular move.} (6. Nxd5 $2 {was played in a few games, but only one player noticed} Qa5+ $1 $19 {Ponkratz,A  (1347) -Al Jou Jou,J (1465) Oberpfalz-ch M3 2004 (5.6) 0-1 winning the knight.} ) (6. Ne2 $146 Qa5+ $5 (6... Nc6 {may transpose to 6.Nb5.}) 7. Bd2 Qb6 8. Nexd4 (8. Bf4 e6 9. Nexd4 Bc5 10. Rb1 f6 11. exf6 O-O 12. c3 Nxf6 13. Be2 Nc6 14. O-O Ne4 $11) 8... Nxe5 $13) (6. Nb5 {By playing ...e7-e6 now or on the next move in the line below, Black could transpose to the French.} Nc6 $5 7. e6 (7. Bf4 g5 $5 8. Bxg5 Bg7 9. Nd6+ Kf8 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Nxe5 12. Nxc8 Rxc8 13. Qd2 h6 14. Be3 Ng4 15. Bd4 Bxd4 16. Qxd4 Rg8 $11) 7... fxe6 8. Nbxd4 (8. Nfxd4 $2 { gives up the control over e5.} Nf6 9. c4 e5 $19 {Sedy,P (2248) -Mojzis,J (2236) CZE-chT1W 0607 2006 (11.4) 1/2-1/2}) 8... Qb6 (8... Nf6 9. Bf4 $14 {maintains the control in the centre.}) 9. Nxe6 Nf6 10. Nxf8 (10. Be3 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. Nxf8 Ne4 13. Be3 Qxb2) 10... Ne4 11. Qxd5 Qxf2+ 12. Kd1 Bg4 13. Ne6 Bxf3+ 14. gxf3 Qxf3+ 15. Ke1 Qf2+ 16. Kd1 $11) 6... e6 {There is no reason to delay this move anymore. Black has achieved a little bit of success with his move order. The queen has emerged on d4 as a blocking piece, something that she is not suited for. Due to that, the pawn on e5 is vulnerable.} 7. Bb5 {Trying to reduce Black's influence over the central dark squares.} (7. Bg5 {is best met with the intermediate move} Nc6 $1 8. Qh4 $5 $146 {The most consistent.} (8. Qa4 $2 {misplaces the queen.} Qc7 9. O-O-O a6 10. Kb1 Bb4 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qb3 Nc5 13. Bxc5 Bxc5 14. Bd3 Nxe5 $19 {De Castro,A (2360) -Filguth,R (2405) BRA-ch Canela 1987 (3) 0-1}) (8. Bxd8 {yields Black comfortable play.} Nxd4 9. Nxd4 Kxd8 10. f4 g5 11. g3 gxf4 12. gxf4 Bh6 13. Nce2 Ke7 14. Bh3 Nc5 15. O-O-O Ne4 16. Rhf1 Bd7 17. Kb1 Rhg8 18. Rf3 $6 Raf8 19. Ng3 f5 20. exf6+ Rxf6 $15 { Nagy,J (2260) -Kustar,S (2405) Szeged TT06 IM 1998 (9) 0-1}) 8... Qc7 9. O-O-O (9. Nb5 Qb8 10. O-O-O a6 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 Qxd6 $15) 9... a6 10. Qg3 Ndxe5 $5 ({The slow positional approach is also good.} 10... b5 11. Kb1 Nc5 12. Bd3 b4 13. Ne2 a5 $11) 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Be2 $1 {Only rapid development followed by a tactical blow in the centre can yield White compensation for the pawn.} Bd7 (12... Bd6 $2 13. Ne4 $1 dxe4 14. Rxd6 Qxd6 15. Rd1 Qb6 16. Rd8+ Qxd8 17. Bxd8 O-O 18. Qxe5 Rxd8 19. Qxe4 $16) 13. Rxd5 $1 (13. Kb1 Rc8 $15) (13. f4 Nc6 14. Rhe1 Bb4 15. Bh4 f6 16. Qxg7 O-O-O $17) 13... exd5 14. Nxd5 Qb8 15. Rd1 Bd6 16. Bf4 Be6 $1 (16... Kf8 {is likely to yield White permanent initiative for the piece.}) 17. Qxg7 Nd3+ $1 18. Kb1 $1 (18. Bxd3 Bxf4+ {Threatening ...Be5 or ... Qe5, with a win.} 19. Nxf4 Qxf4+ 20. Kb1 O-O-O $19) 18... Nxf4 19. Qxh8+ Bf8 20. Nf6+ Ke7 {White does not have more than a perpetual.} 21. Ng8+ Ke8 22. Nf6+ Ke7 23. Nxh7 Nxe2 24. Qf6+ Ke8 25. Qh8 Ke7 26. Qf6+ Ke8 27. Nxf8 Kxf8 28. Qh8+ Ke7 29. Qh4+ Kf8 $11) (7. Bd3 {is a solid, but not very threatening move.} Nc6 8. Qf4 Qc7 9. O-O (9. Nb5 Qb8 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. exd6 O-O 12. Qg3 f6 $13 13. Qh3 f5 $13 {[%cal Gb8d6] Planning ...Qxd6.} 14. Qg3 e5 $17) 9... Ndxe5 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Nb5 Qxf4 12. Bxf4 Kd8 13. Rad1 a6 14. Nd6 (14. Nc3 b5 $17 {Sindelar,F (1962) -Lyashenko,S (1922) CZE-EUR email 2015 [102] 0-1}) 14... Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Kd7 $5 (15... b5 $5 16. f4 g6 $13) 16. Bc5 Kc7 $13) (7. Bf4 {consolidates the central pawn but implies wasting a tempo with the queen on the next move.} Nc6 8. Qd2 Bb4 9. a3 Qa5 10. O-O-O (10. Be2 {Stanojevic,S (2110) -Hinteregger,A  (2140) AUT-chT2W 9798 1997 (8) 0-1} Nc5 11. O-O Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Qxc3 13. bxc3 b6 14. a4 Ba6 15. Bb5 Bxb5 16. axb5 Na5 17. Nd2 O-O $11) 10... Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Qxc3 12. bxc3 Nb6 (12... b6 $11) 13. h4 Bd7 14. h5 h6 15. Rh3 {Romero Barreto,J  (2266) -Caceres Vasquez,S (2094) American Continental 13th 2017 (5) 0-1} (15. Rh4 O-O 16. Rg4 Kh8 $11) 15... Ne7 16. Be3 Na4 $11) (7. Qg4 h5 $5 $146 (7... Nc6 8. Qg3 {transposes below.}) 8. Qg3 h4 9. Qg4 Nc6 10. Bb5 Qc7 11. Bf4 d4 12. Bxc6 dxc3 13. Bxd7+ Bxd7 14. b3 Bc6 $11) (7. Qf4 Nc6 8. Qg3 {is a consistent, but time-consuming attempt to consolidate.} f6 9. exf6 (9. Bb5 fxe5 10. Nxe5 { Tornay Gomez,J (2116) -Cano Gonzalez,J San Sebastian op 13th 2003 (2) 1-0} Ndxe5 11. Qxe5 Bd7 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {[%cal Gd8f6]} 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 Rg8 15. Bg5 Bg7 16. Qf4 Qb8 $11) 9... Nxf6 10. Bd3 Bb4 $1 11. Qxg7 Rg8 12. Qh6 d4 13. Bg5 $1 (13. a3 Bf8 $1 $19) 13... dxc3 14. O-O-O Rxg5 15. Nxg5 Bf8 16. Qh4 Qe7 $13) 7... a6 8. Bxd7+ Bxd7 9. O-O Nc6 10. Qg4 Qc7 11. Bf4 Ne7 {Given the absence of White's light-squared bishop, this is very logical.} (11... O-O-O {is interesting, but maybe a bit risky.} 12. Rfe1 (12. Ne2 h6 13. c4) 12... h6 13. a3 (13. h4) 13... g5 14. Bg3 Qb6 (14... Be7 {McGregor,R (1788) -Carlson,G  (1701) Southwest op U2000 65th 1999 (6) 1/2-1/2} 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. e6 $13) 15. Na4 Qb5 16. b3 Be7 17. c4 dxc4 18. Qxc4 Kb8 $17) 12. Rfe1 Rc8 $15 {Black has several moves on his agenda: ...h7-h5, ...Nf5, ...Qc4.} * 

