{[%evp 0,46,19,38,72,47,78,45,75,62,66,20,37,35,74,81,81,72,122,87,76,42,23,-2, 74,57,51,34,32,16,8,4,0,0,0,0,8,8,12,15,15,13,23,12,17,14,8,11,7]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bb5+ Bd7 5. e5 {This is the critical continuation. If Black does not agree to play a slightly worse position, play will become entertaining.} Bxb5 6. Nxb5 (6. exf6 Ba6 $1 $17) 6... Qd7 $1 {Black cannot afford to step back. His last move over defends e6.} (6... Nfd7 7. e6 fxe6 8. Ng5 Qb6 9. Qe2 e5 10. c4 d4 11. Qf3 $14 {Aagaard,J (2531) -Landa,K (2615) Politiken Cup 30th 2008 (5) 1-0}) (6... Ng8 7. e6 $1 $16) 7. Qe2 {The same goes for White, who needs to fight for the initiative.} (7. exf6 Qxb5 $11) (7. Nc3 Ng8 {transposes} 8. d4 e6 9. Ne2 Nc6 {transposes to Line 3.}) (7. a4 { keeps the knight in its advanced position, but does not contribute to the fight in the centre.} Ng8 8. O-O e6 9. d4 a6 10. Nc3 Nc6 {The insertion of the rook pawn moves has mainly weakened White's queenside.} 11. Ne2 cxd4 12. Nexd4 Nge7 13. c3 Ng6 14. Re1 {Asis Gargatagli,H (2519) -Le,T (2542) Titled Tuesday intern op 02nd May Early blitz 2023 (8) 0-1} Nxd4 15. Nxd4 (15. cxd4 Bb4 16. Re3 Rc8 {[%cal Gg6e7,Ge7f5,Ge7c6] possibly followed by the knight's transfer to either f5 or c6.}) 15... Bc5 16. g3 O-O 17. h4 Ne7 18. Kg2 h6 $11) 7... a6 $1 {The same principle as earlier} (7... Ng8 8. e6 $1 fxe6 9. Ne5 $18) 8. Nc3 ( {The spectacular} 8. Nd6+ {does not promise much.} exd6 9. exf6+ Qe6 10. fxg7 $6 (10. d4 Nc6 11. Be3 O-O-O $13) 10... Bxg7 11. Ng5 Qxe2+ 12. Kxe2 Nc6 13. d3 {Bocharov,I (2563) -Predke,A (2622) Wch Rapid St Petersburg 2018 (6) 1/2-1/2} Kd7 $17 {[%cal Gb7b5,Ga8e8,Gh8g8] followed by ...Rae8, ...Rhg8, ...b7-b5.}) (8. exf6 Qxb5 $11 9. Qe5 $6 gxf6 10. Qxd5 e6 11. Qe4 f5 12. Qe2 Rg8 13. g3 { Kramer,J (2371) -Bach,M (2227) Hamburg Engelbert Memorial-B 2019 (9) 1-0} Nc6 14. d3 O-O-O 15. a4 Qb6 $15) 8... Ng8 9. e6 {The only justification for White's previous play. Otherwise, the queen would have little to do on e2, apart from depriving the knight of this square.} (9. d4 e6 10. O-O Nc6 11. Rd1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 cxd4 13. Rxd4 Ne7 14. Bf4 {Holm,K (2451) -Torma,R (2435) Balatonlelle Benko Memorial GM 2020 (9) 1/2-1/2} Ng6 15. Bg3 h5 16. h3 Rc8 $17 {White's lack of coordination is obvious.}) 9... Qxe6 10. Qxe6 fxe6 11. Ng5 ( 11. O-O h6 12. Re1 Nd7 13. d4 (13. Rxe6 Kf7 14. Re2 e6 $11) 13... Ngf6 14. dxc5 Nxc5 15. Ne2 {Bruzon Batista,L (2623) -Le,T (2527) World op 50th 2022 (8) 0-1} g5 $5 {Gaining space and preparing to continue the development at the same time.} 16. Ned4 g4 17. b4 (17. Ne5 Nfe4 18. Nxg4 Bg7 19. Nf3 Rc8 20. Nge5 Nd7 $15 {Black is better developed and controls the centre.}) 17... Ncd7 18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 Nd7 20. Rxe6 Bg7 21. Bb2 Kf7 22. Rae1 Rhe8 23. Ba1 {[%cal Gd4f5]} h5 24. f3 Rac8 25. fxg4 hxg4 26. Nf5 Bxa1 27. Nh6+ Kg7 28. Rxa1 Rxc2 29. Nxg4 Rc6 $13) (11. Na4 $2 Nd7 12. Ng5 e5 13. Ne6 Rc8 $19) 11... d4 {Black cannot maintain control over the central light squares. In exchange for conceding the square on e4, he will get free development and considerable space advantage.} 12. Nce4 (12. Nxe6 Kf7 13. Nd8+ Ke8 14. Ne6 Kf7 $11 {Tsydypov,Z (2530) -Safarli, E (2671) Baku op 2018 (7) 1/2-1/2} 15. Ng5+ Kg6 16. Nce4 Nf6 17. d3 h6 18. Ne6 Nxe4 19. dxe4 Nd7 20. f4 Kf7 21. f5 g6 $13) 12... Nd7 13. Nxe6 Rc8 14. O-O (14. d3 Ngf6 $5 15. N6g5 $6 h6 $15) 14... Rc6 (14... Ngf6 $6 15. Re1 $1 Rc6 16. N4g5 $14) 15. N6g5 h6 16. Nf3 Ngf6 {It appears that White was not in time to connect his knights to maintain firm control over e4.} 17. Re1 Kf7 18. d3 g5 19. b3 (19. h3 Nxe4 20. Rxe4 Re6 21. Nd2 Bg7 22. a4 b6 23. f4 Rxe4 24. Nxe4 gxf4 25. Bxf4 e5 26. Bh2 Ke6 $11 {White has managed to install his remaining knight on e4, but his lack of space persists. As a consequence, his bishop is passive. Black can unblock e4 with ...Nf6 and prepare ...c5-c4.}) 19... Bg7 (19... g4 20. Nfd2 Nd5 21. a3 Bg7 22. f3 h5 $11) 20. Bb2 Nd5 (20... g4 $5) 21. h3 Rf8 22. a4 b6 23. Ba3 Kg6 $11 {Bodek,M (2395) -Naroditsky,D  (2610) US Masters op 2019 (2) 1/2-1/2 Black has a harmonious development and a space advantage all over the board. White's control over e4 only compensates for these aspects.} * 

