{[%evp 0,34,30,10,46,46,92,63,74,79,60,72,67,72,84,45,35,24,39,46,48,48,54,24, 24,10,26,33,33,28,45,-9,98,61,30,54,18]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 {Strictly speaking, this may look like a slight concession. White gives up his pawn control in the centre, yielding White some space advantage in that area. Things are not that one-sided, though. White has a small advance in development, having developed two knights and forcing Black to move for the second time with an already-developed knight. Under such circumstances, opening the centre and establishing piece and/or pawn contact may be profitable. Practice has shown that it is the most consistent continuation, especially in connection with 5.Bb5+.} Nxd5 5. d4 {Establishing a pawn contact at once is premature, since Black has not committed himself in any way yet.} ( 5. Nxd5 {is a real concession, yielding Black comfortable play.} Qxd5 6. d4 Nc6 (6... Bg4 $5) 7. dxc5 $5 (7. c3 cxd4 8. cxd4 $2 {is not an Alapin tabyia, since two knights are missing, ensuring good stability in the centre for the black queen.} Bf5 9. Be2 e6 $15) (7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 a6 $11 9. Be2 (9. c3 e5 10. Nb3 Qxd1+ 11. Rxd1 Be6 12. Be2 Be7 13. O-O O-O $11) 9... e5 10. Nxc6 (10. Bf3 e4 11. Be2 Bc5 $11) 10... Qxc6 11. O-O Be7 $11) 7... Qxd1+ (7... Qxc5 8. c3 {is likely to yield White some initiative after Be3.}) 8. Kxd1 e5 9. Be3 { White's secret (or maybe outspoken) idea is to retain the extra pawn. With his king exposed in the centre, the plan is not realistic, though.} Bg4 10. Be2 f5 11. h3 (11. g3 f4 12. gxf4 exf4 13. Bxf4 Bxc5 14. Be3 O-O-O+ 15. Nd2 Bxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nd4+ $11 17. Bxd4 Bxd4 18. c3 $2 Rhe8+ 19. Kf1 Bxc3 $1 $17) 11... O-O-O+ 12. Ke1 (12. Kc1 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 f4 14. Bd2 Bxc5 15. Rf1 Rd6 $11) 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nb4 14. Rc1 Be7 15. a3 Nd5 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. b4 Rhd8 18. g3 g5 19. f3 f4 20. Bf2 Bf6 $44) (5. Ne5 {was recommended by Nimzowitsch as interesting. However, Black can clear matters in the centre now. Interestingly, Nimzowitsch's ideologic enemy Tarrasch used this idea in the game below, without too much success, however.} Nxc3 6. bxc3 Qc7 {The knight's jump looks premature now.} 7. Bb5+ Nd7 8. Qe2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 O-O $1 ({The careless } 10... a6 {ran into} 11. Nxf7 $1 Bxh2+ 12. Kh1 O-O 13. Ng5 Nf6 14. Bc4 $14 { Rey Ardid,R-Tartakower,S Barcelona 1929 (2) 0-1}) 11. d4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nxe5 ( 12... b6 $11) 13. dxe5 Bb4 14. Bd2 ({Tarrasch probably discarded} 14. Rd1 { because of} Bc3 (14... Be7 $5 $11) 15. Rb1 a6 (15... Bxe5 16. Ba3 $14) 16. Bd3 (16. Ba4 b5 17. Bb3 Bxe5 18. Ba3 Re8 $17) 16... Bxe5 17. Ba3 Re8 18. Rb4 Bd7 19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Rh4 f5 $13) 14... Bxd2 15. Qxd2 Rd8 16. Bd3 b6 17. Qf4 Bb7 18. Qh4 g6 (18... h6 $15 19. Re3 Qc5 $17 {threatening ...Rd4.} 20. Rg3 $2 Qxe5 $19) 19. Re3 Qc6 20. Be4 Qc4 21. f3 $2 (21. Rh3 $1 Qxe4 22. Qxh7+ Kf8 23. Rf3 Rd7 24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Qf6+ {with a draw by perpetual.}) 21... Rac8 $19 {Tarrasch,S-Tartakower,S Berlin Tageblatt+ 1928 (3) 0-1}) (5. Bc4 {[%emt 0: 00:06] is examined in Line}) ({The critical} 5. Bb5+ {is examined in Lines 7 to 9.}) 5... Nxc3 $1 {The simplest.} (5... e6 {transposes to Lines 12 and 13.}) 6. bxc3 g6 $1 {This is the best answer. Black is heading for some sort of comfortable Gruenfeld structure. The difference is that White has a pawn on c2 instead of e4, which makes things easier for Black.} ({In the event of} 6... e6 {, White can play} 7. Bd3 $14 {, reaching a favourable version of Line 6, since the bishop is better placed on d3 than on c4.}) 7. Bc4 {The most popular continuation.} (7. Be2 {is a bit passive.} Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Qa5 10. Qd2 Nc6 11. Bh6 cxd4 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. Nxd4 Rd8 (13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4+ e5 15. Qe3 Bd7 {White must prove that he has compensation for his spoiled structure.}) 14. Qe3 Qe5 15. Qxe5+ (15. Nxc6 Qxe3 16. fxe3 bxc6 $15) 15... Nxe5 16. f4 Nc6 17. Nxc6 bxc6 18. Bf3 Ba6 19. Rfd1 Kf6 $11 {Aung,T (2268) -Jaskolka,T (2227) Titled Tuesday intern op 15th Aug Early blitz 2023 (1) 0-1 The same as in the lines above, Black's play is more pleasant, due to his better structure, but White can stay close to equality because of his slightly superior activity.}) ( 7. Bb5+ {aims at spoiling Black's coordination a bit. It is a typical idea in the Gruenfeld, too.} Nd7 $1 $146 {I find this move the best. After getting castled, Black will be able to direct the knight towards d5 or c4, making it look like a constructive developing move.} (7... Bd7 {is unanimously played, but I believe that it is not the best. It does not look likea genuine developing move.} 8. Rb1 $5 Bg7 9. O-O O-O {Solovjov,S (2457) -Arbakov,V (2445) Alushta Autumn 1st 2002 (14) 1/2-1/2} 10. d5 Bxc3 (10... Qb6 11. Bg5 Bxb5 12. c4 $14) 11. Bc4 Bc8 12. Qd3 $14) 8. O-O Bg7 9. a4 (9. Ba3 O-O $5 10. Bxd7 $6 Qxd7 11. Bxc5 b6 12. Ba3 Bb7 13. Re1 Rfe8 14. Qd3 Rac8 15. Rad1 e6 16. Ne5 Qa4 17. Bc1 Qxa2 $15) 9... O-O 10. Re1 Nb6 11. a5 Nd5 12. Ra3 Bf5 $11) 7... Bg7 8. O-O (8. Ne5 Bxe5 $5 (8... O-O $11 {[%cal Gb8d7] planning ...Nd7.} 9. Qf3 $6 e6 $15 {WHite has committed himself a bit too much and ...Nd7 will follow soon.}) 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Nc6 11. Bb5 (11. Bf4 Be6 12. Bb5 Bd5 13. f3 a6 14. Be2 O-O-O $15) 11... Bd7 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 $17 {Kulesza,M (2282) -Antoniewski,R (2509) POL-chT 1st League 2006 (7) 0-1}) (8. h4 {is a premature attack.} Nc6 9. Be3 Qa5 10. Qd2 Bg4 $15 11. Ng5 O-O 12. f3 Bd7 $17 13. h5 cxd4 $19 {Schmidt,W  (2305) -Urban,H Oberliga Nord O 9596 1995 0-1}) 8... O-O 9. Ba3 {Trying to induce Black to release the tension.} (9. Re1 {is aimed as a flexible move, waiting for Black to commit himself.} Nc6 (9... Bg4 $5 10. Ba3 Nd7 $11) 10. Ba3 (10. Bb2 Bg4 $15) 10... cxd4 (10... b6 $5) 11. cxd4 Bg4 12. c3 Qa5 13. Bb2 (13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. Rxe7 Qxc3 15. Rc1 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qa5 $11) 13... e5 (13... Rac8 14. Bb3 e6 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Qc7 17. Re2 Na5 18. d5 Nxb3 19. axb3 exd5 20. Qxd5 Rfe8 $11 {Van Zyl,M (2028) -Zarqoni,M Afroasian-chT4 email 2022 1/2-1/2}) 14. d5 Ne7 $1 {The knight is heading for the optimal blockading square on d6.} ( 14... Rad8 $2 {leaves the rook on f8 exposed.} 15. Qb3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 $16 { Ding,Y (2350) -Guo,Q (2351) CHN-ch (Women) 2012 (9) 1/2-1/2} Ne7 17. Ba3 { Now is when the rook's exposure tells.}) (14... Rfd8 $5 {is better, but I believe that it is more logical to leave the rooks' development for later.} 15. Qb3 Bxf3 16. gxf3 b5 $1 17. Qxb5 Rab8 18. a4 $5 Rxb5 19. axb5 Qb6 {[%cal} 20. bxc6 $1 $13 {Preventing bxc6. Ra6 Nd4 Rxb6 Nxf3+ Kh1 axb6 Black was a bit on the edge in this line, something he does not need.}) 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nf5 17. Bb3 Nd6 $11 {If necessary, Black can secure the knight's stability with ... b7-b6.} 18. Qg3 (18. c4 $6 e4 19. Qe2 Bxb2 20. Qxb2 f5 21. Qe5 Qc5 $15) 18... Rac8 (18... b5 $5 19. a4 {Otherwise, White would be worse.} Rfc8 20. Red1 bxa4 21. Bxa4 Qb6 22. Rab1 Qa6 23. Bc6 Rab8 $13) 19. Rad1 Rfd8 $11) (9. Be3 { is equally popular as the main line, but I find it simply wrong.} Nc6 10. h3 ( 10. Qd2 Bg4 11. Be2 Qa5 $15) 10... Na5 11. Be2 Be6 $15 12. Ng5 Bd5 $17) 9... b5 $5 {If possible, why not?} (9... cxd4 10. cxd4 Nc6 11. c3 Qa5 $11 {is not bad, either.}) 10. Bd3 (10. Bxb5 Qa5 $1 11. Bd3 Qxa3 12. Be4 Ba6 13. Bxa8 Bxf1 14. Qxf1 Qxc3 $17) 10... Na6 11. Re1 (11. Qe2 Qa5 12. Bb2 {Jung,H (1941) -Zick,D  (2097) Washington Class-ch Master 2011 (2) 0-1} Bb7 13. Ne5 (13. Bxb5 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nc7 15. Bc4 e6 $15) (13. Qxe7 Bxf3 14. gxf3 cxd4 15. cxd4 Nc7 16. Be4 Rad8 17. c3 Ne6 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gb5b4]} 18. Qa3 Qc7 $44) 13... b4 $5 $11) 11... Qa5 12. Bc1 Bg4 (12... Bb7 $5 13. Bd2 c4 14. Bf1 Qa3 15. Qc1 Qxc1 16. Raxc1 e6 17. a4 Nc7 18. axb5 Nxb5 19. Bxc4 Nxc3 20. Bxc3 Bxf3 21. Ba5 Bd5 $11) 13. Bd2 e6 $11 ( 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 cxd4 15. Rxe7 $36 {Guevara Rincon,C (1664) -Valle,E (2039) COL-ch sf Bogota 2020 (1) 0-1}) 14. Rb1 Nc7 $5 (14... c4 15. Be4 Rad8 $11) 15. c4 (15. dxc5 Bxc3 $11) 15... b4 16. dxc5 Na6 $1 17. a3 Qxa3 $13 * 

