{[%evp 0,38,31,34,41,55,63,66,72,81,69,58,68,71,71,72,61,61,76,62,37,3,-7,-30, -33,-29,-54,-47,5,-3,-3,-15,-15,-21,-16,-21,4,-26,-26,-23,-16]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bc4 {White invites Black to define his intentions in the centre before he chooses his own plans.} Nxc3 {Played at this moment, the knight exchange allows Black to stay flexible.} (5... e6 { is likely to complicate Black's task a bit.} 6. O-O Be7 (6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 $1 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Nc6 9. Be3 Be7 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Nd2 $14) 7. d4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 { we have reached a position we avoid when giving a choice, later in the main line.}) (5... Nb6 6. Bb5+ Bd7 7. d4 {may offer White some light initiative.}) 6. bxc3 (6. dxc3 {is not dangerous as long as White must stay with the king in the centre.} Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Bg4 8. Ke2 Nc6 9. Be3 e6 10. Rhd1 Be7 11. Bb5 f6 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Bg6 14. Rac1 h5 $5 $11) 6... e6 ({The plan} 6... g6 $2 {does not work unfortunately here.} 7. Ne5 e6 8. Qf3 f6 9. Bb5+ $16) 7. O-O {The most restrictive move order.} (7. d4 {offers Black the additional possibility of} cxd4 $5 (7... Bd6 {is likely to transpose to the main line, since} 8. dxc5 { is not dangerous.} Bxc5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Ng5 Ke7 11. Ne4 Nd7 12. O-O b6 $11) 8. cxd4 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. O-O b6 12. Rfe1 (12. d5 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. dxe6 Qxd2 15. exf7+ Rxf7 16. Nxd2 Rc8 17. c4 Rd7 $11) 12... Bb7 13. Ne5 Nc6 (13... Qc7 14. Bb3 Nd7 $11) 14. Rad1 (14. Nxf7 $5 Qxd4 15. Qxd4 Nxd4 16. Rad1 Rxf7 17. Rxd4 Bd5 18. Rxe6 Bxe6 19. Bxe6 Re8 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Kf1 Rc8 22. Rd7+ Kf6 23. Rxa7 Rxc2 {with a probable draw.}) 14... Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Rc8 16. Bd3 Qh4 17. Rde1 Rfd8 18. c3 Rd5 $11 {Lewtak,D (2275) -Markiewicz,J (2241) POL-chT2 Poronin 2013 (7.51) 1/2-1/2}) 7... Bd6 {The most active way of developing the bishop. From this square, the bishop controls e5 and after a later ...Qc7, Black will have some pressure on h2, restricting the enemy knight's mobility among others. True, after an early Ng5-e4 the bishop will have to retreat, but that would not be a problem since the knight would not stand better on e4 than on f3.} (7... Be7 {is more popular, but I feel that it offers White higher freedom.}) 8. d4 {White cannot do without this move. After d2-d3, the light-squared bishop would be exposed to ...Nd7-b6.} O-O 9. Re1 { The most flxible move.} (9. Qe2 Qc7 10. Bd3 Nd7 11. Bg5 Re8 $5 {An interesting, but not the only plan. Black intends to take the steam out of White's attack.} (11... Nb6 {Threatening ...c5-c4.} 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bd2 Nd5 14. Qe4 f5 15. Qh4 Bd7 16. c4 Ne7 17. Bf4 Qd8 18. Ne5 Nc6 19. Qg3 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Qe7 21. Rfe1 Rae8 22. Rad1 Bc6 $11) (11... b6 12. Qe4 g6 {is likely to offer White some attacking chances after the queen's transfer to h4. Objectively, the position may be equal, but I would avoid this position. In any case,} 13. Qxa8 $2 { is bad.} Bb7 14. Qxa7 Ra8 15. Qxa8+ Bxa8 $17) 12. a4 $1 $146 {The only way of maintaining the equality.} (12. Rae1 Nf8 $1 $15 {Black's kingside is rock solid and White's queenside is not.} 13. Ne5 f6 14. Qh5 g6 15. Nxg6 fxg5 16. Nxf8 Rxf8 17. Re3 Qg7 $19 {Brookes,C (2056) -Afek,Y (2298) Vlissingen HZ op 15th 2011 (4) 1-0}) 12... Nf8 (12... b6 $2 13. Qe4 f5 14. Qxa8 $18 {The rook is undefended on e8.}) 13. a5 {By preventing ...b7-b6, White gets some compensation for his structural problems.} h6 14. Bd2 f6 15. Rfe1 Bd7 16. h3 Rac8 $11) (9. Ng5 {is not dagerous.} Nd7 10. Bd3 (10. Ne4 Be7 11. Re1 b6 12. Qg4 Nf6 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. Bd3 Bb7 15. dxc5 g6 $5 $11) (10. Qh5 Nf6 11. Qh4 h6 12. Nf3 Nd5 13. Qg4 e5 14. Qh5 Nb6 15. Bd3 c4 $15) 10... Nf6 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. h3 b6 13. Ne4 Nxe4 14. Qxe4 f5 {The most restrictive move.} (14... g6 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Rb1 Bd7 {Mamedov,R (2667) -Inants,A (2305) Las Vegas Millionaire op 2014 (1) 1-0}) 15. Qxa8 (15. Qe2 Rf6 $1 16. f3 Bb7 17. Be3 Rc8 $15) 15... Bb7 16. Qxa7 Ra8 17. Qxa8+ Bxa8 18. Bc4 Kf7 19. Re1 Be4 20. Bd3 (20. f3 cxd4 21. Bb3 Qxc3 22. Bg5 Bg3 $19) 20... cxd4 (20... Bb7 21. Bc4 $11) 21. cxd4 Qc3 22. Bg5 Bd5 $13) 9... Nd7 10. Be3 (10. Bd3 Qc7 11. Qe2 b6 {transposes above.}) 10... b6 $1 $146 {At this stage, Black does not need to commit his queen. Developing the bishop is more logical.} (10... Qc7 11. Bd3 $6 (11. Qd3 $1 b6 12. Rad1 Nf6 13. Bg5 Nd5 14. Re4 Bb7 15. Rh4 g6 $11) 11... c4 12. Bf1 Nb6 13. Bd2 Bd7 14. Ne5 {Schroeder,J (2568) -Heimann,A (2606) Hobbits Invitational blitz 2021 (2.24) 1/2-1/2} Ba4 15. Rb1 Rad8 16. h3 Rfe8 $15) 11. Qd3 (11. Bd3 Qc7 12. Ng5 Nf6 $15) (11. d5 e5 $5 $11 {justifies the bishop's development to d6.}) 11... Bb7 12. Bg5 (12. Ng5 Nf6 13. dxc5 Bxc5 14. Bxc5 bxc5 15. Rab1 Bd5 $11) 12... Qc7 13. d5 (13. Rad1 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Bxh2+ $17) (13. h3 cxd4 14. cxd4 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Bf4 $17 {In these lines, the setup based on Bd6 reveals its virtues.}) 13... exd5 (13... e5 $5 {may offer White some attacking chances.} 14. Nh4 g6 15. Qh3 a6 16. a4 f5 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Qh6 Nf6 19. Rxe5 Qh7 20. Re6 b5 $13) (13... b5 $5 14. Bxb5 Bxd5 $11 15. Rad1 $1 c4 16. Bxc4 $1 Bxf3 17. Qxd6 Qxc4 18. gxf3 Nb6 $11) 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Rae8 16. Rad1 (16. Red1 $2 Ne5 $1 $17 17. Qxd6 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Re1+ 19. Kg2 Qxd6 20. Rxd6 Rxa1 $19) 16... Ne5 17. Nh4 (17. Qxd6 Nxf3+ 18. gxf3 Rxe1+ $19) 17... Ng6 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. g3 Be5 $11 * 

