{[%evp 0,62,30,10,46,63,90,58,67,72,64,48,47,-1,4,0,7,8,85,85,84,84,84,84,97, 67,73,85,120,45,73,69,86,115,125,112,180,94,105,123,62,21,21,13,21,21,14,21,21, 21,72,65,68,52,55,51,74,44,55,32,36,33,44,64,58]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+ $1 {For several decades, this has been known as the most challenging continuation.} Bd7 6. Ne5 $1 {White has to continue using his slight advance in development. Otherwise, Black will maintain his space advantage in the centre.} (6. Bxd7+ Qxd7 $11 {os very comfortable for Black.}) (6. Bc4 Nb6 {offers Black an extra tempo, since in most of the lines below, ... Bd7 counts as a developing move.} 7. Be2 Nc6 8. d4 (8. O-O e5 {Recommended by Nimzowitsch in his comments on the game mentioned below.} (8... Bf5 {Schlage, W-Nimzowitsch,A Berliner SG 100th anniversary 1928 (8) 0-1} 9. Bb5 $1 $14) 9. Bb5 f6 10. Nh4 Be6 (10... Qe7 11. a4 O-O-O 12. a5 Na8 13. a6 b6 14. f4 Nc7 $15) 11. a4 a6 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qf3 Qd7 14. d3 Be7 15. Qe2 O-O $15 {Tissir,M  (2364) -Rakhmanov,A (2665) Dubai op 19th 2017 (2) 0-1}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 g6 $5 (9... e5 {is another way of using the fact that the knight on c6 is defended by the bishop.} 10. Ndb5 a6 11. Nd6+ Bxd6 12. Qxd6 Bf5 13. Qxd8+ Rxd8 14. Be3 Nd4 $11 {Ponomariov,R (2694) -Rakhmanov,A (2653) Wch Rapid Riadh 2017 (4) 1/ 2-1/2}) 10. Be3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. a4 Ne5 (12... Nb4 13. Qd2 e5 14. Ndb5 Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Qxd2 16. Bxd2 Nxc2 17. Rac1 Nd4 18. Nxd4 exd4 19. a5 Na4 20. Bf3 Rac8 21. Bxb7 Rxc1 22. Bxc1 Nc5 23. Bd5 Rb8 $11) 13. b3 Rc8 14. Qd2 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Bxg4 16. h3 (16. a5 e5 17. Ndb5 Qxd2 18. Bxd2 a6 19. Nd6 Rc6 $11) 16... Bxh3 $5 (16... e5 $2 17. Ndb5 Qxd2 18. Bxd2 Rfd8 19. Bg5 f6 20. hxg4 fxg5 21. Ne4 $16 { Aveskulov,V (2424) -Zubov,A (2490) Kharkov Rector Cup 7th 2005 (8) 1-0}) (16... Bxd4 17. Bxd4 e5 $11) 17. gxh3 Qd7 18. Kg2 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 (19. Bxd4 e5 20. Be3 Qc6+ 21. Kg1 Rfd8 22. Qe1 Qxc3 $17) 19... Qc6+ 20. Qe4 Qxc3 21. Qxb7 Rc7 22. Qe4 Qxc2 23. Qxc2 Rxc2 24. Rfd1 Rc7 $11 {White has certain compensation for the pawn, but not more than that.}) 6... Bxb5 $5 {The adventure starts with this move, which has been held as dubious for many decades. Recently, Mamedyarov has used it in a couple of games.} (6... Nf6 7. Qf3 Qc8 8. a4 $14) ( 6... e6 7. Qf3 $14) 7. Qf3 $1 {The official punishment of Black's last move.} ( 7. Nxb5 e6 $11) (7. Qh5 g6 8. Qf3 f6 9. Qxd5 Qxd5 10. Nxd5 Na6 $11) 7... f6 $1 {Forced.} (7... Nf6 $2 8. Qxb7 $18) 8. Nxb5 $1 (8. Qxd5 Qxd5 9. Nxd5 Na6 { is comfortable for Black.} 10. a4 Bd7 11. Nxd7 Kxd7 12. d3 e6 13. Ne3 Bd6 14. Bd2 Bf4 15. Nc4 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Nb4 $11 {Steiner,L-Steiner,E HUN-ch09 Zoltan Szavay Memorial 1931 (15) 1/2-1/2}) 8... Na6 $1 {The same as in the case of the sixth move, this is recommended despite the engine's unfavourable opinion. We have decided that this was not a struggle in a somewhat worse position, but a fight for the initiative.} (8... fxe5 9. Qxd5 $14 {is not a reason for playing this whole system, of course.}) 9. Qh5+ $1 {There is no way back for White, either} (9. Nc4 Qd7 10. O-O Nab4 11. Nc3 e6 $15) 9... g6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qxh8 {White has won a pawn and an exchange but has wasted a considerable amount of time with his queen. His only developed pieces are temporarily misplaced and vulnerable. On top, the pawn on c2 is a comfortable target. For the human eye, Black should have at least reasonable compensation for the lost material, but for some reason, theory used to be sceptical about Black's position. At this stage, engines share this point of view. However, it is interesting to see that they gradually modulate their opinion as the analysis advances. I am aware of the fact that there could be some mistakes in the lines published in this database since it is not easy to examine a position "against" a "confident" engine. However, we are supposed to fight against human opponents and in practical play, White's task is not that simple. Do not forget that this is partly supposed to be a surprise repertoire. It could work miracles against an opponent who did not check the lines (if he had ever analysed them) right before the game. Some strong grandmasters use it regularly in blitz games and this might be a first sign that things are not that simple for White from a practical point of view. Summing things up, I do believe that the current position is playable for Black, but I have also offered a solid alternative on move 3 (Lines 10 to 13) . The latter is useful anyway, in the event one wishes to play the Nimzowitsch Sicilian more than just occasionally} Qd7 $1 {Maintaining an advance in development is best achieved with developing moves.} (11... Nab4 $2 {is easily parried with} 12. Na3 $1 (12. O-O Nxc2 13. d4 $5 Nxa1 14. Bh6 Kd7 15. Bxf8 Kc6 16. Nc3 Nc2 $13) 12... Nf4 (12... Qd7 13. O-O $18 {Sergin,M (2168) -Kotainy,J (2207) GER-chT Lands U20 2008 (3.2) 1/2-1/2}) 13. O-O (13. g3 $2 Qd5 14. Rg1 Qe5+ $19 { mating next.}) 13... Qd5 14. f3 Nxa2 15. Kh1 $1 (15. Re1 Nxc1 16. Raxc1 Qxd2 $19) (15. Nb5 $5 Kf7 16. Nc7 Qe5 17. Qh4 Qxc7 18. Rxa2 $16) 15... O-O-O 16. Qh4 $16) 12. Nc3 {The most natural and by far most popular answer.} (12. Qg8 { is comfortably answered with} O-O-O $1 {defending the knight.} 13. Nc3 Nf4 14. g3 (14. O-O Qg4 15. g3 {allows Black to force a draw by perpetual in more than one way.} Nh3+ 16. Kg2 Nf4+ 17. Kg1 Qf3 18. gxf4 Qg4+) 14... Ng2+ 15. Kf1 Qh3 16. Ke2 Qg4+ 17. f3 Nf4+ 18. Kf2 Nh3+ 19. Ke2 Nf4+ $11 {White should resign himself to making a draw by perpetual since} 20. Ke3 $2 {loses to} Qh3 $19) ( 12. Qh7 Qxb5 $1 (12... O-O-O $2 13. Qh3 $1 $16) 13. Qxg6+ Kd7 14. Qg4+ { 
[%cal Gc2c4] Threatening c2-c4.} f5 $1 15. Qxf5+ e6 16. Qe4 Nab4 17. a3 (17. c4
Nf6 18. Qe2 Qc6 19. O-O Bd6 $13) 17... Nxc2+ 18. Qxc2 Nf4 $44) (12. a4 $6 Qe6+ $1 13. Kf1 (13. Kd1 Qg4+ $19) 13... Nab4 14. Qh3 $1 {The only move.} (14. Qh4 $2 Nxc2 15. Rb1 Qe1#) 14... Qxh3 15. gxh3 Nxc2 16. Rb1 a6 17. Nc3 Ndb4 18. Rg1 Kf7 $15) (12. Na3 $2 {leaves the king to Black's mercy after} Qe6+ 13. Kf1 Nf4 $19 {White does not have Nc3 and will get mated.}) ({The rare but interesting}  12. Qh4 {is examined in Lines 8 and 9.}) 12... Qe6+ $1 {It makes sense to deprive White of the right to castle.} (12... Nab4 {was successfully played by Mameduarov in one game.} 13. O-O Nxc2 14. Rb1 (14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Rb1) 14... O-O-O (14... Nf4 $1 $11 {threatening ...Nxg2 with a draw by perpetual.} 15. g3 $2 Nd3 $17 16. Qg8 O-O-O 17. Qxg6 f5 $19 {White is paralysed.}) 15. Qh4 Nd4 16. Qe4 e6 17. d3 $6 (17. Nxd5 $1) 17... f5 18. Qe1 Bd6 {Black's position is threatening already.} 19. Bg5 $2 {Caruana,F (2816) -Mamedyarov,S (2808) Leuven GCT blitz 2018 (6) 1/2-1/2} (19. h3 $1 f4 20. f3 Nf5 $13) 19... Bxh2+ 20. Kxh2 Qh7+ 21. Kg1 Rh8 22. f3 Qh2+ 23. Kf2 Rh3 {Threatening ...Rxf3 mate!} 24. Qd2 Rg3 $5 25. Ke1 Rxg2 $19) 13. Kf1 (13. Kd1 Qg4+ 14. Ne2 Nf4 15. Re1 Nxg2 16. Rg1 c4 $44 {White has serious problems completing his development.}) 13... Nab4 14. Qh4 $1 {The most consistent try. White defends his pawn on c2 by indirect means.} (14. Qh3 {is slightly more popular, but offers Black very pleasant play.} Qxh3 15. gxh3 {Pawns will be soon equal and White's shattered structure will not allow him to enjoy his extra exchange. His development has not progressed, either.} Nc7 16. Rb1 Nxc2 (16... Ne6 {may be a more restrictive move order.} 17. d3 Rd8 18. Rg1 Kf7 $44 {The pawn on c2 is not running anywhere.}) 17. Rg1 Kf7 18. d3 (18. b4 $5 Nxb4 19. a3 Nd3 20. Rxb7 Ne6 21. Bb2 c4 $44) 18... Rd8 19. Be3 e5 20. Rd1 Ne6 21. Rd2 Nb4 22. Ke2 f5 $17 23. a3 Nc6 24. Rdd1 Ncd4+ 25. Kf1 Nf3 (25... Be7 $1 $15 {planning ...Rh8.} 26. Bxd4 cxd4 27. Ne2 Bg5 {followed by ...Rc8.}) 26. Rg3 Nfd4 27. Bg5 Rd6 28. h4 Rb6 29. Rd2 Nb3 30. Rd1 Nbd4 31. Rd2 Nb3 32. Rd1 Nbd4 {Efimenko,Z (2632) -Paehtz,E (2456) Monarch Assurance 15th 2006 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 14... Qa6+ $1 (14... Nxc2 $2 15. Qa4+ ) 15. Kg1 $1 (15. Ne2 $6 Nxc2 16. Qe4 Nxa1 17. Qxd5 Rd8 18. Qg8 f5 $15) (15. d3 $2 Nxc3 16. bxc3 Nxc2 $19) 15... O-O-O {Black almost completes his development and renews the threat on c2.} 16. Qg4+ $1 f5 17. Qd1 $1 {White has managed to maintain his structure intact, but the price has been very high. The queen needed three more tempi to return from its adventure and White's development is almost non-existent. I invite you to make an experiment. Switch off the engines and set the position on a tri-dimensional chessboard. Evaluate it with your human senses. Which colour would you choose? Speaking for myself, I would play it with white only if substantially bribed. Where is the fun? On level 50, engines still think that WHite has a clear advantage.} (17. Qe2 Nxc2 18. Qxa6 bxa6 19. Rb1 Na3 20. bxa3 Nxc3 21. Ra1 (21. dxc3 Rd1#) (21. Rb2 Ne2+ 22. Kf1 Nxc1 $19) 21... Bg7 22. Kf1 Ne4 23. Rb1 Nxd2+ 24. Bxd2 Rxd2 $11) 17... Bg7 $1 { Just developing.} ({Most of the games continue} 17... Nxc3 $2 18. bxc3 $16 Bg7 19. Bb2) 18. Nxd5 $1 {The only way of meeting the threat of ...Nxc3 followed by ...Bxc3.} (18. d3 $2 Nxc3 19. bxc3 Bxc3 20. Rb1 Qxa2 21. Bg5 {Parligras,M  (2587) -Westerberg,J (2496) EU-chT (Men) 20th 2015 (8.4) 1-0 is obviously a disaster for White, who nevertheless managed to win in} Bd4 $5 22. Rc1 Nxd3 $1 $19) 18... Rxd5 19. d3 $1 $146 {The only move keeping troubles away.} (19. h4 $2 {and other neutral moves allow Black to disclose his main threat.} Nxc2 $1 20. Qxc2 (20. Rb1 Re5 21. Qxc2 Re1+ 22. Kh2 Rxh1+ 23. Kxh1 Qf1+ 24. Kh2 Be5+ 25. g3 Qxf2+ {mating soon.}) 20... Qe2 21. Qb3 {There is not much White can do. The last move over defends the square on g3.} (21. a4 Qe1+ 22. Kh2 Be5+ 23. g3 Qxf2+ 24. Kh3 Qxg3#) 21... Be5 $1 (21... Qe1+ $2 22. Kh2 Be5+ 23. g3 Qxf2+ 24. Kh3 f4 25. d4 fxg3 26. Qxd5 Qf5+ 27. Kg2 Qf2+ 28. Kh3 {Huschenbeth,N (2533) -Carlstedt,J (2442) Hamburg HSK Summer rapid op 1st 2014 (7) 1/2-1/2}) 22. g3 Bd4 23. Rh2 c4 24. Qc2 g5 25. Rg2 (25. a4 Qe1+ 26. Kg2 Qxf2+ 27. Kh3 g4#) (25. hxg5 Qe1+ 26. Kg2 Qxf2+ 27. Kh3 Qf1+ 28. Kh4 Rd8 $19) 25... gxh4 26. gxh4 (26. a4 {in vain hoping for Ra3.} hxg3 $19) 26... Qe1+ 27. Kh2 Be5+ $19) (19. g3 $2 Qc4 20. c3 (20. d3 Nxc2 21. Rb1 Rxd3 22. Qf1 Qe4 $19) (20. Qf3 Nxc2 21. Rb1 Ne1 22. Qf4 Bd4 $19) 20... Nd3 $19) (19. h3 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 Qe2) 19... Qa4 20. Be3 ( 20. Bg5 Qxc2 21. Qxc2 Nxc2 22. Rd1 Nb4 $11) (20. b3 Qa6 21. Rb1 Qxa2 $15) (20. h4 Qxc2 21. Qxc2 Nxc2 22. Rb1 Nb4 23. h5 gxh5 24. Rxh5 Nxd3 25. b3 b5 $11) 20... Qxc2 21. Qxc2 Nxc2 22. Rc1 (22. Rb1 Nb4 $11) 22... Nxe3 (22... Rxd3 $6 23. Bxc5 Bxb2 24. Rb1 Na3 25. Re1 $16) 23. fxe3 Bxb2 24. Rc2 (24. Rc4 b6 $11) 24... Bf6 {Black has a pawn for the exchange and the better structure.} 25. Kf2 ({An important detail is that} 25. d4 {can be met with} Kd7 $1 26. Rxc5 Rxd4 27. Rxf5 (27. exd4 Bxd4+ 28. Kf1 Bxc5 $11) 27... Rd1+ 28. Rf1 Rd2 29. h4 Rxa2 30. h5 gxh5 31. Rxh5 a5 $13) 25... Kd7 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 26. Rb1 (26. Ke2 b5 $11) (26. a4 Rxd3 27. Rxc5 Rd2+ 28. Kf3 e5 29. e4 fxe4+ 30. Kxe4 Rxg2 $11) 26... b6 27. Rb3 {I do not see any reason why Black should be worse in this ending. How is White going to make progress?} Ke6 (27... Rd6 $5) 28. Rc4 Rd7 29. Ke2 Kd5 30. h3 e6 31. a4 Rb7 $11 {So far, I am confident that Black is doing fine in this line. Moreover, an unprepared player could easily get into trouble with white. That was exactly what happened in the games quoted above. WHite needs to find a long series of only moves to avoid getting the worse of it or even losing. Let us proceed with the next lines.} * 

