1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Ne5 Bxb5 7. Qf3 f6 8. Nxb5 Na6 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qxh8 Qd7 12. Qh4 {A rare move, but possibly the most demanding one.} Qxb5 $1 {Black needs to accept the challenge. } (12... Nab4 $2 13. Na3 Qe6+ 14. Kd1 (14. Kf1 $5 $16) 14... O-O-O {Liepold,S  (2153) -Strobel,W (2275) Landesliga Nord 1314 2013 (6.4) 0-1} 15. Re1 $18) 13. c4 Qb4 14. a3 {Preparing to win the knight on d5 at the cost of one pawn.} (14. Qe4 {is examined in Line 9.}) 14... Qa4 15. b3 Qxb3 16. cxd5 {Analysing this position with the engines is a bit of a nightmare. Black will soon have a pawn for the exchange and the better structure, but engines cry out loud that White has a clear advantage. In many lines, they suggest effective ways of completing White's development, and the hard part of the job is finding the line where their optimism is unjustified.} Qxd5 ({The tempting} 16... Qd3 { has been played twice. It seems that Black does not have enough.} 17. Qg4 $1 { is the only move creating problems. WHite's main idea is h2-h4 followed by Rh3. I did not find any satisfactory line for Black. Can you do better?} (17. Bb2 $6 Rd8 18. O-O-O (18. Qg3 Qe4+ $44) (18. Qg4 Nc7 $44) 18... Rxd5 $6 (18... c4 $1 { threatening ...Nc5.} 19. Qd4 $1 {The only defence.} Qxd4 20. Bxd4 e5 $5 $11) 19. Qg3 (19. Rhe1 $1 $16 {followed by Re3.}) 19... c4 (19... Qf5 $5 $11) 20. Qxd3 Rxd3 (20... cxd3 $1 21. Kb1 Nc5 22. Rhe1 Kd7 $11) 21. Kc2 Nc5 22. Bc3 { Smikovski,I (2554) -Smirnov,A (2452) RUS-ch Higher League 61st 2008 (3) 1-0} b5 23. h4 Rd5 $44) (17. Qg3 $6 Qe4+ 18. Kf1 Rd8 19. d3 Qf5 20. h4 Kf7 21. Rh3 Rxd5 $44) 17... Rd8 (17... Kf7 18. h4 Nc7 19. h5 g5 20. h6 Nxd5 21. Rh3 Qg6 22. d3 Bxh6 23. Rb1 $16 b6 $2 24. Qd7 $18) (17... Nc7 18. d6 exd6 19. Bb2 $16) 18. Qe2 (18. h4 $1 $16) 18... Rxd5 (18... Qxd5 $1 19. O-O Kf7 20. Bb2 Nc7 21. Bc3 Ne6 $11) 19. Qxd3 Rxd3 20. Rb1 b6 21. h4 c4 22. h5 gxh5 23. Rxh5 Nc5 24. Rb4 Rd4 $44 {Moskalenko,A (2558) -Egorov,P (2282) Voronezh op-A 22nd 2018 (1) 1/2-1/2}) 17. O-O O-O-O $1 $146 {We have once again reached a position in which Black has a pawn for the exchange and the better structure. He needs a bit of accuracy, though, since his bishop will be not easy to develop and his king is exposed to checks on the light diagonal.} (17... Bg7 18. Rb1 O-O-O {Bijaoui,M  (2338) -Morelle,L (2232) FRA-ch Accession 2005 (4) 1/2-1/2} 19. d4 $5 cxd4 20. Qh7 $16) 18. Bb2 Nc7 ({With the knight still on a6,} 18... Qxd2 19. Rab1 { is dangerous for Black.}) 19. Bc3 {The most flexible move.} (19. Qg4+ Qf5 { is safe for Black.} 20. Qxf5+ gxf5 21. d3 b5 22. Rac1 Rd5 23. f4 Kd7 24. h4 a5 25. a4 b4 26. h5 Bh6 27. Rf3 e5 28. Re1 e4 $1 {Clearing the path for the c-pawn.} 29. dxe4 fxe4 30. Rxe4 f5 31. Rc4 Ne8 $44 {followed by ...Nd6.}) (19. Rac1 b6 $1 20. Bc3 g5 21. Qa4 (21. Qg4+ Qd7 22. Qxd7+ Kxd7 23. f4 gxf4 24. Rxf4 Nd5 25. Ra4 Ra8 26. Kf2 e5 27. g3 Ke6 $11) 21... Ne6 $1 22. g3 (22. Qxa7 Nf4 23. f3 Ne2+ 24. Kh1 Nxc1 25. Rxc1 Rd6 $5 $11) 22... Kb7 23. Qg4 Nd4 24. Bxd4 Qxd4 {Black has a dominant position in the centre, but the main problem remains the bishop.} 25. Qh5 (25. Qxd4 Rxd4 $15) (25. Qf3+ Qd5 $11) 25... Qd7 $1 {Preparing the next move.} 26. Rc3 e5 27. a4 {The most constructive plan.} Qe6 28. d3 Rd4 29. Rb1 $5 (29. Ra1 Be7 $11 30. a5 b5 31. a6+ Kb6 32. Qe8 Rd8 33. Qg6 Rd4 $11) 29... Rxa4 30. Rc4 $1 Rb4 $1 31. Qh7+ Be7 32. Rbxb4 cxb4 33. Rxb4 a5 $13 {The position could easily go Black's way, since the connected queenside pawns may become dangerous.}) 19... g5 (19... Qf5 20. f4 $5) 20. Qa4 (20. Qg4+ Qd7 21. Qxd7+ (21. h3 Qxg4 22. hxg4 Rd3 $11) 21... Kxd7 22. f4 $1 { The only chance.} (22. a4 Nd5 $11) 22... g4 $1 {This is another interesting ending.} 23. Rae1 f5 24. h3 gxh3 25. gxh3 Ke8 26. h4 Kf7 27. Rf3 Nd5 28. Kf2 b5 29. Be5 c4 30. Rb1 a6 31. h5 Nf6 32. Bxf6 Kxf6 33. Ke2 Rd4 34. a4 Bh6 $132 35. axb5 axb5 36. Rg3 Bxf4 37. Rg6+ Kf7 38. Rxb5 Re4+ 39. Kf3 Be5 {with a probable draw.}) 20... a6 21. f4 b5 22. Qd1 $5 {[%cal Gg5g4] Controlling g4.} (22. Qc2 g4 23. f5 Bh6 $11) 22... b4 $1 {Despite the engine's scepticism at this stage, this pawn break ensures Black enough counterplay.} 23. axb4 cxb4 24. Bb2 Qxd2 $1 (24... gxf4 $2 25. Rxf4 Qxd2 26. Qxd2 Rxd2 27. Rxb4 $18) 25. Qxd2 Rxd2 26. Bc1 (26. Rf2 Rxf2 27. Kxf2 gxf4 $11) (26. Rab1 g4 $11) 26... Rd8 27. fxg5 fxg5 28. Bxg5 (28. Ra4 e5 29. Bxg5 Bc5+ 30. Kh1 Rd5 31. g4 e4 32. h4 e3 33. Kg2 b3 $13) 28... Bg7 29. Ra4 Nd5 30. Rxa6 b3 31. Rb1 (31. Ra8+ Kc7 32. Rxd8 Bd4+ 33. Kh1 Kxd8 $11 {is likely to transpose below.} 34. Rd1 $6 {is ineffective due to} b2 $1) 31... Bd4+ $1 (31... b2 $2 32. Ra8+ Kc7 33. Rxd8 Kxd8 34. Kf1 $18) 32. Kh1 (32. Kf1 Rf8+ 33. Ke1 Rf5 34. Bd2 b2 $13) 32... b2 33. Ra8+ (33. Ra4 Bg7 34. Ra2 Kd7 35. Raxb2 Bxb2 36. Rxb2 Re8 37. h4 e5 38. g4 e4 $11) 33... Kd7 34. Rxd8+ Kxd8 35. h4 Ke8 36. Kh2 Kf7 37. Bd2 (37. Kg3 Nc3 38. Rxb2 Ne4+ 39. Kf4 Nxg5 $11) 37... e5 38. Kg3 e4 39. Kg4 Ke6 $11 {This line may be a bit more obscure than the previous one, but in principle I believe that it is entirely playable for Black.} * 

