{[%evp 0,90,16,28,46,43,78,60,66,87,67,74,49,-6,12,2,2,14,151,82,46,61,42,65, 76,49,60,48,43,34,30,29,65,35,35,35,67,60,85,61,54,30,72,73,141,131,112,106, 106,97,118,111,111,125,125,114,126,126,133,117,119,119,133,117,118,121,132,82, 136,75,101,103,113,101,122,105,105,104,82,103,101,122,123,131,166,108,137,130, 117,64,61,120,120]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 d5 4. exd5 Nxd5 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Ne5 Bxb5 7. Qf3 f6 8. Nxb5 Na6 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. Qxh8 Qd7 12. Qh4 Qxb5 13. c4 Qb4 14. Qe4 $5 {Played only once, this line gave me the most headaches. White refrains from winning the knight and plays for an advance in development. The outside passed pawn h2 might also play an important part, since Black's forces are located on the opposite wing. I assume that the main thing scaring the engine is the black king's presence in the centre. This is an important criterion in its evaluation.} Ndc7 ({I failed to find enough play for Black after} 14... O-O-O 15. Qe6+ Kb8 16. cxd5 Nc7 17. Qe2 Nxd5 18. g3 $1 ( 18. O-O Nf4 $36) 18... Qd4 {In both lines below, Black seems to miss one tempo for consolidating his domination in the centre.} 19. a3 (19. O-O $5 {is also possible, on the condition that after} Nb4 {, White gives up the pawn with} 20. d3 $1 {Otherwise, ...Nd3 would paralyse White.} Nxd3 21. Be3 Qd7 22. Rad1 e5 23. Rd2 Be7 24. Rfd1 c4 25. a3 $16 {preventing ...Bb4 and preparing b2-b3. Black is not in time for ...f7-f5 and ...e5-e4, which would absolve him of the necessity of playing ...b7-b5 after b2-b3.}) 19... c4 20. O-O e5 (20... a5 21. Rd1 Nc7 22. d3 $1 cxd3 23. Be3 Qd5 24. Qg4 $16) 21. Rb1 $1 $16 {Just in time! White prepares b2-b3.} (21. Re1 $2 a5 $1 $11 {threatening ...a5-a4 with complete control.} 22. a4 $2 Bc5 $19 {followed by ...Nb4.})) 15. Qxg6+ Kd8 $1 $146 {This was the hardest move to find. Or better said, its merits were hard to grasp. It is obvious that on d7 the king is exposed to checks along the h3-c8 diagonal, but this does not seem essential at this stage. With the king on d8, White will later need to waste an important tempo with his queen to maintain his dominant setup.} ({Let us compare with} 15... Kd7 16. b3 (16. Qf5+ $5 e6 17. Qh7+) 16... Qb6 17. Bb2 Ne6 18. O-O $1 (18. g3 Qc6 19. O-O-O Kc7 $13) (18. O-O-O Nb4 19. Kb1 Nd4 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21. h4 a5 $132) (18. h4 $6 Nf4 $15 19. Qg4+ Qe6+ 20. Qxe6+ Kxe6) 18... Qd6 19. Rae1 {With the king on d8, this way of developing rapidly would offer Black counterplay at once.} Kc7 ({The main problem with the king on d7 is that} 19... Nf4 $2 {is ineffective due to} 20. Qf5+ {winning, for instance} Kc7 21. d4 $18) 20. Re4 {I have included here part of my analysis on ...Kd7 to show that even after that move, the evaluation remains a question of just one tempo.} (20. g3 Nb4 21. h4 Nc6 $11) ( 20. Bxf6 Nf4 21. Qg4 Qxf6 $19) 20... Nd4 (20... Nf4 21. Qf5 Nd3 22. Bc3 $16) ( 20... Rd8 21. Bxf6 $1 exf6 22. Qf7+ $16) 21. Rfe1 (21. h4 f5 $1 $15) (21. Bxd4 cxd4 22. Rh4 Rd8 23. Rh8 Nb8 24. h4 Nc6 25. h5 Ne5 26. Qe4 Nf7 27. Rg8 d3 28. Re1 Ne5 $14) 21... Nb4 22. Bxd4 (22. h4 Nbc2 $11) 22... cxd4 23. Qf5 e5 24. Rh4 Be7 25. a3 Nc6 26. b4 Qd7 27. Qf3 d3 28. Rh7 Rg8 $16 {The position is not necessarily lost for Black, but WHite's play is easier to carry out.}) 16. b3 ( 16. Qd3+ Kc8 $1 ({More ambitious and better than} 16... Ke8 {transposing to the only game mentioned above, in which the king initially went to d7.} 17. O-O $6 Rd8 18. Qg6+ Kd7 19. d3 Kc8 20. h4 Qa4 21. Be3 Qe8 {Makovsky,P (2502) -Dolgov,I (2507) Rochade 20 years email 2009 [2] 1/2-1/2}) 17. Qf5+ (17. O-O { allows} Qa4 {followed by a quick regrouping with ...Qe8/d7.}) 17... Kb8 18. b3 Qb6 19. O-O Nb4 20. Bb2 a5 21. a3 Nc6 22. Bc3 Na6 {Preparing the next move, without fearing b3-b4.} 23. h4 Ka7 24. Rab1 e5 $1 {Sacrificing a pawn to stabilise the centre and open the communication between the opposite wings.} 25. Qxf6 Be7 26. Qh6 Rg8 27. g3 Qd8 $132 {The threat ...Bxh4 is hard to meet.}) 16... Qb6 17. O-O Ne6 {The same setup as above, in the lines with the king on d7. It is best to start with the knight move, taking measures against d2-d4.} ( 17... Qd6 $6 18. d4 $5 cxd4 19. Bd2 $36) 18. Bb2 (18. Re1 Qd6 {does not make much of a difference.}) 18... Qd6 19. Qf7 {This is the tempo White needs to lose, while also placing the queen somewhat far from the important areas. The main idea is to attack the bishop, thus restricting the mobility of the knight and forcing Black to waste a tempo with his king.} (19. Rae1 {runs into} Nf4 $1 20. Qf7 (20. Qf5 $2 {without check is a disaster.} Nd3 $17 21. Rb1 Nxb2 22. Rxb2 Nb4 $17) 20... Kc7 $1 {slightly improving over the main line.}) (19. Qf5 $6 {is not dangerous since it does not pin the knight.} Nb4 20. Rae1 Ng7 21. Qe4 Nd3 $15) 19... Kd7 $1 {This is the best square now. Black needs to over-defend the knight.} (19... Kc7 $2 20. Bxf6 $18) 20. Rae1 (20. Bxf6 $2 { loses to} Qf4 $19 {, precisely because the knight is defended.}) 20... Nd4 ( 20... Nb4 $2 21. Bxf6 $1 Nd8 22. Qxf8 Qxf6 23. Qg8 $18) 21. Re4 {Threatening Bxd4.} (21. Bxd4 Qxd4 {is comfortable for Black, who has achieved stability in the centre.}) (21. h4 {offers Black a tempo for regrouping.} Nb4 $11) 21... f5 $1 {Black is in time to react.} 22. Rh4 $1 (22. Ree1 {allows Black to complete his development with gain of time.} Bh6 $1 23. Bxd4 Rf8 24. Bxc5 (24. Qh7 cxd4 $17) 24... Nxc5 25. Qh7 Nd3 $15) 22... Qe6 $1 {This is the point. With the queens off the board, Black's king is safer and active, too.} 23. Qxe6+ (23. Qh7 Bg7 $1 24. Qxg7 Nf3+ 25. gxf3 Rg8 $13 26. Qg3 Rxg3+ 27. hxg3 Nb4 28. Bc3 Nd3 $44 {White has a considerable material advantage, but suddenly, it is Black who is very active and controls everything.}) 23... Nxe6 24. Rd1 { Preparing to eliminate the weaknesses along the d-file.} (24. Re1 Nb4 25. Re3 a5 $132 {[%cal Ga8a6,Ga6d6,Ga5a4] followed by either ...a5-a4 or ...Ra6-d6.}) 24... Bg7 25. Bxg7 Nxg7 26. d4 cxd4 27. Rhxd4+ Ke8 {This endgame looks promising for White, but analysis shows that Black can coordinate his knights properly.} 28. h4 Nc7 29. g3 Nge6 30. Rd7 Kf7 31. Kg2 (31. c5 b6 $1 32. c6 Ne8 $1 33. b4 Nf6 34. R7d3 a6 35. a4 Rc8 36. b5 axb5 37. axb5 Ne8 38. Rd7 N8c7 39. Rb1 Nc5 40. Rdd1 Ne4 $13) (31. b4 b5 $5 32. cxb5 Nxb5 $132) 31... b6 32. h5 Ne8 33. R7d5 $5 (33. R1d5 f4 $11 {is simpler for Black.}) 33... Kf6 (33... f4 $2 34. Re1 $1 {followed by R5d5.}) 34. Re1 N8c7 35. Rd7 Na6 36. h6 Nac5 37. Rd5 { Black is perfectly regrouped and his knights can continue jumping around.} Nc7 38. Rdd1 a5 39. h7 Rh8 40. Rh1 Kg6 41. Rde1 Kf7 42. Re3 Ne8 43. a3 Nf6 44. b4 axb4 45. axb4 Ncd7 $13 {/= This and the previous line were the hardest to analyse in the whole database. Engines come to reason very late. On the other hand, this circumstance makes it difficult for the player with white to prepare before the game, even if he knows that his opponent is going to play the Nimzowitsch system. All the lines seem to be very good for White, but over the board, things could be very disappointing and confusing for White. The optimal situation would have a player with black, who is very skilled in piece play and a positional player with white. Even with a bit of preparation, White would be in certain danger. Earlier, I have given a disclaimer concerning possible omissions in this long analysis. Had I written these lines, say, in five years, engines might have been strong enough to sanction the validity of the whole system without the need to push them little by little. For practical reasons, I believe that the line is entirely playable. It is the choice of each of us whether to use it occasionally or regularly, in blitz games over the internet or in over-the-board games.} * 

