{[%evp 0,34,30,19,63,58,76,57,64,51,110,68,68,52,67,33,38,-65,84,35,27,27,21, 21,21,21,23,0,5,2,12,6,13,11,19,9,15]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 ({Now is a good moment for talking about the Closed Sicilian move order.} 2. Nc3 e6 $1 {This is a good antidote to the Closed Sicilian systems. The only question remains what to do if White switches back to the d2-d4 plan, of course, but this does not bother us.} ({If we prefer sticking to 3...d5 as an answer to 3.Nc3, then it is worth examining} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 e5 {, which was also introduced by Nimzowitsch, by the way.}) 3. Nge2 $5 (3. Nf3 Nf6 {transposes to the lines examined here. True, it takes us away from the 3.Nc3 d5 lines, which were much sharper than those examined here.}) (3. g3 d5 {is known to be comfortable for Black.}) (3. f4 d5 {is not a big problem, either.}) 3... Nf6 4. e5 $6 ({ In the event of} 4. d4 d5 {, White does not have anything better than transposing to some of the lines here, for instance} 5. exd5 Nxd5 6. Nxd5 Qxd5 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 a6 {and we have transposed to Line 13.}) 4... Ng4 $1 {Taking full advantage of the fact that the central pawn is not defended by the knight.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 4... Nd5 {, but the main move is simply stronger.} 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. g3 d6 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Nf4 d4 13. Nd3 $11 {Ermenkov,E (2495) -Kuligowski,A (2495) Smederevska Palanka 1979 (2) 1-0 This looks like the most harmonious regrouping move.} Bf8 $5) 5. d4 (5. f4 d5 $15 6. h3 Nh6 $17) 5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 h5 7. f4 (7. Bf4 Nc6 8. Qd2 Ngxe5 9. O-O-O d5 $17 {Moskalenko,A  (2443) -Wieczorek,O (2494) Titled Tuesday intern op 15th Aug Late blitz 2023  (5) 1-0}) 7... Nc6 8. Qd2 d5 $15) 2... Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 $5 {This is a solid alternative to 3...d5. It involves no risk at all but offers fewer chances for grabbing the initiative. Black is aiming to equalise gradually, which is within reach.} 4. d4 {One of the two crucial moves. Neutral continuations allow Black to play ...d7-d5 under more comfortable circumstances.} (4. Be2 Nc6 (4... d5 $5 5. exd5 Nxd5) 5. d4 (5. O-O d5 6. exd5 exd5 7. d4 Be6 {transposes below.}) 5... d5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Bb4 $11 {is supposed to equalise.}) 6. exd5 exd5 7. O-O Be6 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 Be7 10. dxc5 O-O 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Qd2 Qe7 13. Na4 d4 $44 {Haemmerle,D (1978) -Baumann,W (2076) EU-ch SC-OR/406 email 2021 1/ 2-1/2}) (4. g3 d5 5. exd5 exd5 (5... Nxd5 $5) 6. d4 Bg4 7. Be2 Nc6 8. O-O Be7 ( 8... c4 9. Nh4 Be6 10. Bf3 h6 11. Bg2 Be7 12. f4 O-O 13. f5 Bc8 $13 {Lu,S  (2612) -Van Foreest,J (2612) Tata Steel-B 79th 2017 (6) 1-0}) 9. Be3 O-O 10. dxc5 Bxf3 (10... Qd7 $44) 11. Bxf3 d4 12. Bxc6 dxe3 13. Bxb7 Bxc5 14. fxe3 Rb8 15. Bd5 Bxe3+ (15... Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Rxb2 $11) 16. Kh1 Rxb2 17. Bb3 Bd4 18. Nd5 Rxb3 19. Qxd4 Rb6 20. Rxf6 gxf6 (20... Rxf6 21. Nxf6+ Qxf6 22. Qxf6 gxf6 23. c4 Rc8 24. Rc1 Kf8 25. Kg2 Ke7 26. Kf3 Kd6 27. Ke4 Rc5 $11) 21. Qg4+ Kh8 22. Nxb6 axb6 23. Qf3 Qe7 24. Rf1 Rc8 25. c3 b5 $11 {Baklan,V (2631) -Parligras,M (2588) ROM-chT Eforie Nord 2008 (6) 1/2-1/2}) ({The other major continuation is} 4. e5 Nd5 {transposing to Lines 22 to 35.}) 4... d5 $1 {The only consequent reaction. In the lines below, we will find games transposing from the French Defence  (for instance, 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.exd5 exd5, which is completely inoffensive) .} (4... cxd4 {transposes to other Sicilian systems.}) 5. Bg5 {For some reason, the most popular move. WHite does not seem to achieve much with it.} (5. e5 Ne4 $1 (5... Nfd7 {leads to a comfortable French Defence variation, mentioned in the comments to earlier lines.}) 6. Nxe4 (6. Bd3 Nxc3 7. bxc3 c4 8. Be2 Qa5 9. Bd2 Nc6 10. h4 Bd7 11. h5 h6 $15 {It always feels good to double the white pawns without giving away the bishops' pair.}) 6... dxe4 7. Ng5 cxd4 8. Nxe4 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 Qxe5 10. Qe2 (10. Bd3 Nc6 11. O-O {offers better chances for getting some compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Nc6 $17 {as played in four games.}) (5. dxc5 Bxc5 {leads to a comfortable Isolani version, because the bishop has taken on c5 without wasting a tempo with ...Be7.} 6. exd5 exd5 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 Be6 $11) (5. Bd3 c4 $5 (5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 7. Nf3 d4 8. Ne2 Nc6 9. O-O Be7 $11) 6. Be2 (6. e5 cxd3 7. exf6 dxc2 8. Qxc2 gxf6 9. O-O Nc6 10. Re1 Bg7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Qd2 {Sengupta,D-Oflaz,Y ICCF FM/3645 email 2021 1/2-1/2} Kh8 13. Bh6 Rg8 14. Bxg7+ Rxg7 {The engine evaluates the position as equal and that may be true. I will take myself the liberty to say that Black is a pawn up and out of any danger.}) 6... Bb4 7. Nd2 (7. exd5 exd5 8. O-O O-O $11) (7. e5 Ne4 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Qa5 $15 {Vakhlamov,I (2413) -Bluebaum, M (2657) Titled Tuesday intern op 27th Dec Early blitz 2022 (4) 0-1}) 7... Qa5 (7... Nc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. Nf3 f6 10. exf6 Nxf6 11. O-O O-O $11) 8. Ncb1 {Egorov,E (2282) -Volkov,S (2453) Voronezh op 2023 (9) 0-1} b5 9. O-O Be7 10. c3 Nc6 $11) (5. Bb5+ {is examined in Line 11.}) (5. exd5 {may be the critical continuation and is examined in Line 12.}) 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 (6. Bxf6 gxf6 {may transpose below.}) 6... cxd4 7. Bb5+ (7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qxd4 (8. Bb5+ Bd7 {transposes below.}) 8... Qxd4 9. Nxd4 f5 $15 {is very pleaant for Black.}) (7. Nxd4 Be7 ( 7... Qa5+ $5 8. Qd2 Qe5 9. f3 Nxe4 10. fxe4 {In all the games reaching this position, Black took the pawn on e4, which yields White dangerous initiative. It is better to continue developing and maintain the threat in reserve.} Bc5 $5 $146 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. O-O-O Nc6 $11) 8. Nxf6+ Bxf6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11) 7... Bd7 { White's position looks more active, but the multiple-tension is likely to dissipate his initiative through simplification.} 8. Qxd4 (8. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 { helps Black to develop.} 9. Qxd4 Qa5+ (9... Be7 {may transpose below but offers White the additional possibility} 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Qxd6 {, which is not dangerous, though.} Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qc5 $11) 10. Bd2 Qd5 (10... Qa6 $5 { faces White with the dilemma of how to castle.}) 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. Qxd5 Nxd5 13. c4 Nb4 14. Ke2 {Chiricuta,M-Nikolic,N Danube tt1 corr 1984 1/2-1/2} Nc6 $11 ) 8... Be7 $1 $146 {Being slightly behind in development, Black should develop! In this concrete position, the last move is a novelty, but after the exchange on d7 play will transpose to games in which this happened earlier.} ( 8... Qa5+ $2 9. Bd2 $1 Qxb5 (9... Qd8 10. Bd3 $16 {Kobryn,M (1980) -Dovzhenko, V W-ch WS/H/210 email 2009 1-0}) 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Qxf6 Rg8 12. Ne5 Rg7 13. O-O-O $16) 9. O-O-O {The most aggressive continuation.} Nxe4 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Qxe4 Nc5 (12... Nb6 13. Rd4 O-O 14. Rhd1 Rac8 15. Kb1 h6 $11) ( 12... Nf6 $2 13. Qa4+ $16 {Ngo,M (1599) -Pitzer,A (1312) Niedersachsen-ch U12 2012 (2) 1-0}) 13. Qe5 O-O 14. Rd6 Rfd8 (14... Rac8 15. Rhd1 b5 16. Kb1 Qb7 $11 ) 15. Rhd1 Rxd6 16. Qxd6 Kf8 (16... Qxd6 17. Rxd6 {Janowski,D-Teichmann,R Ostend Masters 1905 (12) 1/2-1/2} Rc8 $11) 17. Qd4 Rc8 $11 * 

