{[%evp 0,40,19,18,66,52,79,64,79,40,110,30,69,66,66,33,43,30,30,19,37,27,27,43, 40,54,35,39,44,29,30,-23,-10,-23,-12,-11,-11,-11,-13,-22,-12,4,6]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. d4 d5 5. Bb5+ {The active incursion of the king's bishop is more natural than that of its colleague, examined in Line 10.} Nc6 $1 (5... Bd7 {is likely to yield White some initiative.} 6. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 (6... Qxd7 7. Ne5 $14) 7. exd5 exd5 8. O-O $14 {This position is similar to a popular French tabyia, with the difference that White's queen's knight is on c3 instead of d2. This ensures White more active play.}) 6. exd5 (6. Ne5 Bd7 7. Nxd7 Qxd7 8. e5 ( 8. exd5 Nxd5 $11 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $17) (8. dxc5 d4 9. Ne2 Nxe4 10. b4 a5 11. Qd3 Nc3 12. Nxc3 dxc3 13. Qxc3 axb4 14. Qc4 Qd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 $11 {Weetik,V (2441) -Mamonov,A (2226) Dvorkovich Memorial op 4th 2009 (5) 1-0}) 8... cxd4) (6. Bg5 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Qa5+ 8. Nc3 Ne4 9. Bxc6+ (9. Bd2 Nxd2 10. Qxd2 cxd4 11. Nxd4 Qc7) 9... bxc6 10. Bd2 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 {Major,I-Medvegy,Z (2280) Papp Bela Memorial 1994 (1) 0-1} Rb8 12. O-O-O f6 13. dxc5 Be7) 6... Nxd5 7. Nxd5 {A consistent try to maintain the initiative.} (7. O-O {is best met with} cxd4 {, when the tension does not promise too much to White.} 8. Qxd4 (8. Nxd5 Qxd5 9. Nxd4 Bd7 $11) (8. Nxd4 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Bd7 10. Qg4 Nxd4 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. cxd4 h5 13. Qg3 {Zverev,L (2322) -Zubritskiy,A (2468) St Petersburg Blitz 2023 (6) 1-0} h4 14. Qg4 Rc8 $15) 8... Bd7 9. Qe4 Nf6 10. Qh4 Be7 11. Qg3 a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Ne5 O-O 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Bh6 Ne8 16. Rad1 Qb8 $11) (7. Ne5 {is tempting, but can be parried with} Bd7 $1 $146 {The best way of defending c6. EVen though it seems that the tension is promising for White, he needs to be careful not to get the worse of it.} 8. Nxd7 {Optically, the most molesting continuation. White gains the bishops' pair and has a pin along the a4-e8 diagonal. However, moving for the third time with the same piece to exchange a bishop that had only moved once is wrong from the point of view of the development.} (8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $11) 8... Qxd7 9. dxc5 (9. O-O cxd4 10. Bxc6 {Otherwise, White will be a pawn down.} Qxc6 11. Qxd4 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Rd8 13. Qxa7 Bc5 14. Qa5 O-O $15) (9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $17) 9... Nxc3 10. Qxd7+ Kxd7 11. bxc3 Bxc5 $11) 7... Qxd5 8. c4 {One more consequent move.} (8. O-O {is once again inoffensive, since the capture on d4 forces White to go for simplifications.} cxd4 (8... c4 $5 9. a4 a6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. b3 c5 13. bxc4 Qe4 $44) 9. Nxd4 Bd7 10. Be3 Nxd4 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. Qxd4 {Scheglov,D (1773) -Tsvetkov,A (1816) Palanga Baltija op-A 2014 (8) 1-0} Qxd4 13. Bxd4 f6 $11) 8... Qe4+ 9. Be3 cxd4 10. Qxd4 {White's position would be very good if Black did not have the next move.} Bb4+ $1 {Obvious and strong.} 11. Kf1 (11. Kd1 $5 {is more active since the king will be ready to sustain the queenside majority. On the other hand, it could be more exposed on, say, b3, too.} Qxd4+ 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 $1 {With the white king ready to advance on the queenside, it is better to keep both bishops on the board in order to maintain the possibility of creating threats.} (13... Bxc6 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Kc2 $14) 14. Ba6 Rb8 15. a3 Be7 16. b4 f5 17. c5 e5 18. Bc4 Rd8 19. Kc2 f4 20. Bc1 Bf5+ 21. Kb3 Bf6 22. Ra2 Ke7 23. Re1 a5 $11) (11. Ke2 $6 {runs into} Qc2+ $1 12. Bd2 Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Rac1 Bxf3+ 15. gxf3 Qxd2+ 16. Qxd2 Bxd2 17. Kxd2 Ke7 $15) 11... Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Nxc6 bxc6 (13... Bxc6 {is also playable under the given circumstances.} 14. Bxc6+ bxc6 15. Ke2 Ke7 16. Rhd1 Rhd8 17. Bf4 (17. a3 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 Bd6 $11) 17... f6 18. a3 Bc5 19. Bc7 $6 (19. b4 Bd4 20. Rab1 e5 $11) 19... Rxd1 20. Rxd1 a5 $15 {Gonzalez Benavides,M (1673) -Garcia Porlan,B (2006) ESP-ch U18 Salobrena 2015 (4) 0-1}) 14. Ba4 (14. Ba6 Be7 15. Ke2 e5 16. b4 f5 $11) 14... Be7 15. c5 Rb8 16. Rb1 e5 17. Ke2 Kd8 18. b4 Kc7 19. f4 Bf6 20. Bc2 Be6 $11 * 

