{[%evp 0,24,27,45,66,47,73,79,79,39,45,20,39,36,54,23,24,-53,-46,-46,-46,-85, -56,-76,-42,-168,-114]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 {Together with 3.Nc3, examined above, this is one of the two critical continuations. True, it is not like White has such a wide choice since his pawn on e4 is attacked. We can notice a small principled difference. While 3.Nc3 was more of a question of whether Black had something up to his sleeve for the event that White did not wish to enter the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, 3.e4 is inviting Black to prove the correctness of the line itself.} Nd5 {White has tried many moves in this position. I remember a comment by Tal, who said the same thing about one of his favourite weapons, the Benoni. In that opening, too, White has numerous systems at his disposal. According to Tal, this does not mean White can play however he wishes. On the contrary, it shows that players with white are not sure whether there is a clear way of gaining an advantage. To a certain extent, this applies to the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, too. White's main ideas are questioning the stability of Black's knight, consolidating the pawn on e5 and gaining space with d2-d4.} 4. Bc4 {A somewhat impulsive move, exposing the bishop after Black's natural answer.} (4. c3 {transposes to the Alapin Sicilian, 1.e4 c5 2.c3 Nf6 3.e5 Nd5, when one of the possible move orders is 4. Nf3. We will not examine it here, since this is a different opening. I might make a database on it soon.}) (4. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:15] is examined in Line}) ({ For} 4. b3 {, see Lines 16 and 17.}) (4. g3 {is the subject of Line 18.}) (4. c4 {is examined in Line 19.}) (4. d4 {is an important continuation already and is examined in Line 20.}) ({The absolute main system in the Nimzowitch Sicilian is} 4. Nc3 {, examined in Lines 21 to 35.}) 4... Nb6 5. Be2 {One of White's probloems is that Black has not developed his queen's knight yet, making Bb5 pointless.} (5. d3 e6 {It is better to maintain the threat ...Nxc4 in reserve.} (5... Nxc4 6. dxc4 $14 {offers White some pressure along the d-file.}) 6. Nc3 d5 7. exd6 Bxd6 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 Nc6 10. Ne4 {Petzold,L  (2239) -Bach,M (2276) BL2-Nord 0708 2007 (9.6) 1-0} Qc7 $5 $11 (10... Na5 $5 $11) 11. Bxc5 (11. Nxc5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Bb3 Bxh2+ 14. Kh1 Bf4 $11) 11... Bxc5 12. Nxc5 Nxc4 13. dxc4 Na5 14. b4 Nxc4 15. Qd4 Nb6 $5 16. c4 a5 17. a3 Rd8 18. Qh4 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Rxa1 Nxc4 21. Qxc4 b6 $11) (5. b3 $6 {is a less convincing way of defending the knight than d2-d3.} Nxc4 {This does not create problems along the d-file. It simply spoils White's structure and gets the bishops' pair.} 6. bxc4 Nc6 7. Bb2 (7. d4 $2 {simply loses a pawn.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 {Kunwar, B-Ostrovskij,J IECC Swiss email 1997 1-0 The most effective way of grabbing the pawn is} Qa5+ 9. c3 Nxe5 $19) 7... d6 8. d3 Bg4 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. O-O f6 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nc3 e5 13. Re1 O-O-O $5 {Black has more space, a better structure and the bishops' pair. White's solid position and slight lead in development at most compensates for all these aspects.}) 5... Nc6 6. O-O (6. a4 $6 $146 {is mainly a waste of time.} d5 7. a5 $6 Nc4 $15) (6. c3 { transposes to a sideline of the Alapin system. I will just give here an orientative line.} d6 7. exd6 Qxd6 8. O-O g6 9. d3 (9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. cxd4 Bg7 $11 {Ivanov,A (1006) -Lintchevski,D (2555) Malaya Zemlya Blitz op 2021 (1) 0-1}) 9... Bg7 10. Na3 O-O $11) 6... d6 {The best way of challenging WHite's space advantage.} (6... Qc7 $6 7. Nc3 Nxe5 8. a4 $36) 7. exd6 e5 $11 8. b4 $6 (8. a4 Bxd6 9. a5 Nd7 $11) (8. d3 Bxd6 9. Nc3 O-O $11) 8... cxb4 {Not fearing any ghosts.} (8... Bxd6 9. bxc5 Bxc5 10. Bb2 f6 11. c3 O-O 12. d4 $11 {Certic, B (2376) -Zmijanac,D (2126) Belgrade-chT Quality 2018  (11.3) 0-1}) 9. d4 exd4 10. Re1 Bxd6 11. Bb5+ Be6 12. Ng5 Qd7 $17 * 

