{[%evp 0,26,38,28,41,51,68,76,85,60,46,26,33,8,30,11,70,32,55,-2,26,-27,30,-51, 7,-14,3,3,-12]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Be2 {This modest move leads to more interesting play than the manoeuvre Bc4-e2. The point is that the knight on d5 remains exposed.} Nc6 5. O-O d6 {The simplest way of fight9ing against White's space advantage.} ({The slightly adventurous} 5... Nf4 $5 $146 {was never tried. Black risks falling behind in development, but his position may be playable.} 6. d4 (6. Bb5 Ng6) 6... Nxe2+ 7. Qxe2 cxd4 8. Na3 g6 9. Bf4 Bg7 10. Nb5 O-O {Despite his space advantage and better development, White does not have clear ways of proving his advantage. Black is very solid and the light-squared bishop will emerge into play with considerable force.}) 6. exd6 ( 6. Bb5 $5 $146 Bd7 7. exd6 e6 8. Nc3 Nf6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qf3 Qc7 $11 14. Nb5 $5 Bxh2+ 15. Kh1 Qb7 16. Nxa7 Rxa7 17. Kxh2 h5 $13) (6. d4 {does not promise much, either.} cxd4 7. exd6 e6 8. Nxd4 Bxd6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. c4 Ne7 11. Bf3 O-O $11 {Staben,T (1916) -Pruesse,H (2038) Mecklenburg VP LL 0203 2002 (4.7) 0-1 The weakness on d4 compensates for that on c6.}) 6... e5 {The most ambitious approach. Black gains space and prepares to capture on d6 with a constructive developing move.} (6... e6 {is a bit passive.} 7. c4 Nf6 8. d4 Bxd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nc3 $14 {with freer play for White, who has scored quite well in practice.}) 7. Nc3 (7. b4 $6 {is once again ineffective/} cxb4 (7... Bxd6 $5 8. bxc5 Bxc5 9. Nxe5 Qf6 $15) 8. c4 $1 ( 8. d4 exd4 9. c4 bxc3 10. Bc4 {Basman,M-Sherman,D Guardian Islington op 1973  (6) 0-1} Qxd6 11. Nxd4 c2 12. Nxc2 Be6 $17) 8... bxc3 9. dxc3 Qxd6 10. Qb3 Be6 11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qa6 Rb6 13. Qa4 Be7 $11) ({One has to be aware of moves like}  7. d4 $5 exd4 $1 (7... cxd4 $2 8. c4 Nf6 9. c5 $18) 8. Re1 (8. c3 Bxd6 9. cxd4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxh2+ $5 11. Kxh2 Qh4+ 12. Kg1 Qxd4 $11) 8... Qxd6 9. Bc4+ Be7 10. Ng5 O-O 11. Nxh7 Re8 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5] Planning ...Bf5.} 12. Qh5 Be6 $17 { Black is much better developed and White does not have a real attack.} 13. Ng5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 Ndb4 15. Bxe6 Rxe6 $19) 7... Nxc3 {The simplest.} (7... Be6 { offers White dynamic ideas, even though the position should remain equal objectively.} 8. Ne4 Bxd6 9. Nfg5 Bf5 10. Bc4 Be7 11. d4 Bxe4 (11... cxd4 12. Qf3 $14) 12. Nxe4 Nb6 13. Bxf7+ Kxf7 14. Qf3+ Ke8 15. dxc5 Nd7 16. b4 $44 Nxb4 $2 17. Bg5 $40) 8. dxc3 {Aiming for rapid development and hoping to use the weakness of the square on d5. The knight is far from that square, though.} (8. bxc3 Bxd6 9. d4 O-O $5 $11) 8... Bxd6 9. Nd2 {The most consistent continuation, transferring the knight closer to d5.} (9. Ng5 Be7 10. Qxd8+ Nxd8 11. Bb5+ Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Rd1+ Kc6 14. Ne4 Ne6 15. b3 Rhd8 $15 {Pedrotti,L (1801) -Burani,E (1932) Arco op 33rd 2011 (6) 0-1}) 9... O-O 10. Nc4 Bc7 11. f4 ({ The attempt to invade d5 is not crowned by success:} 11. Ne3 Be6 12. c4 Nd4 $15 13. c3 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Qh4 15. Nd5 Bd6 $15) (11. Qxd8 {is another safe line for White.} Rxd8 12. Be3 b6 13. a4 f5 14. f3 Be6 $11) 11... exf4 12. Bxf4 Bxf4 13. Rxf4 Be6 $11 * 

