1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 ({In later comments, I will refer to this move order:} 2... e6 3. b3 Nc6 4. Bb2 Nf6 5. e5 Nd5 {This position offers White better chances for an advantage than the bishop's development to b2 in our line.}) 3. e5 Nd5 4. b3 {Developing the bishop to b2 is one of the possible closed Sicilian systems. In the line above, ...e7-e6 is a small commitment, allowing White to hope for something. With our move order, we can stay flexible.} Nc6 5. Bb2 g6 { The fight gravitates around the pawn on e5. By developing the bishop to g7, Black will not only increase his pressure on e5 but also pin the pawn, to make ...d7-d6 effective.} 6. Ng5 {An aggressive continuation.} (6. Bb5 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nf4 $5 {Preparing the knight's transfer to e6.} 9. Bxc6 (9. Nc3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 cxd4 11. Ne2 Bxe5 12. Nxf4 Bxf4 13. Bxd4 d5 $11) (9. h3 f6 10. exf6 Bxf6 11. Bxf6 Rxf6 $15) 9... dxc6 10. h3 {Useful for preventing ...Bg4, this also offers Black a target and wastes a tempo, too..} (10. Nc3 Bg4 11. Re4 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Ne6 $11) (10. d3 f5 11. exf6 exf6 $11 12. Nc3 $6 Bg4 $1 13. h3 Bh5 $17 ) 10... f5 {Neutralising White's space advantage.} (10... Bf5 11. Nc3 Qd7 12. Ne2 $14 {Kapengut,A-Mochalov,E Minsk Sokolsky Memorial-04 1973 1-0 This game actually featured the Rossolimo move order.}) 11. exf6 (11. Nc3 Ne6 $11 { with a perfect blockade.}) 11... Bxf6 $1 (11... exf6 12. Nc3 {offers White some chances.}) 12. Bxf6 Rxf6 13. Re3 (13. Nc3 Bxh3 14. Ne4 Nxg2 15. Nxf6+ exf6 16. Re4 Qd6 $11) (13. Ng5 Qf8 14. Ne4 Bxh3 15. g3 Ng2 16. Rf1 Rf5 17. Nbc3 Qh6 18. f4 Raf8 $17) 13... Bxh3 14. gxh3 Nxh3+ 15. Kh2 $1 {Otherwise, ...Qd7 would yield Black a decisive attack.} (15. Kg2 Qd7 16. Qh1 Qg4+ 17. Kf1 Raf8 $19) ( 15. Kf1 Qd7 16. d3 Raf8 17. Nbd2 Qg4 $19) 15... Nxf2 (15... Nf4 16. Nc3 Qf8 17. Qh1 Rf5 18. Kg1 Rh5 19. Nh2 Qh6 20. Ne4 Rf8 $44) 16. Qg1 Qc7+ 17. Kg2 Ng4 18. Rd3 $1 {White needs to keep the knight defended.} (18. Re2 Raf8 $19) 18... Raf8 19. Nc3 Ne5 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 $44 {Black has three pawns for the knight and continuing initiative.}) (6. e6 $6 {only throws the space advantage away.} f6 $1 7. exd7+ Bxd7 8. Bc4 Nb6 9. Bd3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 e5 $15 {Stepanencu, N (2334) -Gevorgyan,M (2218) Titled Tuesday intern op 07th Dec blitz 2021 (9) 0-1}) (6. c4 Nf4 $1 {On its way to e6, the knight keeps the a5-d8 diagonal clear for the queen.} (6... Nc7 7. d4 $11) 7. e6 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Qa5+ $17) 7... f6 $17 8. exd7+ $6 Qxd7 $1 9. Qc2 Nb4 $19 {Dragojlovic,A (2335) -Vukovic, Z (2435) YUG-chT Cup Becici 1994 0-1}) (6. Bc4 {is examined in Line 17.}) 6... Bg7 7. Nxf7 $5 {One of the two possible aggressive continuations. Without them, the knight's incursion to g5 would make no sense.} (7. Qf3 {is the main alternative.} O-O $1 8. Qxd5 (8. Qh3 h6 9. Nf3 d6 $19) 8... e6 9. Qxc5 (9. Qe4 Qxg5 10. f4 Qd8 11. g3 d6 $17) 9... Qxg5 {Black is better developed already and has good compensation for the pawn.} 10. Qe3 (10. d4 $2 d6 $3 11. Qxd6 Rd8 12. Qc5 Nxd4 13. Bxd4 Qc1+ 14. Ke2 b6 15. Qc4 Ba6 16. Qxa6 Rxd4 $19) (10. h4 Qf4 $11 {does not change much.} 11. d4 $2 d6 $1 12. Qxd6 Rd8 13. Qc5 Nxd4 $19) 10... Qxe3+ 11. fxe3 (11. dxe3 Nxe5 $11 12. f4 $2 Nf3+ 13. gxf3 Bxb2 $19) 11... Nxe5 12. Nc3 b6 (12... d5 $11) 13. Ba3 Rd8 14. Be2 f5 15. Nb5 {Mueller,B-Cook, P DESC SE251 email 2015 1-0} Bb7 16. O-O Nf7 17. Rac1 Bc6 $11) 7... Kxf7 8. Qf3+ Nf6 9. exf6 Bxf6 $1 10. Bd3 $5 $146 (10. Bxf6 $6 exf6 11. Qd5+ $6 (11. Bc4+ Kg7 12. O-O Nd4 13. Qd1 d5 14. Be2 Re8 15. Bf3 Bf5 $17 {Ladron de Guevara Pinto,P (2318) -Bjerre,J (2076) Lorca op 4th 2015 (4) 0-1}) 11... Kg7 12. Qxc5 Re8+ 13. Kd1 (13. Be2 d6 14. Qc3 Qe7 15. Qe3 Nd4 $19) 13... d6 14. Qc3 Qb6 15. Qg3 Bf5 16. Nc3 Nb4 17. Rc1 Rac8 $19 {Birnboim,N (2349) -Porat,S (2431) ISR-ch Ramat Aviv 2004 (2) 0-1}) 10... d5 11. Bxf6 exf6 12. O-O Ne5 13. Qf4 h5 14. h4 Qd6 $11 * 

