{[%evp 0,38,19,19,56,56,87,85,85,30,26,14,43,28,34,2,42,-18,-7,2,5,-14,10,11, 16,-18,0,-5,18,-6,-6,-10,-10,-11,-26,-15,-13,-16,-15,9,-24]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. g3 {This apparently inoffensive move is not without a certain amount of poison. White prevents ...Nf4, develops harmoniously and puts some latent pressure on the central knight, without committing himself yet.} Nc6 5. Bg2 g6 {I like this flexible move, preparing to complete the development before breaking in the centre.} (5... d6 {is much more popular, but I am sceptical about entering a reversed King's Indian structure. In similar lines with Be2, things were fine for Black, but the bishop's pressure along the long diagonal and in particular on the central knight may turn Black's position a bit unstable.} 6. exd6 Qxd6 (6... e5 7. d4 $1 $146 {is an improved version of the same pawn break with the bishop on e2.}) 7. O-O e5 (7... Bg4 8. h3 Bh5 9. d4 Nxd4 $6 10. g4 Bg6 11. Nxd4 cxd4 12. Na3 $14) 8. Re1 Be7 9. Na3 f6 (9... Nb6 10. Nb5 Qd7 11. c3 a6 12. Na3 Qd6 13. d4 $36) 10. d4 cxd4 11. c3 $36) 6. O-O ( 6. Nc3 Nc7 (6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Bg7 8. Bf4 $14) 7. Ne4 Ne6 8. c3 d5 9. exd6 { Rossolimo,N-Sherwin,J USA-ch New York 1962 (11) 1/2-1/2} exd6 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 d5 12. Nc3 Bg7 13. O-O O-O {The structure is symmetrical but Black still has to solve the problem of developing his queen's bishop.} 14. Re1 {The best try.} (14. Be3 Nc7 15. h3 Bf5 16. Qd2 Be4 $11) 14... Nexd4 (14... Ncxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Be3 Nc6 17. Nxd5 Be6 18. h4 {may offer White some pressure.}) 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Bh6 (16. Nxd5 Be6 17. Nf4 Bf5 $11) 16... Bg7 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. Nxd5 Be6 {After exchanging the dark-squared bishops, Black disposes over more manoeuvring space. The endgames after an exchange on d5 are also safer, given that he keeps the queens on board.} 19. Rc1 (19. Nf4 Bf5 $11) 19... Rc8 20. Qd2 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 (21. Qxd5 Qf6 $1 $11) 21... Qd6 22. b3 Rfd8 23. Qb2+ Kg8 24. Red1 Qe7 $11) 6... Bg7 {As a result of g2-g3 and Bg2, the pawn on e5 is not hanging yet.} 7. Re1 {However, this is the most popular move, ensuring the absolute safety of the central pawn. The rook move is likely to be useful later anyway.} (7. c3 O-O 8. d4 cxd4 9. cxd4 d6 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. Bg5 h6 13. Be3 { Okhotnik,V (2359) -Deac,B (2625) Titled Tuesday intern op 30th June blitz 2020 (3) 0-1} Be6 $15) (7. d4 {does not have much of an independent value.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc7 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qe2 $146 (10. Re1 {transposes below.}) 10... Ba6 11. c4 Ne6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Bd2 $5 Qb8 14. Rfe1 Qxb2 15. Rab1 Qa3 16. Nb5 cxb5 17. cxb5 Nd4 18. Qc4 Bxb5 19. Qxd4 Rab8 20. Bb4 Qa4 21. Qd1 Qxd1 22. Rbxd1 Rfe8 $11 {/=/+. White has reasonable compensation for the pawn, but Black is not worse.} ) 7... O-O 8. d4 (8. Nc3 {helps Black to regroup properly.} Nc7 9. d3 Ne6 10. h4 h6 11. Bd2 d6 12. exd6 exd6 (12... Qxd6 $11) 13. Nd5 Nc7 14. Nxc7 Qxc7 15. Bc3 Nd4 (15... Bg4 $11) 16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Nd2 (17. Qd2 Be6 18. Re2 Rac8 19. Rae1 b5 $5 $11) 17... Be6 18. a4 Rac8 19. a5 d5 $17 {Adhiban,B (2655) -Mamedov, R (2709) Wch Blitz Riadh 2017 (8) 0-1}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc7 10. Nxc6 bxc6 { An interesting structure. Black should prepare ...d7-d6, after which he would have comfortable play.} 11. Nc3 (11. b3 Ne6 12. Bb2 Bb7 13. c4 d6 14. Qe2 Re8 15. Nd2 dxe5 16. Nf3 Nd4 $17 {Ozates,T (2309) -Baskakov,E (2228) Titled Tuesday intern op 12th Sep Early blitz 2023 (9) 0-1}) 11... Ne6 12. h4 Qa5 { Maybe a bit premature.} (12... Rb8 13. h5 Qc7 14. Qe2 d6 15. exd6 exd6 $11) ( 12... Qc7 13. Nb5 Qb6 14. c4 Bb7 15. Be3 c5 16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Qd5 Rab8 $11) 13. Bd2 Rb8 14. b3 Qc7 (14... Ba6 {Kramnik,V (2753) -Baskakov,E (2215) Titled Tuesday intern op 08th Aug Early blitz 2023 (8) 1/2-1/2} 15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Nf4 $16) 15. Qe2 d6 16. exd6 exd6 17. h5 Nd4 18. Qd1 gxh5 $5 19. Qxh5 Bf5 $11 * 

