{[%evp 0,34,19,19,56,56,79,79,57,13,13,31,34,18,18,40,24,42,20,25,62,58,91,24, 22,30,19,29,28,16,12,22,23,-7,-1,-23,5]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4 { If White intends to open the centre early, he should do it now, without driving the knight away. This will yield him an extra tempo on the next move.} cxd4 5. Qxd4 (5. c3 {transposes to the Alapin Sicilian.}) (5. Nxd4 {is adequately met with} Nc6 6. Nxc6 (6. Nf3 e6 7. c4 Nde7 8. Nc3 Ng6 9. Qe2 Qc7 { winning the pawn o0n e5 soon.}) (6. c4 Nc7 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Nc3 g6 {leads to a familiar picture.}) 6... dxc6 $11 {With this move order, this is the simplest.} (6... bxc6 {may transpose to earlier lines.}) 7. Nc3 {Sadly for White, the most reliable continuation. Otherwise, the black knight would be too strong.} ( 7. Bc4 Bf5 8. Nd2 e6 $15) (7. Bd3 Nb4 $11) (7. c4 Nb4 $15) 7... Nxc3 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. bxc3 g6 $5 $11) 5... e6 $1 {The best continuation. Black prepares ... d7-d6.} (5... Nc7 $2 {does not work now, since White did not spend time on moves like c2-c4.} 6. Nc3 $1 Nc6 7. Qe4 $16 d6 8. exd6 Qxd6 9. Bf4 $18) 6. Bc4 {One of the two ways of attacking d5.} ({The pseudo-active} 6. Bg5 {commits White too soon.} Qc7 7. c4 Nc6 8. Qe4 Bb4+ $1 $146 9. Nbd2 Nde7 10. a3 d5 $5 11. exd6 (11. cxd5 exd5 {opens the diagonal for the bishop on c8.} 12. Qe2 Ba5 13. b4 Bb6 14. Rc1 Qd8 $15) 11... Bxd6 12. b4 f5 13. Qc2 a5 14. b5 Ne5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11) (6. Bd3 {is a solid, but not challenging move.} Nc6 7. Qe4 d6 $11 8. O-O (8. exd6 Bxd6 9. O-O Nf6 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 Qc7 13. Nc3 a6 $11) 8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Bd7 11. Re1 Bc6 12. Qh5 g6 13. Qe5 Qf6 14. Qe2 Nf4 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. Bb5 Bg7 17. Bxc6+ bxc6 18. c3 O-O 19. Na3 Rfd8 20. Rad1 Rd5 21. g3 Qa4 $11 {Zelcic,R (2500) -Marangunic,S (2445) CRO-ch Slavonski Brod 1995 1/2-1/2}) (6. c4 {is best answered with the intermediate move} Nc6 7. Qe4 (7. Qd1 {is a bit passive and leaves the central pawn vulnerable.} Nde7 8. Nc3 Ng6 9. Qe2 Qc7 10. Bd2 a6 {Black can win the central pawn whenever he wants. White will not have more than some formal compensation.} 11. O-O-O Be7 $5 { Trying to prove that the threat is more powerful than its execution.} 12. Re1 b5 $5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Qb8 $15 {with strong initiative for the pawn, for instance} 15. Kb1 Ba6 16. a4 O-O 17. h4 h5 18. Rh3 Bxb5 19. Qxb5 Qc7 $17) (7. Qg4 f5 $1 $146 {Taking on f6 offers a narrower choice to the white queen than in the lines with Qe4.} 8. Qg3 Ndb4 9. Na3 d6 10. exd6 Qxd6 $11 {for instance} 11. Bf4 Nd3+ 12. Bxd3 Qxd3 13. Rd1 Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Qe4+ 15. Kf1 Qd3+ 16. Ke1 Qe4+ 17. Kf1 O-O $5 18. Bxb4 Nxb4 19. Qd6 a5 20. Rd4 Ra6 $11 21. Qe7 Nc6 22. Qxf8+ Kxf8 23. Rxe4 fxe4 24. Nd2 Nd4 25. Nxe4 Rb6 26. b3 a4 $36) 7... f5 8. exf6 (8. Qe2 Bb4+ $1 9. Bd2 Nf4 $1 10. Qe3 Bxd2+ 11. Nbxd2 Ng6 {The knight has reached this square with gain of time and the central pawn is in some danger.} 12. c5 O-O 13. Be2 b6 14. O-O bxc5 15. Qxc5 Qb6 16. Rfc1 Bb7 17. a3 {Sieweck,P (1953) -Weber,K (2113) Stuttgart-chA op 2015 (7) 1/2-1/2} Rfc8 $15) (8. Qc2 {looks like a more harmonious retreat, but leaves the pawn on e5 less well defended.} Nde7 {The knight could also jump to b4, of course.} 9. Bd2 Ng6 10. Bc3 { Neuschmied,S (2253) -Froewis,G (2434) AUT-ch Pinkafeld 2015 (6) 0-1} Qc7 11. Qe2 d6 12. exd6 Bxd6 $15) 8... Nxf6 9. Qc2 Bc5 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Be2 b5 $5 $146 ( 11... d5 12. cxd5 exd5 13. O-O {Packa,L (2220) -Slapak,Z (2205) SVK-chT2 9596 1995 1-0} Be6 $11) (11... b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Bg5 {Onoglu,A (1448) -Abdrakhmanov, D (1573) Uralsk op 2023 (9) 1-0} Ne7 14. Rad1 Nf5 $11) 12. cxb5 (12. Nxb5 Ng4 13. O-O Nxf2 14. Rxf2 Bb7 $44 {Because of the threats ...Ne5 or . ..a7-a6 followed by ...Nd4, Black has excellent compensation for the material.} 15. Qd2 $5 {The queen gets out of the knight's range. Retreating to d1 would run into . ..Qb6.} Ne5 16. Kh1 Ng4 17. Rf1 Bxf3 18. gxf3 {Otherwise, ...Nxh2 would win.} Nxh2 19. Kxh2 Qh4+ 20. Kg2 Rf6 21. Qg5 Rg6 22. Qxg6 hxg6 23. Bd2 $1 Kf7 24. Be1 $1 Qh6 25. Bg3 $1 Rh8 26. Rh1 $1 Qd2 $44) 12... Nb4 13. Qd1 Bb7 14. a3 Ng4 15. O-O $2 (15. Bg5 Bxf2+ 16. Kd2 Qxg5+ 17. Nxg5 Be3+ 18. Ke1 Bf2+ $11 19. Kf1 $2 Ne3#) 15... Qc7 16. g3 Bxf2+ 17. Rxf2 Qc5 18. Qf1 Nc2 19. Rb1 Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Rxf3 $19) 6... Nc6 7. Qe4 {The most active move, keeping e5 well defended, but exposing the queen a bit.} (7. Qd1 Nde7 (7... d6 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Bxd5 exd5 10. Nc3 O-O $11 {Besedina,M-Raskidina,Y RUS-chB U16 Girls 2009 (9) 0-1}) 8. O-O Ng6 9. Re1 Qc7 10. Qe2 Ncxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Bxe6 dxe6 13. Qxe5 Qxe5 14. Rxe5 Bd6 (14... Bd7 $15) 15. Re2 b6 $15 {Frenzel,H-Neukirch,D DDR U18-ch Ruhla 1957 (11) 0-1}) 7... d6 {I have chosen this as the main line because it is by far the most popular but also because it was Nimzowitsch' choice in this position.} ({With the white bishop out,} 7... f5 $2 {is comfortably met with} 8. Qe2 $16) ({However, the rare} 7... Nde7 {is worth considering. I might use it in my first game reaching this position. The plan is as usual to increase the pressure on e5. At the same time, it looks like asking White why he needed a bishop on c4. It is also a way of keeping the tension for a longer time, while the main line tends to lead to simplifications and equality.} 8. O-O (8. Bf4 Ng6 9. Bg3 f5 $1 10. Qe3 { Taking on f6 is impossible due to the fork ...d7-d5.} Qa5+ 11. c3 Bc5 12. Qd2 Be7 $17 {Vaisman,V-Ciocaltea,V ROM-ch29 Final 1965 (17) 1/2-1/2}) (8. Nc3 a6) 8... Ng6 9. Nc3 a6 10. h4 (10. a4 Qc7 11. Re1 b6 12. Bd3 Bb7 $15 {Severiukhina, Z (2267) -Kharmunova,N (2177) EU-ch U18 Girls 17th 2007 (5) 0-1}) (10. Bg5 Qc7 11. Rfe1 b5 12. Bd3 Bb7 $15) 10... b5 11. Bd3 b4 $11 12. Na4 (12. Ne2 Qc7 $11) (12. h5 bxc3 13. hxg6 hxg6 14. bxc3 Qc7 $13) 12... Qa5 $11) 8. O-O {The relatively best try to maintain some symbolic pressure.} (8. Bxd5 exd5 9. Qxd5 dxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nc3 {Vasilchuk,Y-Chistiakov,A URS-ch24 Semifinal 1956 0-1} Bf5 $17) ({Nimzowitsch' game mentioned above was also included with ample commentaries in the database dedicated to Aron.} 8. exd6 Nf6 9. Qe2 (9. Qh4 Bxd6 10. Nc3 Ne5 $1 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. O-O O-O 13. Bd3 Qd4 $1 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 $11 {Schlechter,C-Nimzowitsch,A San Sebastian Int Masters-02 1912 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 9... Bxd6 10. O-O Qc7 11. Nc3 a6 12. Bg5 b5 13. Bd3 Bb7 14. Rad1 Be7 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 O-O 17. Qe3 Bxg5 18. Nxg5 h6 19. Nf3 Rac8 20. c3 Rfd8 21. h3 Na5 {Shaposhnikov,E (2558) -Smirnov,A (2452) RUS-ch Higher League 61st 2008 (2) 1/ 2-1/2}) 8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Qc7 11. Bb5+ (11. Qe2 {allows Black to develop freely.} Nf6 12. Bg5 Be7 13. Nc3 a6 14. Rad1 O-O 15. Bd3 h6 16. Bh4 Bd7 17. Ne4 Nd5 18. Bg3 Nf4 (18... Qa5 $2 19. c4 Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Qe4 g6 22. Qxb7 {Matulovic,M (2510) -Lazic,D (2235) Kragujevac 1977 (6) 1-0}) 19. Qf3 (19. Nf6+ Bxf6 20. Qe4 Ne2+ 21. Qxe2 Qb6 $11) 19... g5 $13 20. Nxg5 hxg5 21. Bxf4 Qxf4 22. Qh5 f5 (22... Qh4 23. Bh7+ Kg7 24. Qxh4 gxh4 25. Rxd7 Bf6 26. Bd3 $14) 23. Qg6+ Kh8 $11 {with a draw by perpetual.} 24. Bc4 Bc8 {only delays the moment when WHite needs to start checking.}) 11... Bd7 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. c4 Nf6 {Maintaining the possibility of gaining a tempo with ...Bd6.} (13... Qc7 { helps White to retrieve his coordination, but is playable nonetheless.} 14. Qe2 Nf6 15. Nc3 a6 (15... Be7 16. Nb5 Qc6 $11) 16. Bg5 (16. Nd5 $1 $14) 16... Be7 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 (17... gxf6 $5 $11) 18. Nd5 Qd8 19. Rad1 O-O 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Rd7 b6 22. Rfd1 Rad8 23. g3 g6 {Karpov,A-Hug,W World U20-ch10 Preliminaries B 1969 (2) 1/2-1/2} 24. R7d6 $14) 14. Nc3 Bd6 15. Qe2 O-O 16. b3 Qc7 17. h3 { Sax,G (2600) -Baumbach,F (2330) BL2-Nord 9192 1991 1/2-1/2} (17. Nb5 Bxh2+ 18. Kh1 Qe5 $11) 17... a6 $11 * 

