{[%evp 0,74,19,19,58,57,67,65,65,87,64,64,109,67,86,66,95,88,103,70,96,73,66, 70,70,65,118,88,165,153,121,113,148,113,161,142,142,83,83,-19,-35,-40,-21,-14, 0,-67,-64,-83,-69,-123,-124,-120,-101,-128,-125,-125,-112,-301,-175,-207,-135, -147,-140,-314,-319,-320,-337,-391,-578,-646,-673,-895,-932,-29975,-29976, -29977,-29978]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 {This move was introduced in the early times of the Nimzowitsch system. Over the decades, it has never ceased to be the main continuation, as far as I know. White attacks the central knight with the most desirable developing move.} Nxc3 $6 {This natural move was Black's reaction in the first game ever reaching this position, but by now has been long known as insufficient. It clears the diagonal for the c1-bishop and the d-file for White's pressure on d6 and d7. After noticing that Duda has repeatedly played it in blitz and rapid games (not only over the Internet) , I have decided to make a brief survey based on his games. It may help the adventurous reader to get a feeling about how to make this position playable. I could not find ways to present it as a reliable repertoire line, though.} (4... e6) 5. dxc3 Nc6 ({Those familiar with my recent database on Aron Nimzowitsch may remember that he once played} 5... b6 $2 {Michell, R-Nimzowitsch,A Marianske Lazne Masters 1925 (12) 0-1} 6. e6 $1 $18 dxe6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Ne5 Ke8 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Nxd7 Nxd7 11. Bf4 e5 12. O-O-O f6 13. Bxd7+ {Petrosian,T-Grigoriev,N Tbilisi 1945 1-0}) 6. Bf4 ({The first game with 4.Nc3 continued} 6. Bc4 d6 (6... Qc7 7. Bf4 e6) 7. Bf4 dxe5 8. Nxe5 (8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Nxe5 e6 10. Bb5+ $18) 8... Qxd1+ 9. Rxd1 Nxe5 10. Bxe5 a6 11. Bc7 $16 { Alapin,S-Rubinstein,A All Russian Masters-02 1912 (3) 1-0}) 6... e6 {In all his games with this variation, Duda applied a rule enunciated by Nimzowitsch. If the centre is solid, one may attack on the wings, even if the purposes remain nebulous. More details about it are in the aforementioned database on Aron Nimzowitsch, published by Modern Chess. His game quoted above is a good example starting with a certain moment. Duda invariably plays ...h7-h6 in the early phase, thus provoking h2-h4. Later, he develops his queenside and aims at carrying out ...b5.} 7. Qd2 (7. Bd3 h6 8. h4 Qb6 {Played by Nimzowitsch himself in a similar position (see Line 22) , this aims at reaching one of two goals: either deprive White from the right to castle after Rb1, or weaken his queenside with b2-b3.} 9. Rb1 {Frankly speaking, this seems to me as the less adequate reaction.} (9. b3 Qc7) (9. Qc1 $5 {may be the most flexible move, preparing Nd2-c4.} Qc7 10. Qe3 Rb8 $6 11. Nd2 b5 12. Qg3 $1 $18 {folowed by Ne4.}) 9... Qc7 10. Bg3 b6 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Nd2 d5 $11 13. exd6 (13. Ba6 $4 { is wrong from a strategic point of view and on top it loses a pawn.} Bxa6 14. Qxa6 Nxe5 15. Qb5+ Qc6 16. Qe2 Nd7 $19 {Demchenko,A (2654) -Duda,J (2760) EU-ch Blitz Katowice 2021 (13) 0-1}) 13... Bxd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. O-O O-O $11) (7. Nd2 d5 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. Bxd6 $6 (9. Qf3 $1 O-O 10. O-O-O Bxf4 11. Qxf4 Qe7 12. Ne4 {White is very active.} e5 13. Qe3 b6 {Herbrechtsmeier,C (2264) -Bartsch,B (2260) GER-chA Seniors 29th 2017 (5) 1/2-1/2} 14. Bb5 $5 $16) 9... Qxd6 10. Ne4 Qe5 11. Qe2 f5 12. Ng5 Ke7 13. O-O-O Qxe2 14. Bxe2 h6 15. Nf3 { Rapport,R (2752) -Duda,J (2732) Berlin Armageddon Euro&Africa W 2023 (3.2) 1/ 2-1/2} Bd7 $11) (7. h4 h6 8. g3 {Not the best plan. The pressure along the long diagonal is less important than the control over the f1-a6 diagonal. White also wastes a tempo and deprives the queen of the square on g3.} b6 (8... Qb6 $5 9. Qc1 Qc7 10. Qe3 Rb8 11. a4 a6 12. Nd2 b5 {There is no Qg3 now to prepare Ne4.} 13. axb5 axb5 14. Bg2 Bb7 $132) 9. Bg2 Bb7 10. Qd3 Qc7 11. O-O-O Ne7 12. h5 c4 13. Qe2 b5 14. Rh4 Rb8 15. Bd2 Qa5 16. Kb1 Bd5 $6 (16... Bc6 17. a3 Qb6 $11 {followed by ... a7-a5.}) 17. Ne1 Rb6 $6 18. Bc1 Ra6 19. a3 Bc6 20. Rhd4 Nd5 21. Bxd5 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 $1 exd5 23. Rxd5 $18 {Nakamura,H (2754) -Duda, J (2729) Paris GCT rapid 2019 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 7... h6 8. h4 a6 {In this game, White played better than in the one mentioned in the next commentary. Duda applied more or less the same plan in both games.} (8... Qc7 9. O-O-O a6 10. Bd3 b5 11. Be4 Bb7 12. Qe3 Ne7 13. Kb1 c4 14. Rhe1 Bxe4 15. Qxe4 Qc6 $11 { Pavlidis,A (2539) -Duda,J (2693) EU-ch 18th Minsk 2017 (5) 0-1}) 9. c4 Qc7 ( 9... Qa5 10. c3 b5) 10. h5 b6 11. O-O-O Bb7 12. Be2 b5 (12... O-O-O 13. Kb1 Kb8 ) 13. Rh3 (13. cxb5 axb5 14. Bxb5 Rxa2 $17) (13. Kb1 $5) 13... Na5 $2 (13... Ne7 $5 14. Kb1 Bc6) 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Bxb5 $1 {Of course.} Bd5 16. a4 Qb7 17. Qe2 c4 18. Nd4 (18. Rxd5 Qxd5 (18... exd5 19. e6 $18) 19. Rh1 $1 Ra7 (19... Qb7 20. Rd1 Nc6 21. Qxc4 $18 {with two pawns for the exchange and crushing pressure.}) 20. Rd1 Qa8 21. Be3 Rb7 22. Nd4 $18 {[%cal Ge2g4] followed by Qg4.} ) 18... Bxg2 19. Nxe6 $6 (19. Rg3 Bd5 20. Bd2 Nc6 21. Bc3 $16) 19... fxe6 20. Bxd7+ Qxd7 21. Rxd7 Kxd7 $13 22. Rg3 Bd5 23. Bd2 Nc6 24. Bc3 Rxa4 $17 25. Qe3 Kc7 26. Qf4 Ra1+ 27. Kd2 Ra7 28. Qf7+ Kd8 29. Qf4 Kc8 30. Bd4 Rd7 31. c3 Nxd4 32. cxd4 Bb4+ 33. Kc2 Rf8 34. Qe3 Rdf7 35. f4 Rxf4 36. Rxg7 Rf2+ 37. Kb1 Rf1+ { Gavrilescu,D (2518) -Duda,J (2750) Warsaw Superbet Classic Blitz 2022 (8.2) 0-1 This survey will serve you either as inspiration or as a warning not to take on c3.} * 

