{[%evp 0,30,19,31,40,40,61,79,79,66,68,60,45,45,104,53,38,47,48,48,63,32,65,19, 41,2,0,-3,-3,3,-10,-23,-14]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 {This is the most popular continuation. As far as I know, it was never "sanctioned" by official theory, meaning that the whole system was regarded with a marked scepticism.} 5. Ne4 {This is the main alternative to the capture on d5 and it was recently used by Caruana. The knight takes the relatively weak dark squares under control. The minor alternatives are not dangerous.} (5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Be2 (6. d3 {transposes to Line 14.}) 6... Nc6 7. d3 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nb5 d6 9. Bg5 {Sinsuat,D (1955) -Pareschi,R (1988) FICGS rapid A 000203 email 2017 (1) 1/ 2-1/2} Qd7 {This is the human answer, avoiding the weakening of the kingside.} 10. Nbxd4 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 a6 12. exd6 Bxd6 $11) (7. O-O d6 8. exd6 Bxd6 {is likely to transpose after 9.d3, since} 9. d4 $2 cxd4 $17 10. Nxd4 $2 {loses to} Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Bxh2+ $1 $19) 7... d5 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. O-O (9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O $11) 9... O-O $11 10. Be3 (10. d4 $2 cxd4 $17 11. Nxd4 $2 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Bxh2+) (10. Ne4 $6 Be7 $15) 10... e5 11. a4 f5 12. a5 Nd7 $11) ( 5. d4 {is likely to transpose:} Nxc3 6. bxc3 d5 7. exd6 (7. Bd3 $6 {leads to some sort of Winawer French, in which Black has spoiled White's queenside structure without giving up the bishops' pair.} c4 8. Be2 Nc6 9. h4 Bd7 10. h5 h6 11. a4 Qa5 12. Bd2 O-O-O $15) 7... Bxd6 8. Bd3 Nd7 9. O-O O-O {Brookes,C  (2056) -Afek,Y (2298) Vlissingen HZ op 15th 2011 (4) 1-0 We have transposed to Line 5, for instance to the game}) (5. g3 {is rather modest.} Nc6 6. Bg2 d6 7. exd6 Bxd6 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 (9. Nxd5 exd5 10. d4 Bg4 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. h3 Bh5 13. c3 Re8 $11) (9. d3 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Be3 Bd7 12. Qd2 Qc7 13. Rfe1 Rad8 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16. Qe3 b6 17. Nd2 Ne7 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Qe5 Qxe5 20. Nxe5 Ba4 21. Re2 Nd5 {Reti,R-Rubinstein,A Goteborg SSK 40th Anniversary Group A 1920 (7) 0-1} 22. Re4 Be8 23. c4 $11) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 e5 $5 {Not the only good move.} (10... h6 11. Be3 Qa5 12. Nd2 {Garakov,M (2447) -Le,T (2542) Titled Tuesday intern op 30th May Early blitz 2023 (1) 0-1} Rd8 $11) 11. dxe5 ( 11. d5 Na5 $11) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Be3 Bxc3 14. Qxd8 Rxd8 15. Rab1 Be6 16. Rxb7 Bxa2 17. Rc7 Bd5 18. Rxc5 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Bb4 20. Rc4 a5 $11 { Harika,D (2509) -Jones,G (2647) Abu Dhabi op 23rd 2015 (2) 1/2-1/2}) ({The absolute main continuation} 5. Nxd5 exd5 {is examined in Lines 24 to 35.}) 5... f5 $5 {This is the adventurous continuation, considered unsatisfactory for Black until recently.} ({The more solid} 5... d6 {is examined in Line 23.}) 6. Nc3 $1 {This paradoxical move, apparently losing two tempi is the most challenging. After ...f7-f5, the threat Nxd5 is even stronger than before.} (6. exf6 Nxf6 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 8. d4 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Be7 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qd2 Nc6 12. O-O-O d5 13. Nb3 Bd7 14. Bc5 b6 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 16. f3 a5 $17 {Eisenbeiser,A  (2411) -Arnold,L (2378) Oberliga Baden 1011 2010 (5.3) 1-0}) 6... Nb4 $5 { This unusual knight jump is justified by the time wasted by the white knight. Black plans to recycle his knight via c6, possibly followed by ...Nd4 and ... N8c6.} (6... Nc6 $2 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. d4 Qb6 9. Bd3 $16) (6... Nxc3 $5 {remains a bit on the edge, but is not necessarily bad. After all, Black is two tempi up if compared with the line with 4...Nxc3?! This is how Caruana's recent game went, but his younger opponent did not seem aware of Nimzowitsch's plan.} 7. dxc3 (7. bxc3 Nc6 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. d4 Na5 11. Nd2 cxd4 12. cxd4 { Cladouras,P (2380) -Kummer,H (2300) Vienna op-B 1996 (5) 1-0} Rc8 $11) 7... Nc6 ({It is interesting to see the first game ever in which Black played ...Qb6 in this type of structure.} 7... Be7 8. Bf4 Qb6 {As we know, this is one important move in Duda's setup.} 9. b3 $6 Qc7 10. Bd3 b6 11. Qe2 c4 12. bxc4 Nc6 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rfe1 {Yates,F-Nimzowitsch,A Karlsbad-04 International Masters 1929 (5) 1-0} Na5 15. Nd4 O-O $13) 8. Bf4 Qb6 $1 (8... Qc7 $6 9. Bd3 b6 10. Qe2 a6 $6 {Losing too much time.} 11. O-O-O b5 12. g4 c4 13. Bxf5 $1 $16 exf5 14. gxf5 Bb7 15. Ng5 Ne7 16. Rhe1 Nxf5 17. Nf7 g6 18. Nxh8 Bg7 19. Nf7 { Caruana,F (2782) -Abdusattorov,N (2725) Julius Baer Rapid Div 1 L 2023 (2.1) 1-0}) 9. b3 (9. Qc1 Qc7 10. Bd3 Ne7 $132) (9. Rb1 Qc7 10. Qd2 b6 11. h4 Bb7 12. Rd1 Ne7 $11) 9... Qa5 10. h4 (10. Qd2 {Baric,M (1974) -Musovic,A (2254) Konjic op 12th 2023 (3) 0-1} Ne7 $11) 10... Qxc3+ 11. Bd2 Qb2 12. c3 Qa3 13. Bb5 Qa5 14. Bxc6 Qa6 $3 (14... bxc6 15. c4 {leaves Black with chronic weaknesses.}) ( 14... dxc6 15. c4 $16 {is similar. The bishop on c8 is doomed to eternal passivity.}) 15. Bd5 (15. Ba4 b5 16. Bxb5 Qxb5 17. c4 Qc6 18. Ba5 Bb7 {The pawn on c6 is missing if we compare it with the line above. This changes things quite a lot.}) 15... exd5 16. Bf4 Qe6 $1 (16... Qc6 17. O-O b6 18. e6 dxe6 19. Ne5 Qb7 20. Re1 Bd6 21. Qh5+ $16) 17. Ng5 Qc6 $1 18. e6 (18. O-O Be7 $13) 18... dxe6 19. Be5 Ke7 $5 $13 {followed by ...Qe8. I believe that 6... Nxc3 deserves no lesser attention than the main line 6...Nb4.}) 7. a3 (7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 N8c6 {solves Black's problems regarding the development.} 9. Nf3 ( 9. a3 Nxd4 10. axb4 Nc6 $13) (9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Be2 Qc7 11. Bf4 Be7 {Milliet,S  (2382) -Clarke,B (2475) Paris Barreau 3rd 2022 (8) 0-1} 12. h4 {Preventing ... g7-g5.} O-O 13. Qd2 a5 14. O-O Nd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Rac1 Ba6 $11) 9... Qa5 10. Qe2 (10. Bf4 Nd5 11. Bd2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Bb4 13. Qd2 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 15. bxc3 Ke7 $15 {Lavrencic,M (2335) -Makridis,D (2372) Balkan-chT U18 final 2022 (5.3) 0-1}) (10. a3 Nxe5 11. Be2 Nbc6 12. O-O Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 Be7 14. Bh5+ g6 15. Bf3 O-O {Perez Ponsa,F (2538) -Le,T (2542) Titled Tuesday intern op 08th Nov Early blitz 2022 (7) 0-1}) 10... Bc5 11. Kd1 Be7 12. Bd2 O-O 13. a3 Nd5 $11) (7. Bc4 {exposes the bishop to} a6 8. a3 N4c6 9. O-O b5 10. Ba2 Be7 11. Re1 O-O 12. d3 Bb7 $13 {Shimanov,A (2581) -Le,T (2542) Titled Tuesday intern op 04th Oct Early blitz 2022 (10) 0-1}) 7... N4c6 8. b4 $1 {This seems to be the only challenging plan.} (8. d3 Nd4 9. Nxd4 cxd4 10. Ne2 Nc6 11. f4 b5 12. g3 Bb7 13. Bg2 Qb6 14. O-O a5 15. Bd2 Bc5) 8... d6 (8... cxb4 9. Nb5 $1 bxa3 10. Rxa3 $5 $16 Bxa3 $2 11. Bxa3 $40) 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. Bc4 (10. bxc5 Bxc5 $11) (10. Nb5 { Semenova,E (2269) -Goltseva,E (2331) Khanty-Mansiysk TOP 28 Rapid GP (Women) 2023 (1) 1-0} Be7 11. bxc5 Bxc5 12. d4 Bb6 {Threatening to win the central pawn after ...a7-a6.} 13. Bf4 Ba5+ $1 14. c3 O-O 15. Qb3 a6 16. Nd6 b5 { Playing for a blockade while reinforcing the threat ...Bc7.} (16... Bc7 17. Nxc8 Bxf4 18. Nb6 $16) 17. Rd1 {Threatening d4-d5.} (17. Be2 Bc7 18. Nxc8 Bxf4) 17... Ne7 $1 (17... Bc7 18. d5 $1 $16) 18. Nxc8 Qxc8 19. Bd2 Ra7 {An elegant and effective way of developing the rook.} 20. Rc1 Rc7 21. Bd3 Nd5 22. c4 bxc4 23. Bxc4 Rb7 24. Qa2 Bxd2+ 25. Qxd2 (25. Kxd2 {defends the rook on c1, but leaves the king somewhat exposed, restricting White's active possibilities.} Qd8 $1 $13) 25... Rc7 26. Ne5 Nd7 27. O-O Nxe5 28. Bxd5 Nc4 29. Bxc4 Rxc4 $11 30. d5 Rd8 31. d6 Rd7 $11) 10... Nd4 11. Nb5 (11. bxc5 Bxc5 12. Nxd4 Bxd4 13. Qe2 {Daggupati,B (2494) -Le,T (2514) Philadelphia int op 15th 2022 (8) 0-1} O-O 14. Bxe6+ Bxe6 15. Qxe6+ Kh8 16. O-O Nc6 17. Rb1 Bb6 18. Nb5 Rf6 19. Qb3 Qd7 $44) 11... Nbc6 {The position is highly unusual, but this is what adventurous play is all about.} 12. Nxd6+ {A World champion's choice.} (12. Nfxd4 {is the main alternative.} cxd4 13. Nxd6+ Qxd6 14. O-O O-O 15. Bb2 Ne5 16. Bb3 Ng6 { This is the only moment when the engine slightly disapproves with White's play, suggesting} 17. f4 $5 (17. Re1 a5 18. c3 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Bxa1 Nf4 21. Qf3 Bd7 22. cxd4 Qxb4 $13 {Volokitin,A (2677) -Kravtsiv,M (2604) UKR-ch 90th Kharkov 2021 (8) 1-0}) 17... Nxf4 18. Qf3 g5 $1 {It is essential to maintain the knight on f4 so that after Qf2 the threat of taking on d4 was not real due to the fork on e2. The knight also covers the f-file, securing the pawn on f5.} (18... Ng6 19. Qf2 Rd8 20. Qxf5 $16) 19. Rae1 a5 {The position remains unusual and unclear. White has compensation for the pawn, but Black is not without chances, either.}) 12... Qxd6 13. O-O O-O 14. Bb2 {This should have made things somewhat easier for Black.} (14. Ba2 $5 {may be a bit more challenging.} cxb4 15. axb4 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Nd4 17. Qd3 $1 (17. Qd1 f4 $132) 17... Qe5 $1 18. Rb1 (18. c3 {offers Black unexpected dynamic resources.} Ne2+ 19. Kh1 Qe4 20. Qxe4 fxe4 21. Bb1 e3 22. dxe3 Nxc3 23. Bd3 Bd7 24. Bb2 Bb5 $11) 18... Ne2+ 19. Kh1 Nxc1 20. Rbxc1 Qf6 21. c3 Kh8 22. f4 (22. Rce1 a5 23. b5 e5) 22... Rd8 23. Qe2 b5 $5 24. d4 a5 $11) 14... cxb4 $1 (14... b5 $2 {Ding,L (2808) -Le,T (2542) Chess.com Rapid CGC KO 2022 (1.1) 0-1} 15. bxc5 Qxc5 16. Ba2 $16) 15. axb4 Qxb4 $13 {We can conclude that 5...f5 is playable for at least two reasons. It remains adventurous, of course, but this is part of Black's approach to the whole system.} * 

