1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Ne4 d6 {This is the most solid continuation. In fact, in the main variation, play may become double-edged, so it is not only about defending or struggling for equality.} 6. exd6 (6. Bb5+ { is premature since it allows} Bd7 $1 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. O-O Nc6 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. d4 (10. Nxd6+ Qxd6 11. d4 Rd8 12. dxc5 Qxc5 13. Qe2 O-O {[%cal Ge6e5]} 14. Bg5 Rd7 15. c4 Nde7 16. Rad1 Rfd8 $11) 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 Be7 12. Bg5 {Tari,A  (2653) -Asadli,V (2579) EU-ch 22nd Terme Catez 2022 (9) 1/2-1/2} f6 $11) (6. c4 {is comfortably met with} Nb4 7. exd6 (7. d4 dxe5 8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. axb4 Bxe4 12. Nd2 Bb7 13. b5 a6 14. h4 Nd7 15. f4 f6 16. exf6 gxf6 17. Rh3 Bd6 18. Rha3 a5 19. g3 f5 $11) 7... Bxd6 8. a3 N4c6 9. d3 Be7 10. g3 O-O 11. Bg2 Qd7 (11... e5 $11) 12. Be3 b6 13. d4 cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. Bxd4 Nc6 17. Bc3 Bb7 $11 {Kravec,P (2085) -Kopnicky,V (2093) SVK-chT2D 1617 2016 (10.1) 0-1}) 6... Bxd6 7. Bb5+ {Now is a better moment for delivering this check.} (7. Nxd6+ Qxd6 8. d4 Nc6 9. dxc5 Qxc5 {Black's centralisation and better development compensates for White's bishops' pair.} 10. a3 O-O 11. Bd3 {Huerter,H (2264) -Stelmaszyk,N (2387) Titled Tuesday intern op 14th Mar Late blitz 2023 (8) 0-1} e5 12. O-O Rd8 13. Re1 Nf6 14. b4 Qd5 15. Bb2 Bg4 16. Be2 Qe6 17. Qc1 Rac8 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 b6 {Planning ... Nd4.} 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Bxe5 Qxc2 22. Qf4 Qg6 23. Rad1 h6 $11) (7. d4 O-O 8. dxc5 {Golubev,M (2479) -Okhotnik,V (2351) Golubev Cup Chess.com INT blitz 2018 (7) 0-1} (8. Nxc5 e5 $36) 8... Be7 $1 (8... Bxc5 9. Nxc5 Qa5+ 10. c3 Qxc5 11. Bd3 {Stetsko,L (2209) -Melnikova,D (1867) Minsk Amateur op 2018 (5) 1-0}) 9. c3 Nd7 $11 10. b4 $6 N7f6 11. Nfd2 a5 $15) 7... Nc6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. d3 O-O 10. O-O e5 {We are following another game of Caruana. Black has double pawns, but is better developed and has more space. Symptomatically, White had to go for a double-edged position as his best chance for an advantage.} 11. h3 (11. Re1 Bg4 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 f5 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. Bd2 Rae8 {Another interesting position featuring the confrontation between space and development on one side and the best structure on the other one. Chances are about even.} 16. Re2 Re6 17. Rae1 h6 18. a3 g5 19. g3 f4 20. g4 Rfe8 21. c4 Ne7 22. Bc3 Ng6 23. Qe4 Nh4 24. f3 Rd8 25. Rd1 Re7 26. Kf2 (26. b4 Qg6 27. Kf2 Qxe4 28. Rxe4 Red7 29. Ke2 Nxf3 $11) 26... Qg6 27. Red2 Red7 $5 28. Bxe5 (28. Qxe5 Re8 29. Qxc5 Rde7 $19) (28. Qxg6+ Nxg6 29. b4 Kf7 30. bxc5 Rb7 $11) 28... Re8 29. Qxg6+ Nxg6 30. Bc3 Nh4 31. d4 Re3 $13) ({An old game went} 11. Nfd2 Bc7 $1 12. Nc4 f5 $1 13. Nxc5 {In the old days, such pawn sacrifices were part of the normality. In this case, it yields Black fantastic compensation due to his attacking chances.} Qe7 $5 ({The game went} 13... Qh4 14. Qe1 e4 {when White stayed out of troubles with} 15. f4 $1 Qxe1 16. Rxe1 {, without claiming an advantage, though.} Nb4 17. Re2 Bb6 18. Be3 Nd5 19. Bd4 exd3 20. cxd3 Nxf4 21. Re7 Bxc5 22. Bxc5 Nxd3 23. Bxa7 Ba6 24. Bd4 Rf7 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Ne5+ Nxe5 27. Bxe5 Re8 28. Bc3 Re2 $11 {Suetin,A-Kozomara,V Sarajevo-08 1965 (4) 1/2-1/2}) 14. Nb3 (14. d4 e4 15. Re1 Be6 {[%cal Ga8e8,Ge6f7]} 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. Qe2 Rae8 18. Bd2 Rf6 $36) 14... e4 15. Qh5 (15. Bd2 f4 $19) (15. Re1 Qh4 $19 16. h3 Rf6) 15... Ba6 $15) 11... f6 12. Nfd2 Be7 ({Had Black known the old game, he would have played} 12... Bc7 13. Nxc5 f5 $44 {, of course.}) 13. Nc4 Be6 $5 (13... Bf5 14. Re1 Qd7 15. b3 Nc7 $6 {Black is obviously concerned about maintaining the material equality, causing him to land in a passive position.} 16. Ng3 (16. f4 $14) 16... Bg6 17. Qg4 Qxg4 (17... Ne6 $5 $14) 18. hxg4 Ne6 19. Be3 $14 {Caruana,F (2792) -Dreev, A (2623) Chess.com Rapid Wk2 KO 2022 (1.1) 1/2-1/2 with enduring pressure.}) 14. Re1 Qc7 15. b3 Rae8 16. Ba3 Nf4 17. Bxc5 Bxc5 18. Nxc5 Bd5 19. f3 Bxc4 20. bxc4 Qb6 21. d4 Rd8 $13 * 

