{[%evp 0,34,29,6,45,45,61,61,61,61,61,69,73,14,4,0,-1,-2,-2,-2,0,0,0,0,0,0,18, -1,10,-36,-22,-22,-6,0,0,-36,-22]} 1. e4 ({When reaching the position after 5 moves, it makes sense to compare the structure with that arising after} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. d5 Ne5 9. Nxe5 dxe5 {Kramer,H-Euwe,M Hoogovens Beverwijk 1953 (11) 1/2-1/2 Here, too, Black has awkwardly looking double pawns in the centre. And e2-e4 may be answered with ...e7-e6, the mirrored version of d2-d4 answered by ...a7-a6 soon, as in some of the lines below. This system is much "younger" than the Nimzowitsch Sicilian, having been played for the first time by Euwe in 1953.}) 1... c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 {This is one of the main positions making the Nimzowitsch Sicilian an adventurous opening, the same as the Dutch system mentioned above. It is interesting to remark, though, that this precise position is by a few years "older" than the variation itself! Nimzowitsch introduced his system in 1911, but before that, there had been a game in 1908, transposing after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e5 Nd5 5.Nxd5 exd5!! The game is mentioned in the comments to Line 27. The position after three moves is part of our repertoire and was examined earlier. Before moving on, we need to evaluate the position abstractly. From a strategic point of view, Black's pawns on d5 and c5 ensure him certain space and control in the centre. He will not have double pawns for the rest of the game, since ...d7-d6 may happen shortly. On the other hand, the pawn on d5 is vulnerable in the short term. To use this circumstance, White needs to make a few important commitments, such as advancing with the queen on an exposed position before completing the development and giving up the right to get castled! The solid positional approach may lead to consistent play but hardly promises an advantage.} 6. c4 {This brutal attempt at questioning Black's stability in the centre is ineffective.} (6. b4 $6 {is a dubious gambit.} cxb4 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. Bd3 {Mincsovics,M (2223) -Szabo,J (2176) HUN-chT2 Breyer 1011 2010 (1.3) 1-0} Bc5 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 d6 11. exd6 Qxd6 $17) (6. c3 {If played to attack the pawn on d5 on the next move, this is not a dangerous plan.} Nc6 7. Qb3 $6 ({The more consistent} 7. d4 {transposes to Line 28.}) 7... d6 8. Bb5 ({The less ambitious} 8. Qxd5 {is preferable.} dxe5 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Bc4 f6 11. O-O Kc7 12. d4 {Otherwise, Black would consolidate his space advantage.} cxd4 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Bf4+ Bd6 15. Bxd6+ Kxd6 16. Bb5 Rd8 17. Rfd1 Bg4 18. Bxc6 Kxc6 19. Nxd4+ Kb6 $11) 8... Be6 9. d4 {Colmenares,A (2203) -Orsenigo,D (1872) Lugano New op 1st 2007 (4) 1-0} a6 $1 10. Bxc6+ (10. Be2 dxe5 11. Nxe5 cxd4 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. cxd4 Bd6 $15 {We will have the same structure later, but here, the queen is exposed on b3 and the kingside will be under certain pressure after .. .Qh4.}) 10... bxc6 11. O-O dxe5 12. Nxe5 f6 13. Nf3 Qd7 $5 {The most flexible continuation.} (13... c4 $5 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Re1+ Kf7 16. Bf4 g5 17. Bg3 h5 18. h4 g4 19. Nd2 c5 20. Qc2 cxd4 21. cxd4 Qb6 22. Nf1 Bh6 $11) 14. Re1 Kf7 { Planning ...Bg4.} 15. h3 c4 16. Qa4 Bd6 17. b3 cxb3 18. axb3 Rhe8 19. Bd2 a5 20. c4 Bc7 $15) (6. g3 {is examined in Line 25.}) (6. Be2 {is covered in Line 26.}) ({The main continuation is} 6. d4 {and we will deal with it in Lines 27 to 35.}) 6... d4 {The most ambitious move, gaining space in the centre.} (6... dxc4 {is good for equalising, though.} 7. Bxc4 d5 8. exd6 Bxd6 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 Nc6 $11) 7. Bd3 {Aiming for rapid kingside development, but leaving the other bishop passive for quite a while.} (7. b4 {is less threatening than it looks.} d6 8. exd6 (8. bxc5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Bxc5 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O Qd6 $15) (8. Qe2 {Freire,D (1810) -Ziechaus,L (2106) VW-Cup13 Gr02 email 2021 0-1} Be6 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. bxc5 O-O $3 11. cxd6 Re8 12. Ne5 f6 13. Qd1 Nd7 $1 14. Be2 Nxe5 15. O-O d3 16. Bh5 g6 17. Bf3 Qxd6 $15) 8... Bxd6 9. bxc5 Bxc5 (9... O-O $1 { threatening ...Re8+ followed by ...d4-d3 is stronger.} 10. d3 Bxc5 11. Be2 Nc6 12. O-O Bf5 $15) 10. Bd3 (10. Qe2+ Kf8 $1 $146 11. d3 Bg4 12. Rb1 Nc6 13. Rxb7 Bb4+ 14. Bd2 Bc3 $15) 10... O-O 11. O-O Nc6 $11 {Abarca Gonzalez,N (2409) -Kantans,T (2508) Titled Tuesday intern op 4th June blitz 2019 (5) 0-1} 12. Be4 $5) 7... d6 8. O-O Nc6 9. Re1 Be7 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Be4 (11. Ng5 {Cruz,J (2347) -Le,T (2542) Titled Tuesday intern op 27th Sep Early blitz 2022 (6) 0-1 is a premature attack, since part of White's queenside is undeveloped.} O-O $3 12. Nxh7 (12. Qh5 h6 13. Ne4 Qf4 $17) (12. Bxh7+ Kh8 13. Qh5 Bxg5 $19 {Black wins a piece since any discovered check can be parried with ...Bh6.}) 12... Rd8 13. Be4 g6 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qf3 f6 16. Rxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxf6+ Kg7 18. Ne4 Bf5 { Strategically, White is doing great, but his huge delay in development leaves him struggling.} 19. d3 Re8 20. Ng3 Qe1+ 21. Nf1 Qe2 $17) 11... O-O 12. d3 (12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. d3 {looks appealing for White, but his poor development once again prevents him from enjoying his better structure.} Bd8 {Preparing ...Bc7 and ...Bg4.} 14. Bg5 f6 15. Bh4 Bf5 16. Bg3 Qd7 17. Qc2 Ba5 {We notice that the bishop can be useful in more than one way.} 18. Re2 Rfe8 $11) 12... h6 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. h3 (14. Nd2 $5 $11) 14... Bf5 15. Bf4 Qxf4 16. Rxe7 Rfe8 17. Re2 Rab8 $11 {Perez,M (2396) -Baskakov,E (2215) Titled Tuesday intern op 20th Jun Late blitz 2023 (4) 0-1} * 

