{[%evp 0,48,12,25,56,66,79,75,87,72,92,71,84,13,-15,14,10,-31,-8,0,-8,-14,-3, -6,-12,-23,-7,1,13,7,-4,-6,-19,-40,2,-9,-6,-28,-9,-9,15,4,4,1,1,0,6,0,0,-10,20] } 1. e4 c5 ({In the comments to move 10, I will refer to the structure arising after one of the French main lines:} 1... e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 c5 4. exd5 exd5 5. Ngf3 Nc6 6. Bb5 Bd6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. O-O Nge7 9. Nb3 Bd6) 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. g3 {Typical for the Closed Sicilian, this is time-consuming and allows Black to reach a comfortable version of the Isolani.} Nc6 7. Bg2 d6 8. exd6 (8. d4 dxe5 9. Nxe5 (9. dxe5 $6 {leads to a structure where the bishop is not optimally placed on g2.} Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. c3 Be6 12. Qe2 h6 13. Bf4 {Botvinnik,I (2355) -Bruk,O (2430) ISR-chT Israel 2015 (11.6) 1/ 2-1/2} Qd7 14. Rad1 Rad8 $17) 9... Be7 (9... Nxd4 {is likely to yield White a light initiative.} 10. O-O Bd6 {Licznerski,L (2442) -Baskakov,E (2215) Titled Tuesday intern op 18th Oct Late blitz 2022 (11) 0-1} 11. Nf3 Nxf3+ 12. Bxf3 O-O 13. Bxd5 $14 {/=}) 10. O-O cxd4 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Qxd4 O-O 13. Be3 a5 $5 $11) 8... Bxd6 9. O-O O-O 10. d4 {This is the first time we come across this structure, typical for the French Isolani. One possible way to reach it is mentioned in my comments to move 1. The bishop's presence on g2 is not positive, but otherwise, the following comments refer to all the positions reaching this structure. White's queen's knight and Black's king's knight are missing, if we compare to the French Isolani lines. Since Black's kin's knight cannot contribute to the fight for the d4-square, we can infer that in the current situation, White will have bigger problems to establish a blockade on d4. Moreover, in the French lines, the knight is a bit passive on e7, while the white one could gain a tempo with Nb3 and later jump to d4.} Bg4 {The most frequent and natural move.} (10... Bf5 $5 11. Be3 {Martinez Duany,L (2507) -Fernandez Fuentes,F (2172) Sitges op 35th 2009 (2) 1/2-1/2} b6 12. c3 Be4 $11) 11. dxc5 (11. h3 {may transpose but also have independent value.} Bh5 (11... Bxf3 $5 $146 12. Bxf3 (12. Qxf3 Nxd4 13. Qd3 Re8 14. Be3 Qc7 15. c3 Ne2+ $1 16. Qxe2 d4 $11) 12... Nxd4 13. Bg2 (13. Bxd5 Bxg3 $15) 13... Re8 14. Be3 (14. c3 $2 Ne2+ $17) 14... Nf5 $11) 12. Be3 {Donchenko,A (2567) -Christiansen,J (2468) Wch U20 56th 2017 (10) 1/2-1/2} (12. g4 Bg6 13. Be3 c4 $15) (12. dxc5 Bxc5 { transposes to the main line.}) 12... cxd4 (12... c4 $11) 13. Bxd4 Re8 14. Qd2 Bg6 15. Rfe1 Be4 $11) (11. Be3 cxd4 12. Bxd4 Re8 {is similar to the line above. }) 11... Bxc5 12. h3 Bh5 13. c3 Re8 {It appears that White has certain problems developing his queenside.} 14. Bf4 {The only available square, but an exposed one.} h6 {Reminding White that the bishop is not stable on f4.} (14... g5 $5 $146 15. g4 (15. Bxg5 Bxf3 16. Qd2 f6 $19) (15. Bc1 h6 $15) 15... Bxg4 16. hxg4 gxf4 17. Qd3 Ne5 18. Qf5 Qd7 $11 19. Qxf4 Ng6 20. Qh6 Re4 $15) 15. b4 (15. g4 {mainly helps Black to regroup.} Bg6 16. Qd2 $6 (16. Re1 Be4 17. Nd2 $5 $11) 16... Be4 $15 17. Rad1 (17. Bg3 Re6 18. Rfe1 Qf6 19. Qf4 Qe7 20. Qc7 Qe8 $15 21. Qxb7 Bb6 $15) 17... Qf6 $17 {Papp,P (2336) -Kantans,T (2501) EU-ch qual Online 2020 (2) 1/2-1/2}) 15... Bb6 16. a4 a6 17. Qd2 Bg6 18. Rad1 Be4 19. Rfe1 Qf6 $11 {Black has a perfect regrouping and faces no problems at all.} 20. Nh2 {White needs to untie himself a bit.} (20. Be3 $2 Bxf3 21. Bxf3 d4 $1 22. Bf4 dxc3 (22... g5 $1 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. a5 Ba7 25. Bc7 dxc3 26. Qc2 Rxe1+ 27. Rxe1 Bd4 $19) 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Qd7 Rd8 25. Qxb7 Rxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Qd4 27. Qc8+ Nd8 28. Be3 Qxd1+ 29. Kh2 Bxe3 {Gabrielian,A (2533) -Kantans,T (2468) Titled Tuesday intern Qual2 11th April blitz 2017 (4) 0-1}) 20... Rad8 21. Ng4 Qg6 22. a5 Ba7 23. Bc7 Rc8 24. Bb6 Bb8 $11 * 

