1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. Be2 {This is more natural and less time-consuming than 6.g3. However, it also offers Black an easy and pleasant game.} d6 7. O-O Nc6 {White has a choice concerning which structure to choose.} 8. d4 {By allowing the exchange on e5, White is heading for a structure typical for the Open Spanish.} (8. exd6 Bxd6 9. d4 {leads to the French Isolani structure.} O-O 10. Bg5 $5 $146 {deserves mentioning since the queen does not have the d6-square as in the similar line above.} (10. dxc5 Bxc5 {offers Black easy development.} 11. Bg5 Qd6 12. Bh4 f5 $5 (12... Be6 13. Bg3 Qd7 $11 {Macak,S (2470) -Stojic,D (2192) Sydney op Parramatta 2010 (6) 1-0} ) 13. c3 h6 $15 {and the bishop is in danger.}) (10. Be3 c4 $5 11. b3 $6 (11. Qd2 b5 $11) 11... c3 $1 $146 {This pawn ensures Black a considerable queenside space advantage and is not easy to attack.} 12. Qd3 (12. a3 Bf5 13. Qe1 $6 Rc8 $17) 12... Nb4 13. Qxc3 Bf5 14. Ne1 (14. Bd3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Bg4 16. Ne5 Bh5 17. g4 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Bxg4 $17) 14... Rc8 15. Qd2 Nxc2 16. Nxc2 Rxc2 17. Qd1 Qd7 $5 $15) 10... f6 11. dxc5 (11. Bh4 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Be5 $11) (11. Be3 c4 $11 { and the move ...f7-f6 tends to be useful.}) 11... Bxc5 12. Bf4 Bf5 13. c3 Be4 $11) (8. Re1 {aims at maintaining White's flexibility.} dxe5 $5 $146 {Black does not need to wait untill White will make his mind.} (8... Be7 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. d4 O-O {leads to a known position where White has the extra tempo Re1. This should not change the general evaluation of the position, but making a tempo as a present is not inspiring.}) ({The same goes for} 8... Be6 9. Bb5 Be7 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. d4 O-O 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Be3 {Now is when the extra tempo proves useful. It is suggestive, though, that Black does not have problems here, either.} Bxe3 14. Rxe3 Qb6 $11 15. Qd3 h6 16. c3 d4 $5 17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Qe2 Rac8 $44 {Trzeciak,R (2077) -Hild,H EU-ch SC-OR/173 email 2016 0-1}) 9. Nxe5 (9. Bb5 Bd6 10. Nxe5 O-O 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Bxc6 Bxh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qd6+ $11) 9... Be7 (9... Nxe5 $2 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Rxe5+ Be7 12. Rxd5 $18) 10. Bb5 (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. d3 O-O 12. Bf4 Bf6 $11) 10... Qb6 11. a4 $5 (11. Ba4 Be6 $11) 11... O-O $1 (11... Be6 12. Ra3 $5) 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {This is possible only with the bishop on b5, which is hanging now.} 13. Bxc6 Qxc6 14. Rxe7 Qf6 (14... Be6 15. d4 cxd4 16. Qxd4 Qxc2 $11) 15. Re1 Bd7 16. d3 Rfe8 $44) 8... dxe5 9. dxe5 Be7 {Black has comfortable play. He can develop his light-squared bishop wherever he wants and the pawn on d5 is easy to defend if given the case.} 10. Re1 (10. Bf4 {is premature.} g5 $1 $146 11. Be3 (11. Bg3 h5 12. h3 g4 13. hxg4 Bxg4 14. Re1 Qd7 $17) 11... d4 12. Bd2 h5 13. Ne1 Bf5 $15) 10... O-O 11. Bf4 Bf5 (11... Re8 12. Qd2 Bf8 13. Rad1 {Krayz,A (2346) -Kantans,T (2501) EU-ch qual Online 2020 (6) 0-1} Be6 $11) 12. c3 Qd7 $11 13. Qd2 Rad8 14. Bg5 Be4 15. Qf4 Rfe8 16. Bb5 Bxf3 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Bxc6 Qxc6 19. Qxf3 Qa6 $5 $11 * 

