{[%evp 0,71,19,31,52,52,78,73,63,66,56,56,56,61,87,71,71,72,72,83,136,42,64,39, 48,53,17,36,30,5,16,36,50,41,47,45,52,52,37,47,47,57,57,57,63,74,87,44,47,37, 54,44,36,35,38,38,39,25,36,42,42,51,51,38,51,36,33,36,32,33,48,49,47,25]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 {The by far most popular move and the most consistent, too.} Nc6 ({Things would be by far simpler for Black if} 6... d6 {worked out well. It was the move chosen by Black in the 1908 game mentioned above. It is playable, but tends to yield White a pleasant advantage.} 7. Bb5+ $1 {This move is available only after Black's last move, since otherwise, the bishop would be lost after ...Qa5+.} ({The old game went}  7. exd6 Bxd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Bb5+ {Too late to cause troubles.} Nc6 10. O-O O-O 11. h3 Bf5 12. Bd3 Bg6 13. Bg5 f6 14. Bf4 Be4 $11 {Howell,C-Ward,W Match/ Nation ENG-USA 1908 (1.6) 1/2-1/2 What can I say, quite a modern game, is it not?}) (7. Bg5 Qb6 8. dxc5 dxc5 9. Qxd5 Be6 10. Bb5+ Nc6 11. Qd3 h6 12. Bd2 { Yukhtman,J-Muhutdinov,M URS-ch25 Semifinal 1957 (5) 1/2-1/2} Rd8 13. Qe2 a6 14. Bd3 Qxb2 15. O-O Qa3 16. Rfb1 b5 17. Be4 Rc8) 7... Nc6 (7... Bd7 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. O-O Nc6 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Re1+ $16) 8. O-O (8. Qe2 $5 Be7 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. dxc5 Qxc5 11. Be3 Qd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rad1 Bg4 {Kveinys,A (2515) -Keuth,G  (2160) Weilburg NBG op 1995 (2) 1-0} 14. h3 $1 {In the game, WHite played Bc4 at once, which could have been met with ...d5-d4.} Bh5 15. Bc4 $14 d4 $2 { does not work now due to} 16. g4 Bg6 17. Nxd4 $18) 8... Be7 9. c4 $1 a6 10. Ba4 dxc4 11. d5 b5 12. dxc6 bxa4 13. exd6 Qxd6 14. Qxa4 $14 {Prins,L-Witkowski,S Olympiad-13 Final B 1958 (3) 1-0 Old theory already.}) 7. Bd3 {A similar approach as in Lines 25 and 26, but with a changed bishop's placement.} (7. c3 {is examined in Line 28.}) (7. dxc5 {is the subject of Lines 29 to 35.}) (7. Be2 d6 {transposes to the previous line.}) 7... d6 (7... c4 $5 8. Be2 d6) 8. exd6 (8. O-O c4 $5 9. Be2 dxe5 (9... Be7 10. b3 $5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 $14) 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bc5 {This is the difference! The bishop immediately defends the important square on d4.} 12. b3 Be6 13. Bb2 O-O 14. Bd4 Qb6 15. Bxc5 Qxc5 $11 {Without a blockade on d4, White does not have an advantage.}) 10... Be7 11. b3 Be6 12. Be3 O-O 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qc7 15. f4 Bf5 16. g4 Be4 17. Bf3 Rad8 18. c3 Bc5 19. b4 Bb6 $11) 8... c4 {The bishop on d3 is asking for this!} ({This does not mean that} 8... Bxd6 {was wrong.} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $1 {Maintain9ing the control on d4 and e3.} (11... Bxe7 12. Be3 Bg4 13. Be2 $14) 12. O-O Be6 13. Ng5 Nb4 14. Rd1 Nxd3 15. Rxd3 Bf5 16. Rxd5 Rhd8 17. Re5+ Kf6 18. Nf3 Rd1+ 19. Re1 Rxe1+ 20. Nxe1 g5 $5 $44) 9. Qe2+ (9. Be2 Bxd6 10. O-O O-O $11 11. b3 $6 c3 $1 {A familiar picture.} 12. Qd3 Nb4 13. Qxc3 Bf5 14. Bd3 Nxd3 15. cxd3 Bg4 16. Ne5 Bh5 { 
[%cal Gf7f6]} 17. h3 f6 18. Ng4 Bxg4 19. hxg4 f5 20. gxf5 Qh4 21. f4 Rxf5 $17)
9... Be6 10. Bf5 Qxd6 $11 * 

