1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. c3 $5 { This move has more venom than it may seem to. The first idea that comes to mind is that White prepares a safe square on d3 for the bishop and takes d4 under control if the game reaches an Isolani structure. There is a third element, though. By defending against a check on a5, White enables Bb5.} cxd4 { This seems to be the best chance for reaching a position with chances for both sides.} ({Played in the vast majority of the games,} 7... d6 {runs into} 8. Bb5 $1 {which causes some problems.} (8. exd6 Bxd6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Re8 $11) 8... Be7 $1 {Black should not delay his kingside development.} (8... a6 {delays the king's evacuation from the centre for too long.} 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. O-O Be7 11. Qa4 Bd7 12. exd6 Bxd6 13. Re1+ Be7 14. dxc5 O-O 15. Be3 $18) ( 8... cxd4 $6 9. Qxd4 $1 $16) 9. exd6 (9. O-O O-O 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Qd3 $5 {could be a slightly improved version of the Isolani structure from White's point of view.}) 9... Bxd6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 (11... Bxe7 12. Ne5 $16) 12. dxc5 Bxc5 {Black's position is a bit uncomfortable but not necessarily worse. It looks like a one-sided affair to me, though, explaining my main line choice.} 13. Bf4 a6 14. Ba4 Be6 15. O-O Rhd8 16. Rfe1 h6 17. Rad1 Rac8 18. Be3 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 {Adhiban,B (2666) -Kantans,T (2469) Titled Tuesday intern op 1st Nov 10am blitz 2016 (2) 1-0} d4 $5 20. cxd4 Kf8 $44 21. a3 Na5) 8. Nxd4 $1 {To get the control on d4, White sacrifices a pawn and Black should refrain from accepting it!} (8. cxd4 d6 {is just equal.} 9. Be2 (9. Bb5 Qa5+) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 (10. Nxe5 Bd6 11. Nxc6 (11. O-O O-O 12. Bf4 Qf6 $11) 11... bxc6 12. O-O O-O 13. Be3 a5 14. Qd2 (14. Qc2 Qf6 15. Rac1 Bd7 $15) 14... Bd7 15. Bf4 Bxf4 16. Qxf4 Qb8 17. Qc1 (17. Qd2 Qb4 18. Rfd1 Rfb8 19. Rab1 Qxd2 20. Rxd2 Rb4) 17... Qb6 18. Rd1 Rfe8 19. Bd3 a4 $11) 10... Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. Qf4 (14. Rfd1 Nxe5 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Rxd5 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Rb8 18. a3 b6 19. Rad1 Be6 20. R5d3 Kf8 21. h3 Ke7 22. Bd5 Red8 23. Bxe6 Rxd3 24. Rxd3 Kxe6 25. Re3+ Kd7 {Abdelaal,I (1903) -Deschamps,M (1633) Laval op 2019 (5) 1/2-1/2}) 14... Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. Nxf7 Rxe2 18. Nd6 Rxb2 19. Rfe1 Bd7 20. Re7 Rd8 21. Rae1 Bc6 22. Nf5 Rd7 $11) 8... d6 (8... Nxe5 $2 9. Bf4 d6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qb3 $16 {Korneev,O (2649) -Recuero Guerra,D (2315) Dos Hermanas op 5th 2006 (8) 1-0 White retrieves the pawn on d5 and retains the better structure.}) 9. Bb5 {A familiar issue.} (9. exd6 Bxd6 { is a slightly different Isolani position than those we had seen earlier. The main difference is that White's knight has blocked the d5-pawn already, which abstractly favours White, but objectively does not ensure an advantage.} 10. Be2 (10. Bb5 {fails to prevent} O-O $11 {After failing to fulfill his mission, the bishop does not stand well on b5.} 11. Nxc6 Qe8+ $1 12. Ne7+ Qxe7+ 13. Qe2 Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 $15) 10... O-O 11. O-O Re8 ({The simplest way to equality may be fighting against the blockade with} 11... Bc5 $5 12. Be3 Qb6 $11) 12. Bf3 { White has stabilised the position and can hope that after a few more moves the pawn on d5 will be hanging.} Qf6 13. Be3 {White has stabilised the position and can hope that after a few more moves the pawn on d5 will be hanging.} (13. Bxd5 Bxh2+ 14. Kxh2 Qe5+ $11) (13. h3 $2 Qe5 $19) (13. g3 Bh3 14. Bg2 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Qxd4 17. cxd4 Re2 $15) 13... Bd7 $5 $146 (13... Be6 $2 { With queens on board, it does not make sense to weaken the kingside light squares.} 14. Nxe6 fxe6 15. g3 $16 {Iordachescu,V (2589) -Le,T (2501) Titled Tuesday intern op 25th Aug blitz 2020 (6) 1/2-1/2}) 14. Re1 (14. Kh1 { threatening Bxd5 may run into} Rxe3 $5 15. fxe3 Qh6 16. g3 Bxg3 $44) 14... Re7 (14... Rad8 $6 15. Qd2 h6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Bxa7 $16) (14... Be5 15. Qb3 $14) 15. Qd2 (15. Qb3 $6 {does not work as long the e5-square ios available:} Na5 $1 16. Qxd5 $2 Re5 $19) (15. Nb5 Ne5 16. Be2 Bxb5 17. Bxb5 a6 18. Be2 Nc4 $11) 15... Rae8 16. Rad1 (16. Kh1 Nxd4 $11 {forces White to re-capture with the pawn now or on the next move, since} 17. Bxd4 $2 {allows} Qf4 $1 $19) 16... h6 17. Nc2 (17. Nb5 Ne5 $17) (17. Nb3 Qh4 18. h3 (18. g3 Ne5 19. Bxd5 Qh5 $15) 18... Ne5 19. Bxd5 Bxh3 20. gxh3 Qxh3 21. Bf4 Nf3+ 22. Bxf3 Bxf4 {This would not work with the knight on c2, since in that case the rook on e1 would be defended.} 23. Rxe7 Bh2+ 24. Kh1 Bg3+ $11) 17... Bf5 $5 18. Bxd5 Rd8 19. Qe2 Qg6 20. Bxc6 (20. Nd4 Bxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Rxd5 $11) 20... bxc6 21. Nd4 Bh3 22. Qf1 Rde8 $44) 9... Bd7 10. exd6 (10. Nf3 $5 a6 11. Ba4 Nxe5 {The simplest.} (11... dxe5 $5 $146 12. Qxd5 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Nxe5 Bd5 17. Be3 Bd6 18. Nf3 Bc7 19. b3 f6 20. Rad1 Ba5 21. c4 Be4) 12. Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. O-O (13. Qxd5 Qc6 14. Qxc6+ bxc6 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Be3 O-O-O 17. Ke2 Bd6 18. Rhd1 Bc7 $11 {Brkic,A (2602) -Jankovic,A (2534) CRO-ch Opatija 2015 (9) 1/2-1/2 }) 13... Be7 14. Qxd5 Qc6 15. Qxc6+ bxc6 16. Nxe5 dxe5 17. Be3 O-O-O {Gunther, C (2138) -Altea,E (1534) IECG WC.2004.P.00001 email 2001 1/2-1/2}) (10. e6 $6 fxe6 $15 11. Bxc6 $6 bxc6 $19 12. O-O e5 13. Re1 Be7 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Qf3 Bf6 ( 15... Bh4 $1 {threatening ...Rf8.} 16. Bh6 Qf6 $19) 16. Bh6 {Sliwicki,D (2140) -Khripachenko,A (2201) Titled Tuesday intern op 13th Sep Late blitz 2022 (2) 1-0} Kf7 17. Ne2 Re8 $17) 10... Bxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Be3 (12. Nf3 {allows} Bg4 {solving all Black's problems.} 13. h3 Bh5 14. Be2 Bc5 15. Bg5 Qd6 16. Qd2 { Zhigalko,A (2549) -Aukhatov,R (2119) Samara Polugaevsky Memorial 9th 2019 (3) 1/2-1/2} Rfe8 17. Rae1 Re4 $11) (12. Nb3 a6 13. Be2 Qc7 14. h3 Rfe8 15. Re1 Re5 (15... h6 $5 {Preparing ...Rad8.} 16. Qxd5 Rad8 17. Kh1 Bc8 $44) 16. Be3 (16. Bf4 $2 Rxe2 $1 $19) 16... Rae8 17. Bd3 Qc8 $5 {Maintaining the fluency of Black's play.} (17... g6 {A high-level game proved that Black can reach a draw by doing nothing, too.} 18. Qd2 Qd8 19. Nd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Qe8 23. Qd2 Be5 24. Be3 Qe6 $11 {Giri,A (2782) -Kovalev,V (2655) Dortmund 46th 2018 (3) 0-1}) 18. Nd4 (18. Qd2 Bxh3 $1 $17) (18. Qf3 R8e6 $15) 18... Bb8 $5 (18... Nxd4 19. cxd4 R5e7 $11) 19. Qd2 Qc7 20. Nf3 R5e7 21. Bg5 Re4 $1 {[%cal Gc6e5] Threatening ...Ne5.} 22. Kf1 (22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Bf4 { The only defence.} Qxf4 24. Qxd7 Rd8 25. Qg4 Qxg4 26. hxg4 exf3 27. gxf3 Kf8 $17) 22... Qc8 23. Bxe4 (23. Kg1 Bxh3 $1 $40) 23... dxe4 24. Ng1 (24. Nd4 Bxh3 25. Nxc6 Bxg2+ 26. Kxg2 Qg4+ $11) 24... Ne5 25. Rxe4 Bb5+ 26. Ne2 Qc6 27. Re3 Ba7 28. a4 Bc4 29. Rg3 Ng4 30. Rxg4 Bxe2+ 31. Kg1 Bxg4 32. hxg4 h6 33. Bh4 Re4 34. Qd1 Qe6 $11) 12... Re8 ({The simplifications starting with} 12... Nxd4 $5 { also ensure the equality.} 13. Bxd7 Qxd7 14. Qxd4 b6 $1 {Freeing the rook from the task of defending a7 and preparing ...Bc5.} 15. Rad1 Rad8 16. Bg5 f6 17. Bc1 Bc5 18. Qd3 a5 $11) 13. Bd3 (13. Re1 Qf6 (13... Nxd4 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Qxd4 b6 16. Rad1 Rad8 $11) 14. Qb3 Rad8 (14... a6 15. Bf1 Ne5 {Tsaruk,M (2324) -Le, T (2514) Titled Tuesday intern op 22nd June blitz 2021 (11) 0-1} 16. Qxd5 $1 Ng4 17. h3 Nxe3 18. Rxe3 Rxe3 19. fxe3 $16) 15. Rad1 a6 16. Bf1 Ne5 17. Qxb7 ( 17. Qxd5 Ng4 $15 18. h3 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Bg4 $5 {threatening ...Bh2!+}) 17... Ng4 18. Nf3 Rxe3 19. fxe3 (19. Rxe3 $2 Bxh2+ $1 $19 {wins}) 19... Bxh2+ $1 { Nevertheless!} 20. Nxh2 Qf2+ 21. Kh1 Qh4 22. Qc7 Rc8 23. Qf4 g5 24. Qd6 Rc6 25. Qb8+ Rc8 $11 {with a draw by move repetition.}) 13... Ne5 14. Be2 Nc4 15. Bc1 Qf6 16. Bf3 {Zufic,M (2366) -Le,T (2501) Titled Tuesday intern op 12th May blitz 2020 (1) 0-1} Qe5 17. g3 Bh3 18. Bg2 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qe4+ $11 * 

