{[%evp 0,39,20,20,60,38,75,75,59,68,62,53,53,53,53,53,53,56,66,60,60,60,61,52, 44,44,249,249,249,55,55,55,55,55,60,55,55,14,102,55,55,43]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5 {Whenever I see this position I am invaded by old emotions from my childhood and early teenage. I used to be a 1.e4 player then and knew that this line was supposed to be good or close to winning for White. I had read the theory, and I remembered the convincing evaluation of the Opening Encyclopaedia, but the simple thought that I could ever get this position with white gave me the shivers. Was it really safe to develop the queen so early and advance with the king before even completing my queenside's development? Now I know that this is possible, indeed, but also that the old theory did not do justice to Black.} Qb6 {Abstractly speaking, this is the adventurous alternative. Black picks up the gauntlet by attacking f2. However, analysis suggests that this is the safe continuation, leading almost by force to an ending that is only symbolically better for White.} (8... d6 {is examined in Lines 32 to 35.}) 9. Bc4 $1 { If he wants to fight for an advantage, White has to make a series of "only moves".} (9. Qd2 d6 $11 10. exd6 $2 O-O 11. Bd3 Re8+ 12. Kf1 Nb4 $17) (9. Bd3 Nb4 (9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 d6 11. exd6 Be6 {Diez del Corral,J (2480) -Marovic,D  (2445) Costa del Sol-21 1981 (11) 0-1}) 10. Qe4 Nxd3+ 11. cxd3 Bxf2+ 12. Kf1 Bc5 13. d4 Be7 14. d5 Bc5 15. d6 {Clarke,B (2411) -Zulfic,F (2179) Gold Coast op 2018 (8) 1/2-1/2} Qc6 16. Qd3 (16. Qxc6 bxc6 17. Bg5 f6 18. exf6 gxf6 19. Bxf6 O-O $17) 16... b6 $15) 9... Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 $1 {The king should keep contact with the bishop and leave the f1-square available for the rook. Mathematically, this means that it has to advance, the thing that scared me many decades ago. In all the lines examined below, we get the clear feeling that White is walking on a tightrope, many times balancing between an advantage and a loss.} (10. Kf1 O-O $11 11. Qb5 (11. Ng5 $2 Bh4 12. Ne4 d6 $19 {Lang,M-Kirov,N (2460) St Ingbert op 1989 (7) 1/2-1/2}) (11. Qe4 d5 12. exd6 Bd7 13. Ng5 g6 14. Qf4 Bd4 15. Qh4 h5 16. c3 {Noorda,H-Jowett,P a1-h8 Winners 17 email 2001 0-1} Qc5 17. Bd3 Bg7 $19) 11... d5 12. exd6 (12. Qxb6 Bxb6 13. Bxd5 Rd8 14. c4 Be6 $17 {Codenotti,M (2175) -Bossi,A (2012) Livigno op 2010 (4) 0-1} 15. Bxe6 Rd1+ 16. Ne1 fxe6 17. Ke2 Rad8 $19) 12... Re8 13. Bf4 Be6 14. Qxb6 Bxb6 15. Bxe6 Rxe6) (10. Kd1 O-O $11 11. a4 $5 $146 {Apparently, the only way out of trouble.} (11. Ng5 Qd4+ 12. Qxd4 Bxd4 $17) (11. c3 d6 12. exd6 Be6 13. Qd3 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Rad8 15. Kc2 Rxd6 16. Bf4 Rc8 $1 $19 {Kuijpers,F-Minic,D WchT Students 09th Group2 1962 (4.2) 0-1}) (11. Rf1 $2 d6 12. exd6 Be6 13. Qe4 Bxc4 14. Qxc4 Rad8 15. Bf4 Be3 16. Bg3 Qxb2 17. Ke2 Rfe8 $19) (11. Qb5 { Feher,G (2400) -Varlamov,V (2290) Budapest Spring op 10th 1994 (8) 1/2-1/2} d5 $1 12. exd6 Qd8 $1 13. Bf4 Qf6 14. g3 Bg4 $19) (11. Qe4 d5 $1 12. exd6 g6 $19) ({Without the intermediate a2-a4 and ...a7-a5,} 11. b3 {does not work.} d6 12. exd6 Be6 13. Qb5 Qd8 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. c3 Qxd6+ 16. Kc2 Rac8 17. Kb2 Bc5 $1 $17 {In a similar position from the main line, Black does not have the threat ... Ba3+, yielding White a tempo for organising his defence.}) 11... a5 12. b3 d6 13. exd6 Be6 14. Qb5 Qd8 15. Bxe6 Qxd6+ (15... fxe6 16. c3 Qxd6+ 17. Kc2 Rac8 18. Kb2 $11) 16. Bd5 Rad8 17. Bd2 (17. c4 Qg6 $36) 17... Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Rxd5 $11 ) 10... O-O 11. Rf1 (11. Ng5 $2 d6 12. Nxf7 (12. Qe4 Bf5 $1 {Arribas Lopez,A  (2379) -Alonso Rosell,A (2442) ESP-chT Autonomicas 4th 2009 (6) 1/2-1/2}) 12... Be6 $5 $19 {In both lines, the possible knight fork on d4 dooms White.}) (11. Rd1 d6 12. exd6 Be6 13. Qb5 Nd4+ 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Kf3 $1 {The only saving move.} (15. Qxb6 Bxc4+ $19 {Musial,M-Castro,S BRA TC1-C-0574 corr 1996 (1) 1/ 2-1/2}) (15. Bf4 Rfc8 $1 16. Bd3 Rxc2+ $1 17. Ke1 Bc3+ $1 18. Bd2 Qg1+ 19. Bf1 Bc4 {Boukal,P-Simunek,J EU-ch M corr 1975 0-1}) (15. Kf1 a6 $1 16. Qb3 Qc5 $19) 15... Bxc4 16. Qxc4 Bg1 17. Kg3 Rae8 {Threatening ...Re3+ or ...Re6.} 18. Kh3 $1 Re5 19. Rd5 Re1 20. Rd3 h5 21. Qd5 $1 Bf2 22. Rf3 Qb4 23. c4 $1 Qc5 24. Rf5 Qxd5 25. Rxd5 f6 26. g3 Kf7 {The game is about level, but enormously interesting still.} 27. b4 g5 28. d7 Rd8 29. Kg2 Bb6 30. c5 Bc7 31. Bf4 Rxa1 32. Bxc7 Rxa2+ 33. Kf3 Ke7 34. Bxd8+ Kxd8 35. Ke4 Rxh2 36. b5 Rc2 37. Kf5 h4 38. Kxf6 hxg3 39. Rxg5 {Ball,J-Hohlbein,M RR-19998 freechess.de 2016 1/2-1/2}) 11... Bc5 12. Ng5 {White finally reveals his secret idea. Black's development is not that great, either, so White tries to set up an attack.} (12. c3 Ne7 13. Qe4 d5 14. exd6 Qxd6 15. Ng5 $1 {Sarapu,O-Myagmarsuren,L Interzonal-07 1967  (18) 1-0} Bf5 16. Rxf5 Nxf5 17. Qxf5 Rae8+ 18. Kf3 g6 19. Qd3 (19. Qd5 Qf6+ 20. Bf4 Re3+ {Houweling,B (1986) -Peretz,M (2142) Wch Seniors 65 30th 2022 (2) 0-1} ) 19... Qf6+ 20. Kg4 Re5 21. Bf4 h5+ 22. Kh3 Rxg5 23. Bxg5 Qxg5 24. g3 $11 { Black's position remains more pleasant, but the objective evaluation is close to equality.}) (12. Qe4 d5 $1 13. Bxd5 (13. exd6 Bd7 14. Kd1 Rae8 15. Qh4 h6 $19) 13... Be6 14. Ng5 Nd4+ 15. Ke1 (15. Kd1 {Bialas,W-Weiss,H EU-chT 03th Group2 1963 (1.1) 0-1} Nf5 16. Rxf5 Bxd5 $19) 15... g6 16. Bxe6 Nxe6 17. Nxe6 fxe6 $15) 12... Nxe5 $1 {Combining the defence with the attack.} ({Mamedyarov recently won against Karjakin with} 12... Nd4+ $6 {. I have not managed to see how it can be playable.} 13. Kd1 $1 {Of course, White still has to be careful.} (13. Kd3 $6 Ne6 14. Ne4 d6 15. exd6 Bd7 16. c3 Bc6 17. Qf5 {Johannessen, S-Rivera,D Olympiad-15 Final C 1962 (7) 1-0} Rae8 $17) 13... Ne6 14. Ne4 d6 { Black has to continue developing.} 15. exd6 Rd8 (15... Bd7 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. Be3 Be6 18. Qxc5 Qxc5 19. Bxc5 Bxc4 {leads to an ending where Black may be able to hold the blockade, but this is not the kind of position we are heading for when playing adventurous variations.}) 16. Bd3 $1 {White does not have to forget why he entered this adventure: it was for his attacking chances!} (16. Bf4 Nxf4 17. Qxf7+ Kh8 18. Qxf4 Bxd6 19. Nxd6 Rxd6+ 20. Kc1 Rf6 21. Qe5 Rxf1+ 22. Bxf1 Qh6+ 23. Kb1 Bd7 $11 24. a3 Re8 25. Qg3 Bf5 $44 {Krattenmacher, W-Longwitz,A FRG-ch M corr 1985 0-1}) ({The aforementioned game went} 16. c3 $2 {This only looks safe. In fact, it offers Black an attacking tempo on a golden plate.} Bxd6 17. Kc2 Bf4 18. Qb5 Qxb5 19. Bxb5 Bxh2 20. g3 b6 21. Bc4 b5 22. Bxb5 Bb7 23. Bd3 Rd7 $19 {Karjakin,S (2757) -Mamedyarov,S (2770) Carlsen Inv Prelim rapid 2021 (12) 0-1}) (16. Qh5 Bxd6 17. Bd3 $1 {is the other possible move order.}) 16... Bxd6 17. Qh5 $1 Bc7 $5 ({The most frequent move is} 17... f5 {but I did not find the point after} 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Qxf5 $16) 18. Qxf7+ ( 18. Nf6+ gxf6 19. Qxh7+ Kf8 20. Qh8+ Ke7 21. Qxf6+ Kd7 22. Qxf7+ Kc6 23. Qf3+ Kd6 24. c3 Qc5 25. Be3 Qd5 $11 {Lindhom,E (2257) -Andreassen,E (2325) NOR-ch Seniors email 2005 1/2-1/2}) (18. Bd2 $5 Rd7 19. Kc1 $16) 18... Kh8 {The position remains sharp, but with a bit of accuracy, White can prove an advantage.} 19. a4 $3 {Notably, the only move maintaining White's advantage. White intends to prepare Bd2 and for that reason, he needs to clear the a2-square for the king. He also needs to prevent a later ...Ba4. Does it make sense to you?!} (19. Qh5 $6 Rxd3+ $1 20. cxd3 Bd7 $44) (19. Nf6 $5 Qc5 $1 20. Ne8 Bd7 $1 21. Nxc7 Nxc7 22. Bd2 Rac8 $44) (19. Bd2 {is premature due to} Nf4 $3 20. Bxf4 Bg4+ 21. Kc1 Rd7 22. Qb3 Bxf4+ 23. Kb1 {The bishop is taboo on account of ...Qe3+.} Bxh2 $11) (19. a3 Bd7 20. Bd2 $2 {allows} Ba4 $3 $19) 19... Bd7 20. Bd2 Bc6 $5 $146 ({ALl the games played so far continued with}  20... Nc5 21. Nxc5 Qxc5 {when after for instance} 22. Kc1 {Black is simply a pawn down and worse.}) (20... Nf4 $2 {does not work anymore:} 21. Bxf4 Bg4+ 22. Kc1 Rd7 23. Bxc7 $1 Qe3+ 24. Kb1 Rxf7 25. Rxf7 $18 {and there is no mate on e1. }) 21. Qxe6 (21. Ng5 Nxg5 22. Bxg5 Rxd3+ 23. cxd3 Rg8 24. Kc2 Be5 25. Qb3 Qd4 $44) (21. Kc1 Bxe4 22. Bxe4 Rf8 $19) (21. a5 $1 $18) 21... Rxd3 22. Kc1 $1 Rxd2 23. Nxd2 Bxg2 24. Qxb6 axb6 25. Rf2 Bc6 $16 {I have made this brief survey for curious researchers. Unfortunately, I did not find anything convincing for Black.}) 13. Qxe5 {This leads to complicated play with chances for both sides.} (13. Nxf7 $1 {is examined in Line 31.}) 13... d5 $1 {Of course.} 14. Qxd5 (14. Bxd5 Bg4+ 15. Kd3 (15. Ke1 $2 Rae8 $1 16. Bxf7+ Kh8 {White has to take on e8 with the queen and hope to prolong the fight, since} 17. Bxe8 $6 {runs into} Qa5+ 18. c3 Bf2+ $1 19. Rxf2 Qxe5+ 20. Kf1 Qe2+ {Tokarczyk,T (2153) -Tomczak,J (2447) Police Gniota Memorial 24th 2009 (6) 0-1}) (15. Kd2 Rae8 {forces} 16. Nxf7 Rxe5 17. Nh6+ Kh8 18. Rxf8+ Bxf8 19. Nf7+ Kg8 20. Nh6+ {with a draw by perpetual.}) 15... Rfe8 16. Nxf7 (16. Bxf7+ Kh8 17. Bxe8 Rd8+ {Voge,A (2192) -Huettemann,K (2249) Ruhrgebiet VL1 0910 2009 (5.4) 0-1}) 16... Rxe5 17. Nh6+ Kh8 18. Nf7+ {once again drawn.}) 14... Bg4+ 15. Rf3 $1 {White needs to maintain the pressure on f7 at any cost.} (15. Nf3 Rad8 $19) 15... Rad8 $1 ( 15... Rae8+ $2 16. Kf1 $18) 16. Qe4 (16. Qe5 Qc6 $19) 16... Bxf3+ (16... Rde8 $2 17. Bxf7+ $1) 17. gxf3 (17. Kxf3 g6 18. Qh4 Qf6+ 19. Bf4 h5 20. Bb3 Rd4 21. Re1 Kg7 22. Bxf7 Be7 23. Rxe7 Qxe7 24. Ne6+ Kxf7 25. Qxe7+ Kxe7 26. Nxd4 g5 27. Ne2 gxf4 28. Nxf4 $15 {Brayman,N (1699) -Korostenski,F (1662) SC-2012-0-00158 1/2-1/2 with chances to reach a draw with white, but not more, of course.}) 17... Qh6 18. Qe5 $1 {The only good way of defending h2.} (18. Bf4 $2 Rd4 $19) 18... Qg6 19. Qe4 (19. Bb3 $2 Qa6+ 20. Ke1 Qa5+ 21. Ke2 h6 22. Ne4 Rfe8 23. Qf5 Qb5+ 24. c4 Qc6 25. Kf1 Rxe4 26. Qxe4 Qd7 27. Kg2 Re8 28. Qc2 Re1 $19) 19... Qh6 20. Qe5 {Maur,R (1852) -Korostenski,F (1678) SD-2011-0-00116 1/2-1/2} Qg6 21. Qe4 {with a possible repetition. In all these lines, the fun is all Black's, even though the position is objectively equal.} * 

