1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5 Qb6 9. Bc4 Bxf2+ 10. Ke2 O-O 11. Rf1 Bc5 12. Ng5 Nxe5 13. Nxf7 $1 { This is the most promising continuation, requiring certain accuracy from Black. } Nxf7 14. Rxf7 Qe6+ $1 15. Qxe6 dxe6 16. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {The long forced variation has resulted in an ending that remains more pleasant for White. He has the better structure and the black king is a bit exposed. Thorough analysis suggests that Black should maintain the equality with a bit of accuracy or/and knowledge.} 17. Bg5 (17. Bf4 Bd7 18. Rf1 Ke7 19. Bd3 (19. Bg5+ Ke8 20. Bd3 Be7 {transposes below.}) 19... Bc6 $1 (19... h6 20. Be5 $14 Bd6 $6 21. Bxd6+ Kxd6 22. Rf7 $16) 20. Bg5+ Ke8 21. Bxh7 Bxg2 22. Rf4 (22. Bg6+ { mainly helps the king to reach a safer area.} Kd7 23. Rf7+ Kc6 24. Rxg7 Bd4 25. Re7 Rg8 26. Bf6 $1 {The only available resource.} Rxg6 27. Bxd4 Be4 28. Bxa7 Bxc2 29. Bf2 Be4 30. Bg3 Kc5 {due to his centralised position, Black has adequate compensation for the pawn.}) 22... Bd5 (22... Kd7 {Stojanovic,A (2258) -Nonkovic,B (2052) SRB-ch (Women) 2013 (2) 1/2-1/2} 23. Rf7+ Kc6 24. Rxg7 Bd4 25. Re7 Bxb2 26. Rxe6+ Kd5 27. Re7 $14) 23. Bg6+ (23. c4 e5 $11) 23... Kd7 24. Rf7+ Kc6 25. Kd3 (25. Rxg7 Bd4 26. Re7 Rg8 27. Be8+ Kb6) 25... Rf8 26. c4 (26. Rxg7 Rf3+ 27. Ke2 Rf2+ 28. Ke1 Rxh2 $11) 26... Bg2 27. Rxg7 Rf3+ 28. Kd2 Rf2+ 29. Ke1 {The position is equal anyway, but if anything, Black can force a draw by perpetual with} Rf1+ $5 $11) (17. Bd2 Bd7 18. Rf1+ Ke7 19. Bd3 (19. Bg5+ Ke8 {transposes to the main line.}) 19... h6 $11 20. Bc3 Bd6 $1 {This is the difference with respect to the line with 17.Bf4: the white bishop does not occupy the central e5-square.} 21. Bxg7 (21. g3 e5 $11) 21... Bxh2 22. Bxh6 ( 22. Rf6 Be5 23. Rg6 Bxg7 24. Rxg7+ Kd6 25. g4 Rf8 26. Rg6 Bc6 $11) 22... Rg8 23. Kf2 Bc6 $11) 17... Bd7 18. Rf1+ Ke8 19. Bd3 Be7 20. Bd2 $1 {The best square for the bishop. It stays ready to occupy the long diagonal and leaves the e3-square available for the rook.} (20. h4 Rc8 $1 $11 21. Bxh7 $6 Bb5+ 22. c4 (22. Bd3 $2 Rxc2+ 23. Ke3 Bxg5+ 24. hxg5 Bxd3 25. Kxd3 Rxg2 $19) 22... Rxc4 $15) (20. Be3 g6 $11) 20... g6 21. Rf3 e5 22. Re3 {Now is when we understand the latter aspect mentioned above. WHite needs to maintain his light initiative since otherwise, Black would reach full equality.} Bg4+ 23. Ke1 Bh4+ $1 $146 {This move forces White to either weaken his second rank or worsen the king's placement.} (23... Bf6 24. Be4 Rc8 25. Ra3 Bf5 26. Bxb7 Rxc2 {With the king on f1, the bishop would not be defended.} 27. Rxa7 e4 28. Kd1 e3 29. Bxe3 Rxb2 30. Bd5 $16 {The point is that Black does not have targets along the second rank. This is why he needs to provoke g2-g3.}) 24. g3 (24. Kf1 Bf6 25. h3 ({In the event of} 25. Be4 {, the simplest is} Rd8 $1 {attacking the already undefended bishop.} 26. Bc3 b6 $11) 25... Bd7 26. Bc3 Kf7 27. Bxe5 Re8 28. Bc4+ (28. Bf4 Bxb2 $11) 28... Be6 29. Bb5 (29. Bxf6 $2 Bxc4+ $19) 29... Bd7 $1 30. Bxd7 Rxe5 31. Rb3 {The rook is stuck to the defence of the pawn on b2 for a while. In the meantime, Black will be able to organise his counterplay against the slightly exposed white king.} b6 32. Bc6 h5 (32... Bh4 33. g3 Be7 34. Rd3 Bc5 35. Rd7+ Re7 36. Rd2 Re3 37. Kg2 Ke6 $11) 33. Kf2 Kg7 34. Kf3 Re1 35. Rb4 Be7 36. Rc4 a5 37. Be4 Bc5 38. Bd3 Re3+ 39. Kf4 Re7 40. Be4 Kf6 41. a3 Rd7 42. b4 g5+ 43. Kf3 axb4 {Morozov,D (2381) -Kmiecik,K (2219) W-ch32 prel02 email 2008 1/2-1/2} 44. axb4 Rd4 $11) 24... Bf6 25. Be4 (25. Bc3 Kf7 26. Bxe5 Re8 27. Bc4+ Be6 28. Bxf6 (28. Bb5 Bd7 29. Bxd7 Rxe5 $11) 28... Bxc4 29. Be5 Bxa2 30. b3 a5 31. Kd2 a4 32. bxa4 Rd8+ 33. Kc3 Bd5 $11) 25... Rc8 26. Ra3 Bf5 27. Bxb7 (27. Bxf5 gxf5 28. Rxa7 Rxc2 29. Rxb7 e4 $11) 27... Rxc2 28. Rxa7 e4 29. Kd1 e3 30. Bxe3 Rxb2 {With the pawn on g3, White cannot parry both ...Rxh2 and ...Be6.} 31. h4 Be6 32. a4 Bb3+ 33. Ke1 Bc3+ 34. Kf1 Bxa4 $5 $11 {What started as an adventure, ended as a technical thing. Objectively, Black can be happy with the final result, though.} * 

