{[%evp 0,52,19,28,42,60,65,67,67,67,67,64,57,62,74,71,66,66,68,66,93,76,64,36, 51,42,42,41,38,24,31,23,46,4,9,-33,-56,0,0,0,-58,-179,-57,-237,-275,-293,-295, -321,-324,-363,-298,-361,-275,-275,-293]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Qxd5 d6 $5 {Known since a game played in 1959 and mentioned below, this move leads to a completely different type of position. Black admits playing with a pawn less to get an advance in development. It starts like a classical things, but playing with a material disadvantage is likely to turn into an adventure later. Black's main threats are the obvious ...Be6 and the more subtle ...Qa5+, when the threat ...Bxf2+ forces White to play Qd2. After the queen exchange, Black retrieves the pawn with ...dxe5, leading to equality.} 9. exd6 (9. Bc4 Be6 10. Qd3 Nb4 11. Qe2 Bxc4 12. Qxc4 Rc8 13. Qb5+ (13. Ke2 O-O 14. c3 Nc6 15. exd6 Re8+ 16. Be3 Qxd6) 13... Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7 15. Kd1 Rhe8 $11) 9... Qb6 10. Qe4+ {Hurrying with the queen to h4 to defend on f2.} (10. Bc4 Bxf2+ 11. Kf1 O-O {does not promise much.} 12. Qb5 ({The aforementioned game went} 12. Qe4 $2 Bd7 13. Bg5 Bc5 14. Bd3 g6 15. Bf6 Nb4 16. Qh4 {Tal,M-Gipslis,A Riga International 1959 (2) 1/2-1/2 } h5 $19) 12... Re8 (12... Be6 13. Qxb6 Bxb6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Ke2 Rad8 16. Rd1 e5 17. Be3 Bxe3 18. Kxe3 Rf6 19. a3 Rfxd6 20. Rxd6 Rxd6 {Socko,B (2617) -Kantans,T (2447) EU-ch rapid Wroclaw 2014 (10) 0-1} 21. Rf1 $16) 13. Bf4 Be6 14. Qxb6 Bxb6 15. Bxe6 Rxe6 16. Re1 Rae8 17. c3 f6 18. h4 Kf7 19. Rh3 Bc5 $11) 10... Be6 11. Qh4 (11. Bc4 {once again offers Black good play.} Bxf2+ 12. Kf1 ( 12. Kd1 O-O-O 13. Bxe6+ fxe6 14. Qxe6+ $2 {It is better to play c2-c3 at once, with chances to maintain the equality.} Kb8 $17 15. c3 Nb4 $1 $19) (12. Ke2 O-O 13. Bxe6 Rae8 14. Ng5 Rxe6 15. Nxe6 Re8 16. Rf1 Rxe6 17. Qxe6 fxe6 18. Rxf2 Qb5+ 19. Ke1 Qe5+ 20. Kf1 Qxh2 $11) 12... O-O 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Kh8 15. d7 (15. Qb3 Rad8 16. Qxb6 Bxb6 $44) 15... Bc5 16. a4 (16. c3 Rf6 17. Qe8+ Rf8 18. Qe6 Rad8 $5 19. b4 Bxb4 $13 20. cxb4 $2 Qd4 $19) 16... Rad8 17. Ke1 Qc7 $19 {Gross,M (2212) -Boronowskis,P (2308) AUS-ch32 email 2008 0-1}) (11. d7+ Kxd7 $1 12. Be3 Bxe3 13. Rd1+ Kc7 14. Qxe3 Qxb2 15. Qf4+ Kc8 16. Bd3 Qb4+ 17. Qxb4 Nxb4 $11) 11... Bxd6 {Black has achieved his first goal: he is better developed and the white queen is awkwardly placed on h4. The fight is very much on.} 12. Bd3 {This prevents the immediate castle, but exposes the bishop.} (12. c3 {is examined in Line 33.}) (12. Be2 {will be the subject of Lines 34 and 35.}) 12... Nb4 {Just natural.} 13. O-O (13. Be4 {leads to interesting complications after} f5 $1 (13... Nxa2 $2 14. Be3 Qxb2 15. O-O $16 {Zezulkin,J (2354) -Sopur, L (2395) POL-chT 1st League 2005 (4.13) 1/2-1/2}) 14. Ng5 (14. Bd3 Nxd3+ 15. cxd3 Bb4+ 16. Kf1 {Razafindratsima,T (2199) -Makridis,D (1908) Wch FIDE Online U14 Europe qual rapid 2020 (3) 0-1} Rd8 17. Be3 Qb5 $44) 14... fxe4 15. Qxe4 (15. Nxe6 Nxc2+ 16. Kd1 Nxa1 $19) 15... O-O-O $1 16. Be3 (16. Qxe6+ Kb8 17. Be3 Nxc2+ $19) 16... Rde8 17. Bxb6 (17. Nxe6 Bc5 $3 18. Bxc5 Rxe6 19. Bxb6 Rxe4+ 20. Be3 Nxc2+ $17) 17... Bd5 18. Qxe8+ Rxe8+ 19. Be3 Nxc2+ 20. Ke2 Nxa1 21. Rxa1 Bxg2 22. f3 h6 23. Ne4 Be5 $11) 13... Nxd3 14. cxd3 O-O { Black has obvious compensation for the weak pawn on d3.} 15. Be3 (15. b3 Bf5 16. Be3 Qa6 17. d4 Rfe8 $11) 15... Qxb2 16. Rfb1 Qc3 $11 17. Bd4 $2 Qxd3 18. Bxg7 (18. Rxb7 Rfb8 $17) 18... Kxg7 19. Rd1 Qc3 20. Nd4 (20. Rac1 Qf6 21. Qxf6+ Kxf6 22. Rxd6 Rfd8 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 24. a4 b6 $17) 20... Qc5 21. Rd3 Be7 22. Qe4 Rad8 23. Rad1 Kh8 24. Qxb7 Bf6 25. Qe4 Rxd4 26. Rxd4 Bxd4 {Giri,A (2768) -Abdusattorov,N (2731) Norway Masters blitz 11th 2023 (8) 0-1} * 

