1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {We will have a brief look at the minor continuations on White's third move.} 3. d3 {Probably the most consistent of them all. White intends to play the so-called King's Indian attack.} (3. Bc4 $2 {has been played several times but White doe snot have any compensation after} Nxe4 $17) ({The same applies to} 3. d4 $2 Nxe4 4. d5 (4. Bd3 d5 $17) 4... d6 5. Bd3 Nf6 6. c4 g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 $15) (3. Qe2 {has similar ideas as 3.d3, but commits the queen earlier than necessary.} d6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. d3 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. c3 O-O 9. Nbd2 (9. a4 c4 $5 $11) 9... Nc6 10. Re1 Rc8 11. a3 Nd7 $5 $11) 3... d6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O g6 $5 (6... e6 {transposes to a system I recommended in my French Repertoire databases against 2.d3. The main line there goes} 7. c3 Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. a3 Ne5) 7. c3 (7. c4 Bg7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Nc6 10. Be3 e6 $5 (10... Rc8 $5) 11. d4 (11. Qd2 d5 $11) 11... e5 $5 12. dxe5 (12. d5 Nd4) 12... dxe5 13. Nd2 Nd4 $11 14. Nd5 $2 Nxd5 15. cxd5 f5 $17 {Pranav,V (2275) -Tiviakov,S (2584) Chennai op 10th 2018 (3) 0-1}) (7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Re1 Nc6 ({Anticipating} 8... O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {when the threat e4-e5 forces Black to make a slight concession, such as} Nfd7 {, which is entirely playable, though.}) 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. Qd1 (12. e5 $2 Bxg2 $1 {The intermediate capture on f6 is answered with ...Bxf6, so White has to play} 13. Kxg2 Nd7 $17) 12... Qc7 (12... Nd7 $5 13. Nd5 e6 14. Nf4 Qc7 $11) 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 e5 15. dxe6 Bxg2 16. e7 (16. Kxg2 fxe6 17. Rxe6 Qf7 $44) 16... Rfe8 17. Kxg2 Rxe7 18. Rxe7 Qxe7 19. c3 Re8 20. Be3 Qe4+ 21. Kg1 Be5 22. Qd2 h5 $11 {Baumgartner,H (2300) -Brandstaetter,F (2135) AUT-chT2M 9899 1998 (6) 1/2-1/2}) 7... Bg7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. d4 cxd4 11. cxd4 e6 $5 12. Nf1 (12. Nb1 b5 $11) (12. e5 dxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 14. Nc4 Qc7 $11) 12... Rc8 13. a3 Na5 14. N3d2 Nd7 15. Nf3 {Skomorokhina,E (1707) -Vlasova,E (1365) Nizhny Novgorod Region-ch (Women) 2014 (1) 1-0} b5 $5 $11 * 

